<TEI.2><teiHeader><fileDesc><titleStmt><title>Lyrical Ballads, an electronic edition</title><author>Samuel Taylor Coleridge and William Wordsworth </author><editor>Bruce Graver and Ronald Tetreault </editor></titleStmt><editionStmt><edition>Second edition, 1800</edition></editionStmt><publicationStmt><p>Not for publication or distribution, yet. </p></publicationStmt><sourceDesc><p>Edited from the copy of <emph>Lyrical Ballads</emph>, 1800, vol. 2,containing corrections for
the 1802 edition, in the Beinecke Library, Yale University, Summer, 1997</p></sourceDesc></fileDesc><encodingDesc><p>Encoded in TEI-conformant SGML by Bruce Graver and Ronald Tetreault,
with significant help from CETH, the STG, and others.</p></encodingDesc></teiHeader><text><group id="LB1800-2a"><text><body><pb><signed>This book is made <lb>up of proof <lb>sheets of the original edition; <lb>and the M.SS <lb>corrections are <lb>by the hand of <lb>the Authors <lb>Sister Dorothy <lb>Wordsworth & by the authour himself<lb>in Some <lb>cases  <lb>This book <lb>belonged to <lb>the Author's <lb>nephew, John <lb>Wordsworth, Son <lb>of Richard <lb>Wordsworth.  <lb>Chr W--  </signed><pb n="1"><signed id="ggw">John Wordsworth (only son of Richard <lb>Elder brother of W. W. the Poet and <lb>of J. W. Captn of the &lsquo;Earl of Abergavenny&rsquo; <lb>and of Chr. W. master of Trin. Coll. Cam., <lb>and of Dorothy W.) was Staff-Assistant <lb>surgeon to H. M. Forces in the Ionian <lb>Island, and died at Ambleside <lb>Aug.18, 1846, aged 31, unmarried. </signed><pb><lb><lb><lb><head><emph>HART-LEAP WELL. </emph><emph><note>Hart-Leap Well is a small spring of water, about five miles <lb>from Richmond in Yorkshire, and near the side of the road <lb>which leads from Richmond to Askrigg.  Its  name is derived <lb><add place="lmargin">&sol;C</add> from a remarkable <del>c</del>hace, the memory of which is preserved <lb>by the monuments spoken of in the second Part of the following <lb>Poem, which monuments do now exist as I have there described <lb>them.</note> </emph></head><div n="1" type="part"><lb><lb><lg n="1" type="stanza"><l n="1">The Knight had ridden down from Wensley moor</l><l n="2">With the slow motion of a summer&rsquo;s cloud;</l><l n="3">He turn&rsquo;d aside towards a Vassal&rsquo;s door,</l><l n="4">And, &ldquo;Bring another Horse!&rdquo; he cried aloud.</l></lg><lg n="2" type="stanza"><l n="5">&ldquo;Another Horse!&rdquo;&mdash;That shout the Vassal heard,</l><l n="6">And saddled his best steed, a comely Grey;</l><l n="7">Sir Walter mounted him; he was the third</l><l n="8">Which he had mounted on that glorious day.</l></lg><pb><milestone n="2" unit="page"><lb><lb><lg n="3" type="stanza"><l n="9">Joy sparkled in the prancing Courser&rsquo;s eyes;</l><l n="10"><add place="lmargin">&sol;H&sol;H</add> The <del>h</del>orse and <del>h</del>orsem<del>e</del>n are a happy pair;  <add place="rmargin">a&sol;</add></l><l n="11">But, though Sir Walter like a falcon flies,</l><l n="12">There is a doleful silence in the air.</l></lg><lg n="4" type="stanza"><l n="13">A rout this morning left Sir Walter&rsquo;s Hall,</l><l n="14">That as they gallop&rsquo;d made the echoes roar;</l><l n="15"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&sol;H</add> But <del>h</del>orse and <del>m</del>an are vanish&rsquo;d, one and all; <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">M&sol;</add></l><l n="16">Such race, I think, was never seen before.</l></lg><lg n="5" type="stanza"><l n="17">Sir Walter, restless as a veering wind,</l><l n="18"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&sol;D</add> Calls to the few tired <del>d</del>ogs that yet remain:</l><l n="19">Brach, Swift and Music, noblest of their kind,</l><l n="20">Follow, and <del>weary</del> up the ^<add place="aboveline" resp="ww">weary</add> mountain strain.</l></lg><lg n="6" type="stanza"><l n="21">The Knight halloo&rsquo;d, he chid and cheer&rsquo;d them on</l><l n="22">With suppliant gestures and upbraidings stern;</l><l n="23">But breath and eye-sight fail<del>,</del> and, one by one, <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">;&sol;</add></l><l n="24"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&sol;D</add> The <del>d</del>ogs are stretch&rsquo;d among the mountain fern.</l></lg><pb><milestone n="3" unit="page"><lb><lb><lg n="7" type="stanza"><l n="25">Where is the throng, the tumult of the^<del>chace</del>? <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">race?&sol;</add></l><l n="26">The bugles that so joyfully were blown?</l><l n="27"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">Chase</add> &mdash;This ^<del>race</del> it looks not like an earthly <del>race</del>; <del>c</del><add place="rmargin" resp="ww">Chase&sol;</add></l><l n="28">Sir Walter and the Hart are left alone.</l></lg><lg n="8" type="stanza"><l n="29">The poor Hart toils along the mountain side;</l><l n="30">I will not stop to tell how far he fled,</l><l n="31">Nor will I mention by what death he died;</l><l n="32">But now the Knight beholds him lying dead.</l></lg><lg n="9" type="stanza"><l n="33">Dismounting then, he lean&rsquo;d against a thorn;</l><l n="34">He had no follower, <del>d</del>og, nor <del>m</del>an, nor <del>b</del>oy: <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">D&sol;M,B</add></l><l n="35">He neither smack&rsquo;d his whip, nor blew his horn,</l><l n="36">But gaz&rsquo;d upon the spoil with silent joy.</l></lg><lg n="10" type="stanza"><l n="37">Close to the thorn on which Sir Walter lean&rsquo;d,</l><l n="38">Stood his dumb partner in this glorious act;</l><l n="39">Weak as a lamb the hour that it is yean&rsquo;d,</l><l n="40">And foaming like a mountain cataract.</l></lg><pb><milestone n="4" unit="page"><lb><lg n="11" type="stanza"><l n="41">Upon his side the Hart was lying stretch&rsquo;d:</l><l n="42">His nose half-touch&rsquo;d a spring beneath a hill,</l><l n="43">And with the last deep groan his breath had fetch&rsquo;d</l><l n="44">The waters of the spring were trembling still.</l></lg><lg n="12" type="stanza"><l n="45">And now, too happy for repose or rest,</l><l n="46"><add place="lmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">(^</add> Was never man in such a joyful case<del>,</del><add place="rmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">^) !</add></l><l n="47">Sir Walter walk&rsquo;d all round, north, south and west,</l><l n="48">And gaz&rsquo;d, and gaz&rsquo;d upon that darling place.</l></lg><lg n="13" type="stanza"><l n="49">And<del>turning</del><add place="belowline" rend="ink" resp="ww">^</add><add hand="dw" place="aboveline" rend="ink" resp="ww">climbing</add> up the hill<del>,</del> <add place="belowline" rend="ink" resp="ww">^</add><add place="inline" rend="ink" resp="ww">(</add> it was at least <add place="rmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">&mdash;&sol;</add></l><l n="50">Nine roods of sheer ascent<del>,</del><add place="inline" rend="ink " resp="ww">)^</add> Sir Walter found</l><l n="51">Three several <del>marks which with his hoofs the beast</del> <add hand="dw" place="aboveline" rend="ink" resp="ww">hoof-marks
which the 
hunted </add><add hand="dw" place="rmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">Beast</add></l><l n="52">Had left imprinted on the verdant ground.</l></lg><lg n="14" type="stanza"><l n="53">Sir Walter wiped his face, and cried, &ldquo;Till now</l><l n="54"><add place="lmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add>Such sight was never seen by living eyes:</l><l n="55"><add place="lmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add>Three leaps have borne him from this lofty brow,</l><l n="56"><add place="lmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add>Down to the very fountain where he lies.</l></lg><pb><milestone n="5" unit="page"><lb><lb><lg n="15" type="stanza"><l n="57"><add place="lmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add>I&rsquo;ll build a Pleasure-house upon this spot,</l><l n="58"><add place="lmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add>And a small Arbour, made for rural joy;</l><l n="59"><add place="lmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">&sol;T</add> <add place="lmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add>&rsquo;Twill be the <del>t</del>raveller&rsquo;s shed, the <del>p</del>ilgrim&rsquo;s cot, <add place="rmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">P&sol;</add></l><l n="60"><add place="lmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">&sol;D</add> <add place="lmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add>A place of love for <del>d</del>amsels that are coy.</l></lg><lg n="16" type="stanza"><l n="61"><add place="lmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add>A cunning Artist will I have to frame</l><l n="62"><add place="lmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add>A bason for that <del>f</del>ountain in the dell; <add place="rmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">F&sol;</add></l><l n="63"><add place="lmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add>And they, who do make mention of the same,</l><l n="64"><add place="lmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add>From this day forth, shall call it Hart-leap Well. <add hand="dw" place="rmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">H<hi>art-leap</hi> W<hi>ell</hi></add></l></lg><lg n="17" type="stanza"><l n="65"><add place="lmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add>And, gallant brute! to make thy praises known,</l><l n="66"><add place="lmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add>Another monument shall here be rais&rsquo;d;</l><l n="67"><add place="lmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">&sol;P</add> <add place="lmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add>Three several <del>p</del>illars, each a rough hewn <del>s</del>tone, <add place="rmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">S&sol;</add></l><l n="68"><add place="lmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add>And planted where thy hoofs the turf have graz&rsquo;d.</l></lg><lg n="18" type="stanza"><l n="69"><add place="lmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add>And in the summer-time when days are long,</l><l n="70"><add place="lmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add>I will come hither with my <del>p</del>aramour<del>,</del> <add place="rmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">P&sol; ;&sol;</add></l><l n="71"><add place="lmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">&sol;D</add> <add place="lmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add>And with the <del>d</del>ancers, and the <del>m</del>instrel&rsquo;s song, <add place="rmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">M&sol;</add></l><l n="72"> <add place="lmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add>We will make merry in that pleasant <del>b</del>ower. <add place="rmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">B&sol;</add></l></lg><pb><milestone n="6" unit="page"><lb><lb><lg n="19" type="stanza"><l n="73"><add place="lmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add>Till the foundations of the mountains fail</l><l n="74"><add place="lmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">M&sol;A</add><add place="lmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add>My <del>m</del>ansion with its <del>a</del>rbour shall endure,</l><l n="75"><add place="lmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add>&mdash;The joy of them who till the fields of Swale,</l><l n="76"><add place="lmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add>And them who dwell among the woods of Ure<del>.</del>&rdquo; <add place="rmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">!&sol;</add></l></lg><lg n="20" type="stanza"><l n="77">Then home he went, and left the Hart, stone-dead,</l><l n="78">With breathless nostrils stretch&rsquo;d above the spring.</l><l n="79">And soon the Knight perform&rsquo;d what he had said,</l><l n="80">The fame whereof through many a land did ring.</l></lg><lg n="21" type="stanza"><l n="81">Ere thrice the moon into her port had steer&rsquo;d,</l><l n="82"><add place="lmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">C&sol;S</add> A <del>c</del>up of <del>s</del>tone receiv&rsquo;d the living <del>w</del>ell; <add place="rmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">W&sol;</add></l><l n="83"><add place="lmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">&sol;P</add> Three <del>p</del>illars of rude stone Sir Walter rear&rsquo;d,</l><l n="84">And built a <del>h</del>ouse of <del>p</del>leasure in the dell. <add place="rmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">H&sol;P</add></l></lg><lg n="22" type="stanza"><l n="85">And near the fountain, flowers of stature tall</l><l n="86">With trailing plants and trees were intertwin&rsquo;d,</l><l n="87">Which soon composed a little sylvan <del>h</del>all, <add place="rmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">H</add></l><l n="88">A leafy shelter from the sun and wind.</l></lg><pb><milestone n="7" unit="page"><lb><lb><lg n="23" type="stanza"><l n="89">And thither, when the summer days were long,</l><l n="90">Sir Walter journey&rsquo;d with his <del>p</del>aramour; <add place="rmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">P&sol;</add></l><l n="91"><add place="lmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">D&sol;M</add> And with the <del>d</del>ancers and the <del>m</del>instrel&rsquo;s song</l><l n="92">Made merriment within that pleasant <del>b</del>ower. <add place="rmargin" rend="ink" resp="w">B&sol;</add></l></lg><lg n="24" type="stanza"><l n="93">The Knight, Sir Walter, died in course of time,</l><l n="94">And his bones lie in his paternal vale.&mdash;</l><l n="95">But there is matter for a second rhyme,</l><l n="96">And I to this would add another tale.</l></lg></div><pb><milestone n="8" unit="page"><lb><lb><div type="part" n="2"><head><emph><hi rend="small">PART  SECOND. </hi></emph><lb></head><lg n="25" type="stanza"><l n="97">The moving accident is not my trade<del>.</del> <add place="rmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">:&sol;</add></l><l n="98">To<del>curl</del> <add hand="dw" place="aboveline" rend="ink" resp="ww">freeze</add> the blood I have no ready arts<del>;</del> <add place="rmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">:&sol;</add></l><l n="99">&rsquo;Tis my delight, alone in summer shade,</l><l n="100">To pipe a simple song to thinking hearts.</l></lg><lg n="26" type="stanza"><l n="101">As I from Hawes to Richmond did repair,</l><l n="102">It chanc&rsquo;d that I saw standing in a <del>d</del>ell <add place="rmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">D&sol;</add></l><l n="103"><add place="lmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">&sol;A</add> Three <del>a</del>spins at three corners of a square,</l><l n="104">And one, not four yards distant, near a <del>w</del>ell. <add place="rmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">W&sol;</add></l></lg><lg n="26" type="stanza"><l n="105">What this imported I could ill divine<del>,</del> <add place="rmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">:&sol;</add></l><l n="106">And, pulling now the rein my horse to stop,</l><l n="107"><add place="lmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">&sol;P</add> I saw three <del>p</del>illars standing in a line,</l><l n="108"><add place="lmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">S&sol;P</add> The last <del>s</del>tone <del>p</del>illar on a dark hill-top.</l></lg><pb><milestone n="9" unit="verseparagraph"><lb><lb><lg n="27" type="stanza"><l n="109"><add place="lmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">&sol;T</add> The <del>t</del>rees were grey, with neither arms nor head;</l><l n="110">Half-wasted the square <del>m</del>ound of tawny green; <add place="rmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">M&sol;</add></l><l n="111">So that you just might say, as then I said,</l><l n="112">&ldquo;Here in old time the hand of man has been.&rdquo;</l></lg><lg n="28" type="stanza"><l n="113">I look&rsquo;d upon the hills both far and near;</l><l n="114">More doleful place did never eye survey;</l><l n="115"><add place="lmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">&sol;S</add> It seem&rsquo;d as if the <del>s</del>pring-time came not here,</l><l n="116">And Nature here were willing to decay.</l></lg><lg n="29" type="stanza"><l n="117">I stood in various thoughts and fancies lost,</l><l n="118"><add place="lmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">&sol;,</add> When one<add place="belowline" rend="ink" resp="ww">^</add> who was in Shepherd&rsquo;s garb attir&rsquo;d,</l><l n="119"><add place="lmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">&sol;H</add> Came up the <del>h</del>ollow.  Him did I accost,</l><l n="120">And what this place might be I then inquir&rsquo;d.</l></lg><lg n="30" type="stanza"><l n="121">The Shepherd stopp&rsquo;d, and that same story told</l><l n="122">Which in my former rhyme I have rehears&rsquo;d.</l><l n="123">&ldquo;A jolly place,&rdquo; said he, &ldquo;in times of old<del>,</del> <add place="rmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">!&sol;</add></l><l n="124"><add place="lmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add>But something ails it now; the spot is curs&rsquo;d.</l></lg><pb><milestone n="10" unit="page"><lb><lb><lg n="31" type="stanza"><l n="125"><add place="lmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">&sol;S</add>  <add place="lmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add>You see these lifeless <del>s</del>tumps of aspin wood,</l><l n="126"><add place="lmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add>Some say that they are beeches, others elms<del>,</del> <add place="rmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">&mdash;&sol;</add></l><l n="127"><add place="lmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add>These were the Bower; and here a Mansion stood,</l><l n="128"><add place="lmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add>The finest palace of a hundred realms<del>.</del> <add place="rmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">!&sol;</add></l></lg><lg n="32" type="stanza"><l n="129"><add place="lmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">&sol;A</add> <add place="lmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add>The <del>a</del>rbour does its own condition tell<del>,</del> <add place="rmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">;&sol;</add></l><l n="130"><add place="lmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">&sol;S&sol;F</add> <add place="lmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add>You see the <del>s</del>tones, the <del>f</del>ountain, and the <del>s</del>tream, <add place="rmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">S&sol;</add></l><l n="131"><add place="lmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add>But as to the great Lodge<del>,</del> you might as well <add place="rmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">!&sol;</add></l><l n="132"><add place="lmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add>Hunt half a day for a forgotten dream.</l></lg><lg n="33" type="stanza"><l n="133"><add place="lmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add>There&rsquo;s neither dog nor heifer, horse nor sheep,</l><l n="134"><add place="lmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add>Will wet his lips within that <del>c</del>up of <del>s</del>tone; <add place="rmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">C&sol;S</add></l><l n="135"><add place="lmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add>And, oftentimes, when all are fast asleep,</l><l n="136"><add place="lmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add>This water doth send forth a dolorous groan.</l></lg><lg n="34" type="stanza"><l n="137"><add place="lmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add>Some say that here a murder has been done,</l><l n="138"><add place="lmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add>And blood cries out for blood: but, for my part,</l><l n="139"><add place="lmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add>I&rsquo;ve guess&rsquo;d, when I&rsquo;ve been sitting in the sun,</l><l n="140"><add place="lmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add>That it was all for that unhappy Hart.</l></lg><pb><milestone n="11" unit="page"><lb><lb><lg n="35" type="stanza"><l n="141"><add place="lmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add>What thoughts must through the creature&rsquo;s brain have pass&rsquo;d!</l><l n="142"><add place="lmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add><del>To this place from the stone upon the steep</del> <add hand="dw" place="aboveline" rend="ink" resp="ww">From the stone <del>on</del> <add hand="dw" rend="ink" place="aboveline" resp="ww">upon</add> the 
summit of the steep</add></l><l n="143"><add place="lmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add>Are but three bounds<del>,</del><add place="belowline" rend="ink" resp="ww">^</add> and look, Sir, at this last<del>!</del><add place="belowline" rend="ink" resp="ww">^</add><add place="rmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">&mdash;&sol; &mdash;&sol;</add></l><l n="144"><add place="lmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">&ldquo;&mdash;</add><add place="belowline" rend="ink " resp="ww">^</add> O Master! it has been a cruel leap.</l></lg><lg n="36" type="stanza"><l n="145"><add place="lmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add>For thirteen hours he ran a desperate race;</l><l n="146"><add place="lmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> And in my simple mind we cannot tell</l><l n="147"><add place="lmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add>What cause the Hart might have to love this place,</l><l n="148"><add place="lmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add>And come and make his death-bed near the <del>w</del>ell. <add place="rmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">W&sol;</add></l></lg><lg n="37" type="stanza"><l n="149"><add place="lmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add>Here on the grass perhaps asleep he sank,</l><l n="150"><add place="lmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add>Lull&rsquo;d by the <del>f</del>ountain in the summer-tide; <add place="rmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">F&sol;</add></l><l n="151"><add place="lmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add>This water was perhaps the first he drank</l><l n="152"><add place="lmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add>When he had wander&rsquo;d from his mother&rsquo;s side.</l></lg><lg n="38" type="stanza"><l n="153"><add place="lmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add>In April here beneath the scented thorn</l><l n="154"><add place="lmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add>He heard the birds their morning carols sing<del>,</del> <add place="rmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">;&sol;</add></l><l n="155"><add place="lmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add>And he, perhaps, for aught we know, was born</l><l n="156"><add place="lmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add>Not half a furlong from that self-same <del>s</del>pring. <add place="rmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww"><del>S&sol;</del></add></l></lg><pb><milestone n="12" unit="page"><lb><lb><lg n="39" type="stanza"><l n="157"><add place="lmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add>But now here&rsquo;s neither grass nor pleasant shade;</l><l n="158"><add place="lmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">&sol;H</add><add place="lmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add>The sun on drearier <del>h</del>ollow never shone:</l><l n="159"><add place="lmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add>So will it be, as I have often said,</l><l n="160"><add place="lmarging" rend="ink" resp="ww">T&sol;S</add><add place="lmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add>Till <del>t</del>rees, and <del>s</del>tones, and <del>f</del>ountain all are gone.&rdquo; F&sol;</l></lg><lg n="40" type="stanza"><l n="161">&ldquo;Grey-headed Shepherd, thou hast spoken well;</l><l n="162"><add place="lmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add>Small difference lies between thy creed and mine<del>;</del> <add place="rmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">:&sol;</add></l><l n="163"><add place="lmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">&sol;B</add><add place="lmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add>This <del>b</del>east not unobserv&rsquo;d by Nature fell<del>,</del><add place="rmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww"> ;&sol;</add></l><l n="164"><add place="lmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add>His death was mourn&rsquo;d by sympathy divine.</l></lg><lg n="41" type="stanza"><l n="165"><add place="lmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add>The Being, that is in the clouds and air,</l><l n="166"><add place="lmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add>That is in the green leaves among the groves,</l><l n="167"><add place="lmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add>Maintains a deep and reverential care</l><l n="168"><add place="lmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add>For them the quiet creatures whom he loves.</l></lg><lg n="42" type="stanza"><l n="169"><add place="lmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add>The Pleasure-house is dust:&mdash;behind, before,</l><l n="170"><add place="lmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add>This is no common waste, no common gloom;</l><l n="171"><add place="lmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add>But Nature, in due course of time, once more</l><l n="172"><add place="lmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add>Shall here put on her beauty and her bloom.</l></lg></div></body></text><pb><text><body><milestone n="19" unit="page"><lb><lb><head><lb><emph>The BROTHERS.</emph>*</head><lg n="1" part="I" type="verseparagraph"><l n="1"><add place="lmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add>These Tourists, Heaven preserve us! needs must live</l><l n="2"><add place="lmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add>A profitable life: some glance along,</l><l n="3">&ldquo;<add place="lmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add>Rapid and gay, as if the earth were air,</l><l n="4"><add place="lmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add>And they were butterflies to wheel about</l><l n="5"><add place="lmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">:&sol;</add> <add place="lmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add>Long as their summer lasted <del>;</del> some, as wise,</l><l n="6"><add place="lmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add>Upon the forehead of a jutting crag</l><l n="7"><add place="lmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add>Sit perch&rsquo;d with book and pencil on their knee,</l><l n="8"><add place="lmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add>And look and scribble, scribble on and look,</l><l n="9"><add place="lmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add>Until a man might travel twelve stout miles,</l><l n="10"><add place="lmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add>Or reap an acre of his neighbour&rsquo;s corn.</l></lg><note n="*" resp="author" place="foot">* This Poem was intended to be the concluding poem of a series <lb>of pastorals, the scene of which was laid among the mountains <lb>of Cumberland and Westmoreland.  I mention this to apologise <lb>for the abruptness with which the poem begins.</note><pb><milestone n="20" unit="page"><lb><lb><lg n="1" part="M" type="verseparagraph"><l n="11"><add place="lmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">&sol;S</add><add place="lmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add>But, for that moping <del>s</del>on of Idleness<add place="belowline" rend="ink" resp="ww">^</add> <add place="rmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">,&sol;</add></l><l n="12"><add place="lmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add>Why can he tarry <emph>yonder?</emph>&mdash;In our church-yard</l><l n="13"><add place="lmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add>Is neither epitaph nor monument,</l><l n="14"><add place="lmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add>Tomb-stone nor name<del>,</del> only the turf we tread, <add place="rmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">&mdash;&sol;</add></l><l n="15"><add place="lmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add>And a few natural graves. <add place="belowline" rend="ink" resp="ww">^</add><add place="inline" rend="ink" resp="ww">&rdquo;</add> To Jane, his Wife,</l><l n="16">Thus spake the homely Priest of Ennerdale.</l><l n="17"><add place="lmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">&sol;;</add> It was a July evening<del>,</del> and he sate ;</l><l n="18">Upon the long stone-seat beneath the eaves</l><l n="19">Of his old cottage, as it chanced<add place="belowline" rend="ink" resp="ww">^</add> that day, <add place="rmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">&lsquo;&sol;</add></l><l n="20">Employ&rsquo;d in winter&rsquo;s work. Upon the stone</l><l n="21">His Wife sate near him, teasing matted wool,</l><l n="22">While, from the twin cards tooth&rsquo;d with glittering wire,</l><l n="23">He fed the spindle of his youngest <del>c</del>hild, <add place="rmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">C&sol;</add></l><l n="24">Who turn&rsquo;d her large round wheel in the open air</l><l n="25">With back and forward steps. Towards the field</l><l n="26"><add place="lmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">&sol;P&sol;C</add> In which the <del>p</del>arish <del>c</del>hapel stood alone,</l><l n="27">Girt round with a bare ring of mossy wall,</l><l n="28">While half an hour went by, the Priest had sent</l><l n="29">Many a long look of wonder. and at last,</l><l n="30">Risen from his seat, beside the snow<del>y</del><add place="belowline" rend="ink" resp="ww">^</add><add hand="dw" place="aboveline" rend="ink" resp="ww">-white</add> ridge</l></lg><p><add hand="dw" place="pagebottom" rend="ink" resp="ww">snow-white<lb>with a hyphen</add></p><pb><milestone n="21" unit="page"><lb><lb><lg n="1" part="F" type="verseparagraph"><l n="31">Of carded wool which the old Man had piled</l><l n="32">He laid his implements with gentle care,</l><l n="33">Each in the other lock&rsquo;d; and, down the path</l><l n="34">Which from his cottage to the church-yard led,</l><l n="35">He took his way, impatient to accost</l><l n="36">The Stranger, whom he saw still lingering there.</l></lg><lg n="2" part="I" type="verseparagraph"><l n="37"> &rsquo;Twas one well known to him in former days,</l><l n="38">A Shepherd-lad: who ere his thirteenth year</l><l n="39">Had chang&rsquo;d his calling, with the mariners</l><l n="40">A fellow-mariner, and so had fared</l><l n="41">Through twenty seasons; but he had been rear&rsquo;d</l><l n="42">Among the mountains, and he in his heart</l><l n="43">Was half a Shepherd on the stormy seas.</l><l n="44">Oft in the piping shrouds had Leonard heard</l><l n="45">The tones of waterfalls, and inland sounds</l><l n="46"><add place="lmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">&sol;&mdash;</add> Of caves and trees<del>;</del> and<add place="belowline" rend="ink" resp="ww">^</add> when the regular wind ,&sol;</l><l n="47">Between the tropics fill&rsquo;d the steady sail^ ,&sol;</l><l n="48">And blew with the same breath through days and weeks,</l><l n="49">Lengthening invisibly its weary line</l></lg><pb><milestone n="22" unit="page"><lb><lb><lg n="2" part="F" type="verseparagraph"><l n="50"><add place="lmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">&sol;M</add> Along the cloudless <del>m</del>ain, he, in those hours</l><l n="51"><add place="lmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">&sol;,</add> Of tiresome indolence^ would often hang</l><l n="52">Over the vessel&rsquo;s side, and gaze and gaze,</l><l n="53">And, while the broad green wave and sparkling foam</l><l n="54">Flash&rsquo;d round him images and hues, that wrought</l><l n="55">In union with the employment of his heart,</l><l n="56">He, thus by feverish passion overcome,</l><l n="57">Even with the organs of his bodily eye,</l><l n="58">Below him, in the bosom of the deep<add place="belowline" rend="ink" resp="ww">^</add> <add place="rmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">,&sol;</add></l><l n="59">Saw mountains, saw the forms of sheep that graz&rsquo;d</l><l n="60">On verdant hills, with dwellings among trees,</l><l n="61">And Shepherds clad in the same country grey</l><l n="62" part="i">Which he himself had worn.*</l></lg><lg n="3" part="I" type="verseparagraph"><l part="f" rend="right"> And now at length,</l><l n="63">From perils manifold, with some small wealth</l><l n="64">Acquir&rsquo;d by traffic in the Indian Isles,</l><l n="65">To his paternal home he is return&rsquo;d,</l></lg><note n="*" place="foot" resp="author">*This description of the Calenture is sketched from an imper-<lb>fect recollection of an admirable one in prose, by Mr. Gilbert, <lb>Author of the Hurricane.</note><pb><milestone n="23" unit="page"><lb><lb><lg n="3" part="M" type="verseparagraph"><l n="66">With a determin&rsquo;d purpose to resume</l><l n="67"><add place="lmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">&sol;:</add> The life which he liv&rsquo;d there<del>,</del> both for the sake</l><l n="68">Of many darling pleasures, and the love</l><l n="69">Which to an only brother he has borne</l><l n="70">In all his hardships, since that happy time</l><l n="71">When, whether it blew foul or fair, they two</l><l n="72">Were brother Shepherds on their native hills.</l><l n="73">&mdash;&mdash;They were the last of all their race<del>;</del> and now, <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">:&sol;</add></l><l n="74">When Leonard had approach&rsquo;d his home, his heart</l><l n="75"><add place="lmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">;</add>Fail&rsquo;d in him<del>,</del> and, not venturing to inquire</l><l n="76">Tidings of one whom he so dearly lov&rsquo;d,</l><l n="77">Towards the church-yard he had turn&rsquo;d aside,</l><l n="78">That, as he knew in what particular spot</l><l n="79">His family were laid, he thence might learn</l><l n="80">If still his Brother liv&rsquo;d, or to the file</l><l n="81">Another grave was added.&mdash;He had found</l><l n="82">Another grave, near which a full half hour</l><l n="83"><add place="rmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">&sol;;</add> He had remain&rsquo;d<del>,</del> but, as he gaz&rsquo;d, there grew</l><l n="84">Such a confusion in his memory,</l><l n="85">That he began to doubt, and he had hopes</l></lg><pb><milestone n="24" unit="page"><lb><lb><lg n="3" part="F" type="verseparagraph"><l n="86">That he had seen this heap of turf before,</l><l n="87">That it was not another grave, but one,</l><l n="88">He had forgotten. He had lost his path,</l><l n="89">As up the vale he came that afternoon,</l><l n="90">Through fields which once had been well known to him.</l><l n="91">And Oh! what joy the recollection now</l><l n="92">Sent to his heart! he lifted up his eyes,</l><l n="93">And looking round he thought that he perceiv&rsquo;d</l><l n="94">Strange alteration wrought on every side</l><l n="95">Among the woods and fields, and that the rocks,</l><l n="96">And the eternal hills, themselves were chang&rsquo;d.</l></lg><lg n="4" type="verseparagraph" part="I"><l n="97"> By this the Priest who down the field had come</l><l n="98">Unseen by Leonard, at the church-yard gate</l><l n="99">Stopp&rsquo;d short, and thence, at leisure, limb by limb</l><l n="100">He scann&rsquo;d him with a gay complacency.</l><l n="101">Aye, thought the Vicar, smiling to himself,</l><l n="102">&rsquo;Tis one of those who needs must leave the path</l><l n="103">Of the world&rsquo;s business, to go wild alone:</l><l n="104">His arms have a perpetual holiday<del>,</del> <add place="rmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">;&sol;</add></l></lg><pb><milestone n="25" unit="page"><lb><lb><lg n="4" part="F" type="verseparagraph"><l n="105"><add place="lmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">M</add> The happy <del>m</del>an will creep about the fields</l><l n="106">Following his fancies by the hour, to bring</l><l n="107">Tears down his cheek, or solitary smiles</l><l n="108">Into his face, until the setting sun</l><l n="109">Write Fool upon his forehead.  Planted thus</l><l n="110">Beneath a shed that overarch&rsquo;d the gate</l><l n="111">Of this rude church-yard, till the stars appear&rsquo;d</l><l n="112">The good man might have commun&rsquo;d with himself</l><l n="113">But that the Stranger, who had left the grave,</l><l n="114">Approach&rsquo;d; he recogniz&rsquo;d the Priest at once,</l><l n="115"><add place="lmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">,</add> And<add place="belowline" rend="ink" resp="ww">^</add>after greetings interchang&rsquo;d, and given</l><l n="116">By Leonard to the Vicar as to one</l><l n="117">Unknown to him, this dialogue ensued.</l></lg><sp><speaker>LEONARD.</speaker><lg n="5" type="verseparagraph" part="I"><l n="118">You live, Sir, in these dales, a quiet life:</l><l n="119">Your years make up one peaceful family;</l></lg><pb><milestone n="26" unit="page"><lb><lb><lg n="5" part="F" type="verseparagraph"><l n="124">And yet, some changes must take place among you<del>.</del> <add place="rmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">:</add></l><l n="125">And you, who dwell here, even among these rocks</l><l n="126">Can trace the finger of mortality,</l><l n="127">And see, that with our threescore years and ten</l><l n="128">We are not all that perish.&mdash;&mdash;I remember,</l><l n="129">For many years ago I pass&rsquo;d this road,</l><l n="130">There was a foot-way all along the fields</l><l n="131">By the brook-side&mdash;&rsquo;tis gone&mdash;and that dark cleft!</l><l n="132">To me it does not seem to wear the face</l><l n="133" part="i">Which then it had.</l></lg></sp><sp><speaker>PRIEST.</speaker><lg n="6" type="verseparagraph"><l part="f" rend="right">   Why, Sir, for aught I know,</l><l n="134" part="i">That chasm is much the same&mdash;</l></lg></sp><sp><speaker>LEONARD.</speaker><lg n="7" type="verseparagraph"><l part="f" rend="right">      But, surely, yonder&mdash;</l></lg></sp><sp><speaker>PRIEST.</speaker><pb><milestone n="27" unit="page"><lb><lb><lg n="8" part="M" type="verseparagraph"><l n="144">For accidents and changes such as these,</l><l n="145">Why we have store of them! a water-spout</l><l n="146">Will bring down half a mountain; what a feast</l><l n="147">For folks that wander up and down like you,</l><l n="148">To see an acre&rsquo;s breadth of that wide cliff</l><l n="149"><add place="lmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">!&mdash;</add> One roaring cataract<del>&mdash;</del>a sharp May storm</l><l n="150">Will come with loads of January snow,</l><l n="151">And in one night send twenty score of sheep</l><l n="152"><add place="lmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">;</add> To feed the ravens<del>,</del> or a Shepherd dies</l><l n="153">By some untoward death among the rocks:</l><l n="154">The ice breaks up and sweeps away a bridge&mdash;</l><l n="155">A wood is fell&rsquo;d:&mdash;and then for our own homes!</l><l n="156"><add place="lmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">C</add> A <del>c</del>hild is born or christen&rsquo;d, a <del>f</del>ield plough&rsquo;d, <add place="rmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">F&sol;</add></l><l n="157"><add place="lmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">D</add> A <del>d</del>aughter sent to service, a <del>w</del>eb spun, <add place="rmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">W&sol;</add></l><l n="158">The old <del>h</del>ouse <del><del>cloth</del></del> <add place="belowline" rend="ink" resp="ww">^</add><add hand="dw" place="aboveline" rend="ink" resp="ww">-clock</add> is deck&rsquo;d with a new face; <add place="rmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">H&sol;</add><lb><add hand="dw" place="belowline" rend="ink" resp="ww">House-clock</add></l></lg><pb><lg n="8" part="F" type="verseparagraph"><l n="164" part="i">Commend me to these vallies.</l></lg></sp><sp><speaker>LEONARD.</speaker><lg n="9" type="verseparagraph"><l part="f" rend="right">	Yet your <del>c</del>hurch-yard <add place="rmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">C&sol;</add></l><l n="165">Seems, if such freedom may be used with you,</l><l n="166">To say that you are heedless of the past.</l><l n="167" rend="ms."><add hand="dw" place="betweenlines" rend="ink" resp="ww">An orphan could not find his mothers grave:</add></l><l n="168">Here&rsquo;s neither head nor foot-stone, plate of brass,</l><l n="169">Cross-bones or skull, type of our earthly state</l><l n="170">Or emblem of our hopes: the dead man&rsquo;s home</l><l n="171">Is but a fellow to that pasture field.</l></lg></sp><sp><speaker>PRIEST.</speaker><lg n="10" part="I" type="verseparagraph"><l n="172">Why there, Sir, is a thought that&rsquo;s new to me.</l><l n="173">The Stone-cutters, &rsquo;tis true, might beg their bread</l><l n="174"><add place="lmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">&sol;C</add> If every English <del>c</del>hurch-yard were like ours:</l><l n="175">Yet your conclusion wanders from the truth.</l></lg><pb><milestone n="29" unit="page"><lb><lb><lg n="10" part="F" type="verseparagraph"><l n="176">We have no need of names and epitaphs<del>,</del> <add place="rmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">;&sol;</add></l><l n="177">We talk about the dead by our fire-sides.</l><l n="178">, And<add place="belowline" rend="ink" resp="ww">^</add>then for our immortal part<del>,</del> <emph>we</emph> want <add place="rmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">!&sol;</add></l><l n="179">No symbols, Sir, to tell us that plain tale:</l><l n="180">The thought of death sits easy on the man</l><l n="181">Who has been born and dies among the mountains<del>:</del> <add place="rmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">.&sol;</add></l></lg></sp><sp><speaker>LEONARD.</speaker><lg n="11" type="verseparagraph"><l n="182"><add place="lmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">D</add> Your <del>d</del>alesmen, then, do in each other&rsquo;s thoughts</l><l n="183">Possess a kind of second life: no doubt</l><l n="184">You, Sir, could help me to the history</l><l n="185" part="I">Of half these Graves?</l></lg></sp><sp><speaker>PRIEST.</speaker><lg n="12" part="I" type="verseparagraph"><l part="F" n="185"><add hand="dw" place="betweenline" rend="ink" resp="ww">For eight-score winters past,</add></l><l n="186">With what I&rsquo;ve witness&rsquo;d, and with what I&rsquo;ve heard,</l><l n="187">;Perhaps I might<del>,</del> and, on a winter&rsquo;s evening,</l><l n="188">If you were seated at my chimney&rsquo;s nook<add place="belowline" rend="ink" resp="ww">^</add> <add place="rmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">,&sol;</add></l><l n="189">By turning o&rsquo;er these hillocks one by one<del>,</del> <add place="rmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww"><add place="rmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">d&sol;</add></add></l><l n="190">We two could travel, Sir, through a strange round,</l><l n="191">Yet all in the broad high-way of the world.</l><l n="192">Now there&rsquo;s a grave&mdash;your foot is half upon it,</l></lg><pb><milestone n="30" unit="page"><lb><lb><lg n="12" part="F" type="verseparagraph"><l n="193"><add place="lmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">&sol;;</add> It looks just like the rest<del>,</del> and yet that <del>m</del>an <add place="rmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">M&sol;</add></l><l n="194" part="i">Died broken-hearted.</l></lg></sp><sp><speaker>LEONARD.</speaker><lg n="13" type="verseparagraph"><l part="f" rend="right">      &rsquo;Tis a common case,</l><l n="195">We&rsquo;ll take another: who is he that lies</l><l n="196">Beneath yon ridge, the last of those three graves;&mdash;</l><l n="197">It touches on that piece of native rock</l><l n="198" part="i">Left in the church-yard wall.</l></lg></sp><sp><speaker>PRIEST.</speaker><lg n="14" part="I" type="verseparagraph"><l part="f" rend="right">         That&rsquo;s Walter Ewbank.</l><l n="199">He had as white a head and fresh a cheek</l><l n="200">As ever were produc&rsquo;d by youth and age</l><l n="201">Engendering in the blood of hale fourscore.</l><l n="202">For five long generations had the heart</l><l n="203">Of Walter&rsquo;s forefathers o&rsquo;erflow&rsquo;d the bounds</l><l n="204">Of their inheritance, that single cottage,</l><l n="205"><add place="lmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">&sol;!</add> <add place="lmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">&sol;&mdash;</add><add place="belowline" rend="ink" resp="ww">^</add>You see it yonder<del>,</del> and those few green fields.</l><l n="206">They toil&rsquo;d and wrought, and still, from <del>s</del>ire to<del>s</del>on, <add place="rmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">S&sol;S&sol;</add></l><l n="207">Each struggled, and each yielded as before</l></lg><pb><milestone n="31" unit="page"><lb><lb><lg n="14" part="F" type="verseparagraph"><l n="208">A little&mdash;yet a little&mdash;and old Walter,</l><l n="209">They left to him the family heart, and land</l><l n="210">With other burthens than the crop it bore.</l><l n="211">Year after year the old man still <del>preserv&rsquo;d</del> <add hand="dw" place="rmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">kept up</add></l><l n="212">A chearful mind, and buffeted with bond,</l><l n="213">Interest and mortgages; at last he sank,</l><l n="214">And went into his grave before his time.</l><l n="215">Poor Walter! whether it was care that spurr&rsquo;d him</l><l n="216">God only knows, but to the very last</l><l n="217">He had the lightest foot in Ennerdale:</l><l n="218">His pace was never that of an old man:</l><l n="219">I almost see him tripping down the path</l><l n="220">With his two Grandsons after him&mdash;but <del>y</del>ou, <add place="rmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">Y&sol;</add></l><l n="221">Unless our Landlord be your host to-night,</l><l n="222">Have far to travel, and in these rough paths</l><l n="223">Even in the longest day of midsummer&mdash;</l></lg></sp><sp><speaker>LEONARD.</speaker><lg n="224" type="verseparagraph"><l part="I" n="223">But these two Orphans!</l></lg></sp><sp><speaker>PRIEST. </speaker><lg n="16" type="verseparagraph" part="I"><l n="223" part="F" rend="right">     Orphans! such they were&mdash;</l></lg><pb><milestone n="32" unit="page"><lb><lb><lg n="16" part="F" type="verseparagraph"><l n="225">Yet not while Walter liv&rsquo;d&mdash;for, though their Parents</l><l n="226">Lay buried side by side as now they lie,</l><l n="227">The old Man was a father to the boys,</l><l n="228">Two fathers in one father: and if tears<add place="belowline" rend="ink" resp="ww">^</add> <add place="rmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">,&sol;</add></l><l n="229"><add place="lmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">&sol;d</add> Shed<del>,</del> when he talk&rsquo;d of them where they were not,</l><l n="230">And hauntings from the infirmity of love,</l><l n="231">Are aught of what makes up a mother&rsquo;s heart,</l><l n="232">This old Man in the day of his old age</l><l n="233">Was half a mother to them.&mdash;If you weep, Sir,</l><l n="234"><add place="lmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">&sol;S</add> To hear a <del>s</del>tranger talking about <del>s</del>trangers, <add place="rmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">S&sol;</add></l><l n="235">Heaven bless you when you are among your kindred!</l><l n="236">Aye.  You may turn that way&mdash;it is a grave</l><l n="237" part="I">Which will bear looking at.</l></lg></sp><sp><speaker>LEONARD.</speaker><lg n="17" type="verseparagraph"><l part="F" n="236" rend="right">			These Boys<add place="belowline" rend="ink" resp="ww">^</add>I hope <add place="rmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">&mdash;&sol;</add></l><l part="I" n="238">They lov&rsquo;d this good old Man&mdash;</l></lg></sp><sp><speaker>PRIEST. </speaker><lg n="18" part="I" type="verseparagraph"><l part="f" rend="right">			They did&mdash;and truly<del>,</del> <add place="rmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">:&sol;</add></l><l n="239">But that was what we almost overlook&rsquo;d,</l></lg><pb><milestone n="33" unit="page"><lb><lb><lg n="18" part="M" type="verseparagraph"><l n="240">They were such darlings of each other. For</l><l n="241">Though from their cradles they had liv&rsquo;d with Walter,</l><l n="242"><add place="lmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">&sol;K</add> The only <del>k</del>insman near them in the house,</l><l n="243">Yet he being old, they had much love to spare,</l><l n="244">And it all went into each other&rsquo;s hearts.</l><l n="245">Leonard, the elder by just eighteen months,</l><l n="246">Was two years taller: &rsquo;twas a joy to see,</l><l n="247">To hear, to meet them! from their house the School</l><l n="248">Was distant three short miles<del>,</del> and in the time <add place="rmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">&mdash;&sol;</add></l><l n="249">Of storm and thaw, when every water-course</l><l n="250">And unbridg&rsquo;d stream, such as you may have notic&rsquo;d</l><l n="251">Crossing our roads at every hundred steps,</l><l n="252">Was swoln into a noisy rivulet,</l><l n="253">Would Leonard then, when elder boys perhaps</l><l n="254">Remain&rsquo;d at home, go staggering through the fords</l><l n="255">Bearing his Brother on his back.&mdash;I&rsquo;ve seen him,</l><l n="256">On windy days, in one of those stray brooks,</l><l n="257">Aye, more than once I&rsquo;ve seen him mid-leg deep,</l><l n="258">Their two books lying both on a dry stone</l><l n="259">Upon the hither side:&mdash;and once I said,</l></lg><pb><milestone n="34" unit="page"><lb><lb><lg n="18" part="F" type="verseparagraph"><l n="260">As I remember, looking round these rocks</l><l n="261">And hills on which we all of us were born,</l><l n="262">That God who made the great book of the world</l><l n="263" part="I">Would bless such piety&mdash;</l></lg></sp><sp><speaker>LEONARD<sic>,</sic></speaker><lg n="19" type="verseparagraph"><l part="f" rend="right">			It may be then&mdash;</l></lg></sp><sp><speaker>PRIEST.</speaker><lg n="20" type="verseparagraph" part="I"><l n="264">Never did worthier lads break English bread<del>:</del> <add place="rmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">!&sol;</add></l><l n="265">The finest Sunday that the Autumn saw,</l><l n="266">Withal its mealy clusters of ripe nuts,</l><l n="267">Could never keep these boys away from church,</l><l n="268">Or tempt them to an hour of sabbath breach.</l><l n="269">Leonard and James! I warrant, every corner</l><l n="270">Among these rocks and every hollow place</l><l n="271">Where foot could come, to one or both of them</l><l n="272">Was known as well as to the flowers that gr<del>e</del>w there. <add place="rmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">o&sol;</add></l><l n="273"><add place="lmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">&sol;R</add> Like <del>r</del>oe-bucks they went bounding o&rsquo;er the hills:</l><l n="274"><add place="lmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">&sol;R</add> They play&rsquo;d like two young <del>r</del>avens on the crags:</l><l n="275">Then they could write, aye and speak too, as well</l></lg><pb><milestone n="35" unit="page"><lb><lb><lg n="20" part="F" type="verseparagraph"><l n="276">As many of their betters&mdash;and for Leonard!</l><l n="277">The very night before he went away,</l><l n="278">In my own house I put into his hand</l><l n="279">A Bible, and I&rsquo;d wager twenty pounds,</l><l n="280">That, if he is alive, he has it yet.</l></lg></sp><sp><speaker>LEONARD.</speaker><lg n="21" type="verseparagraph"><l n="281">It seems, these Brothers have not liv&rsquo;d to be</l><l n="282" part="i">A comfort to each other.&mdash;</l></lg></sp><sp><speaker>PRIEST.</speaker><lg n="22" type="verseparagraph"><l part="f" rend="right">That they might</l><l n="283">Live to that end, is what both old and young</l><l n="284">In this our valley all of us have wish&rsquo;d,</l><l n="285">And what, for my part, I have often pray&rsquo;d:</l><l n="286" part="i">But Leonard&mdash;</l></lg></sp><sp><speaker>LEONARD.</speaker><lg n="23" type="verseparagraph"><l part="f" rend="indent">	Then James still is left among you<del>&mdash;</del> <add place="rmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">!&sol;</add></l></lg></sp><sp><speaker>PRIEST.</speaker><lg n="18" type="verseparagraph"><l n="287">&rsquo;Tis of the elder brother I am speaking:</l></lg><pb><milestone n="36" unit="page"><lb><lb><lg part="M" type="verseparagraph" n="18"><l n="288">They had an Uncle, he was at that time</l><l n="289">A thriving man, and traffick&rsquo;d on the seas:</l><l n="290">And, but for this same Uncle, to this hour</l><l n="291">Leonard had never handled rope or shroud.</l><l n="292">For the Boy lov&rsquo;d the life which we lead here;</l><l n="293">And, though a very Stripling, twelve years old<del>;</del> <add place="rmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">,&sol;</add></l><l n="294">His soul was knit to this his native soil.</l><l n="295">But, as I said, old Walter was too weak</l><l n="296">To strive with such a torrent; when he died,</l><l n="297"><add place="lmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">E&sol;H</add> The <del>e</del>state and <del>h</del>ouse were sold, and all their <del>s</del>heep, <add place="rmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">S&sol;</add></l><l n="298">A pretty flock, and which, for aught I know,</l><l n="299">Had clothed the Ewbanks for a thousand years.</l><l n="300">Well&mdash;all was gone, and they were destitute.</l><l n="301">And Leonard, chiefly for his <del>b</del>rother&rsquo;s sake, <add place="rmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">B&sol;</add></l><l n="302">Resolv&rsquo;d to try his fortune on the seas.</l><l n="303">&rsquo;Tis now twelve years since we had tidings from him.</l><l n="304">If there was one among us who had heard</l><l n="305">That Leonard Ewbank was come home again,</l></lg><pb><milestone n="37" unit="page"><lb><lb><lg n="18" part="M" type="verseparagraph"><l n="306">From the Great Gavel*, down by Leeza&rsquo;s banks, </l><l n="307">And down the Enna, far as Egremont,</l><l n="308">The day would be a very festival,</l><l n="309">And those two bells of ours, which there you see</l><l n="310">Hanging in the open air&mdash;but, O good Sir!</l><l n="311">This is sad talk&mdash;they&rsquo;ll never sound for him</l><l n="312">Living or dead&mdash;When last we heard of him</l><l n="313">He was in slavery among the Moors</l><l n="314">Upon the Barbary Coast&mdash;&rsquo;Twas not a little</l><l n="315">That would bring down his spirit, and, no doubt,</l><l n="316">Before it ended in his death, the Lad</l></lg></sp><note n="*" place="foot" resp="auth">* The great Gavel, so called<add place="belowline" rend="ink" resp="ww">^</add> I imagine, from its resemblance <add place="rmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">,&sol;</add><lb>to the Gable end of a house, is one of the highest of the Cum-<lb>berland mountains. It stands at the head of the several vales of <lb>Ennerdale, Wastdale, and Borrowdale.<lb><lb>The Leeza is a River which <del>follows</del> <add place="belowline" rend="ink" resp="ww">^</add>into the Lake of Enner- <add hand="dw" place="rmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">flows&sol;</add><lb>dale: on issuing from the Lake, it changes its name, and is <lb>called the End, Eyne, or Enna. It falls into the sea a little be-<lb>low Egremont.</note><pb><milestone n="38" unit="page"><lb><lb><lg n="18" part="F" type="verseparagraph"><l n="317">Was sadly cross&rsquo;d&mdash;Poor Leonard! when we parted,</l><l n="318">He took me by the hand and said to me,</l><l n="319">If ever the day came when he was rich,</l><l n="320">He would return, and on his Father&rsquo;s Land</l><l n="321" part="i">He would grow old among us.</l></lg><sp><speaker>LEONARD.</speaker><lg n="19" type="verseparagraph"><l part="f" rend="right">			If that day</l><l n="322">Should come, &rsquo;twould needs be a glad day for him;</l><l n="323">He would himself, no doubt, be <del>as</del> happy then <add place="rmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">d&sol;</add></l><l n="324" part="i">As any that should meet him&mdash;</l></lg></sp><sp><speaker>PRIEST.</speaker><lg n="20" type="verseparagraph"><l part="f" rend="right">				Happy<del>,</del> Sir&mdash; <add place="rmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">!&sol;</add></l></lg></sp><sp><speaker>LEONARD.</speaker><lg n="21" type="verseparagraph"><l n="325">You said his kindred all were in their graves,</l><l n="326" part="i">And that he had one Brother&mdash; </l></lg></sp><sp><speaker>PRIEST.</speaker><lg n="22" part="I" type="verseparagraph"><l part="f" rend="right">				That is but</l></lg><pb><milestone n="39" unit="page"><lb><lb><lg n="22" part="F" type="verseparagraph"><l n="327">A fellow tale of sorrow. From his youth</l><l n="328">James, though not sickly, yet was delicate,</l><l n="329">And Leonard being always by his side</l><l n="330">Had done so many offices about him,</l><l n="331">That, though he was not of a timid nature,</l><l n="332">Yet still the spirit of a <del>m</del>ountain <del>b</del>oy <add place="rmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">M&sol;B</add></l><l n="333">In him was somewhat check&rsquo;d<del>,</del> and<add place="belowline" rend="ink" resp="ww">^</add>when his Brother <add place="rmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">,&sol;</add></l><l n="334">Was gone to sea and he was left alone<add place="belowline" rend="ink" resp="ww">^</add> <add place="rmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">,&sol;</add></l><l n="335">The little colour that he had was soon</l><l n="336">Stolen from his cheek, he droop&rsquo;d, and pin&rsquo;d and pin&rsquo;d<del>: </del><add place="rmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww"> &mdash;&sol;</add></l></lg></sp><sp><speaker>LEONARD.</speaker><lg n="23" type="verseparagraph"><l n="337">But these are all the graves of full-grown men!</l></lg></sp><sp><speaker>PRIEST.</speaker><lg n="24" part="I" type="verseparagraph"><l n="338">Aye, Sir, that pass&rsquo;d away: we took him to us.</l><l n="339"><add place="lmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">&sol;C</add> He was the <del>c</del>hild of all the dale&mdash;he liv&rsquo;d</l><l n="340">Three months with one, and six months with another<del>:</del> <add place="rmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">;&sol;</add></l><l n="341">And wanted neither food, nor clothes, nor love<del>,</del> <add place="rmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">:&sol;</add></l><l n="342">And many, many happy days were his.</l></lg><pb><milestone n="40" unit="page"><lb><lb><lg n="24" part="F" type="verseparagraph"><l n="343">But, whether blithe or sad, &rsquo;tis my belief</l><l n="344">His absent Brother still was at his heart.</l><l n="345">And, when he liv&rsquo;d beneath our roof, we found</l><l n="346">(A practice till this time unknown to him)</l><l n="347">That often, rising from his bed at night,</l><l n="348">He in his sleep would walk about, and sleeping</l><l n="349">He sought his Brother Leonard&mdash;You are mov&rsquo;d!</l><l n="350">Forgive me, Sir: before I spoke to you,</l><l n="351" part="i">I judg&rsquo;d you most unkindly.</l></lg></sp><sp><speaker>LEONARD.</speaker><lg n="25" type="verseparagraph"><l part="f" rend="right">			But this <del>y</del>outh, <add place="rmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">Y&sol;</add></l><l n="352" part="i">How did he die at last? </l></lg></sp><sp><speaker>PRIEST.</speaker><lg n="26" part="I" type="verseparagraph"><l part="f" rend="right">			One sweet May morning,</l><l n="353">It will be twelve years since, when Spring returns,</l><l n="354">He had gone forth among the new-dropp&rsquo;d lambs,</l><l n="355"><add place="lmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">&sol;C</add> With two or three <del>c</del>ompanions whom it chanc&rsquo;d</l><l n="356">Some further business summon&rsquo;d to a house</l></lg><pb><milestone n="41" unit="page"><lb><lb><lg n="26" part="M" type="verseparagraph"><l n="357">Which stands at the Dale-head.  James, tir&rsquo;d perhaps,</l><l n="358">Or from some other cause <add place="belowline" rend="ink" resp="ww">^</add> remain&rsquo;d behind. <add place="rmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">,&sol;</add></l><l n="359"><add place="lmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">&sol;P</add> You see yon <del>p</del>recipice&mdash;it almost looks</l><l n="360">Like some vast building made of many crags<del>,</del> <add place="rmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">;&sol;</add></l><l n="361">And in the midst is one particular rock</l><l n="362">That rises like a column from the vale,</l><l n="363">Whence by our Shepherds it is call&rsquo;d, the Pillar.</l><l n="364">James, point<del>ing</del><add place="belowline" rend="ink" resp="ww">^</add><add place="aboveline" rend="ink" resp="ww">ed</add> to its summit, over which</l><l n="365">They all had purpos&rsquo;d to return together,</l><l n="366"><del>Inform&rsquo;d</del> <add place="belowline" rend="ink" resp="ww">^</add><add hand="dw" place="aboveline" rend="ink" resp="ww">and told </add>them that he there would wait for them:</l><l n="367"><add place="lmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">&sol;C</add> They parted, and his <del>c</del>omrades pass&rsquo;d that way</l><l n="368">Some two hours after, but they did not find him</l><l n="369" rend="interlinear"><add hand="dw" place="aboveline" rend="ink" resp="ww">Upon the Pillar&mdash;at the appointed place.</add></l><l n="369"><del>At the appointed place, a circumstance</del></l><l n="370"><add hand="dw" place="lmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">this</add> Of <del>which</del> <add place="belowline" rend="ink" resp="ww">^</add><add place="aboveline" rend="ink" resp="ww">this</add> they took no heed : but one of them, </l><l n="371">Going by chance, at night, into the house</l><l n="372">Which at <del>this</del> <add place="aboveline" rend="ink" resp="ww" hand="dw">that</add> time was James&rsquo;s home, there learn&rsquo;d</l><l n="373">That nobody had seen him all that day:</l><l n="374">The morning came, and still, he was unheard of:</l><l n="375">The neighbours were alarm&rsquo;d, and to the Brook</l><l n="376">Some went, and some towards the Lake; ere noon</l></lg><pb><milestone n="42" unit="page"><lb><lb><lg n="26" part="F" type="verseparagraph"><l n="377">They found him at the foot of that same Rock<add place="belowline" rend="ink" resp="ww">^</add> <add place="rmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">&mdash;&sol;</add></l><l n="378">Dead, and with mangled limbs. The third day after</l><l n="379">I buried him, poor Lad, and there he lies.</l></lg></sp><sp><speaker>LEONARD.</speaker><lg n="27" type="verseparagraph"><l n="380">And that then <emph>is</emph> his grave!&mdash;Before his death</l><l n="381">You said that he saw many happy years?</l></lg></sp><sp><speaker>PRIEST.</speaker><lg n="28" type="verseparagraph"><l n="382" part="i">Aye, that he did&mdash; </l></lg></sp><sp><speaker>LEONARD.</speaker><lg n="29" type="verseparagraph"><l part="f" rend="right">And all went well with him&mdash;</l></lg></sp><sp><speaker>PRIEST.</speaker><lg n="30" type="verseparagraph"><l n="383">If he had one, the Lad had twenty homes.</l></lg></sp><sp><speaker>LEONARD.</speaker><lg n="31" type="verseparagraph"><l n="384">And you believe then, that his mind was easy&mdash;</l></lg></sp><pb><milestone unit="page" n="43"><lb><lb><sp><speaker>PRIEST.</speaker><lg n="32" type="verseparagraph"><l n="385">Yes, long before he died, he found that time</l><l n="386"><add place="lmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">&sol;:</add> Is a true friend to sorrow<del>,</del> and unless</l><l n="387">His thoughts were turn&rsquo;d on Leonard&rsquo;s luckless fortune,</l><l n="388">He talk&rsquo;d about him with a chearful love.</l></lg></sp><sp><speaker>LEONARD</speaker><lg n="33" type="verseparagraph"><l n="389">He could not come to an unhallow&rsquo;d end!</l></lg></sp><sp><speaker>PRIEST.</speaker><lg n="34" type="verseparagraph" part="I"><l n="390">Nay, God forbid!  You recollect I mention&rsquo;d</l><l n="391">A habit which disquietude and grief</l><l n="392"><add place="lmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">&sol;;</add> Had brought upon him<del>,</del> and we all conjectur&rsquo;d</l><l n="393">That, as the day was warm, he had lain down</l><l n="394">Upon the grass, and, waiting for his comrades</l><l n="395"><add place="lmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">&sol;;</add> He there had fallen asleep<del>,</del> that in his sleep</l><l n="396">He to the margin of the precipice</l><l n="397">Had walk&rsquo;d, and from the summit had fallen head-long<del>,</del> <add place="rmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">.&sol;</add></l><l n="398">And so no doubt he perish&rsquo;d : at the time,</l><l n="399">We guess, that in his hands he must have had</l></lg><pb><milestone n="44" unit="page"><lb><lb><lg n="34" part="F" type="verseparagraph"><l n="400">His Shepherd&rsquo;s staff; for midway in the cliff</l><l n="401"><add place="lmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">&sol;;</add> It had been caught<del>,</del> and there for many years</l><l n="402" part="i">It hung&mdash;and moulder&rsquo;d there.</l></lg></sp><lg n="35" type="verseparagraph"><l part="f" rend="right">The Priest here ended&mdash;</l><l n="403">The Stranger would have thank&rsquo;d him, but he felt</l><l n="404">Tears rushing in ; both left the spot in silence,</l><l n="405">And Leonard, when they reach&rsquo;d the church-yard gate,</l><l n="406">As the Priest lifted up the latch, turn&rsquo;d round,</l><l n="407">And, looking at the grave, he said, &ldquo;My Brother.&rdquo;</l><l n="408">The Vicar did not hear the words : and now,</l><l n="409">Pointing towards the Cottage, he entreated</l><l n="410">That Leonard would partake his homely fare:</l><l n="411">The other thank&rsquo;d him with a fervent voice,</l><l n="412">But added, that, the evening being calm,</l><l n="413">He would pursue his journey. So they parted.</l></lg><lg n="36" type="verseparagraph"><l n="414">It was not long ere Leonard reach&rsquo;d a grove</l><l n="415">That overhung the road : he there stopp&rsquo;d short,</l><l n="416">And, sitting down beneath the trees, review&rsquo;d</l><l n="417">All that the Priest had said : his early years</l></lg></body><pb></text><text><body><milestone n="47" unit="page"><lb><lb><lg n="2" type="stanza"><l n="9">From many Knights and many Squires</l><l n="10">The Bruce had been selected<del>,</del> <add place="rmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">;&sol;</add></l><l n="11">And Gordon, fairest of them all,</l><l n="12">By Ellen was rejected.</l><l n="13">Sad tidings to that noble Youth!</l><l n="14">For it may be proclaim&rsquo;d with truth,</l><l n="15">If Bruce hath lov&rsquo;d sincerely,</l><l n="16">The Gordon loves as dearly.</l></lg><lg n="3" type="stanza"><l n="17">But what is Gordon&rsquo;s beauteous face?</l><l n="18">And what are Gordon&rsquo;s crosses</l><l n="19">To them who sit by Kirtle&rsquo;s Braes</l><l n="20">Upon the verdant mosses?</l><l n="21">Alas that ever he was born!</l><l n="22">The Gordon, couch&rsquo;d behind a thorn,</l><l n="23">Sees them and their caressing,</l><l n="24">Beholds them bless&rsquo;d and blessing.</l></lg><pb><milestone n="48" unit="page"><lb><lb><lg n="4" type="stanza"><l n="25">Proud Gordon cannot bear the thoughts</l><l n="26">That through his brain are travelling,</l><l n="27">And, starting up, to Bruce&rsquo;s heart</l><l n="28">He launch&rsquo;d a deadly jav&rsquo;lin!</l><l n="29">Fair Ellen saw it when it came,</l><l n="30">And, stepping forth to meet the same,</l><l n="31">Did with her body cover</l><l n="32">The Youth her chosen lover.</l></lg><lg n="5" type="stanza"><l n="33">And, falling into Bruce&rsquo;s arms,</l><l n="34">Thus died the beauteous Ellen,</l><l n="35">Thus from the heart of her true-love</l><l n="36">The mortal spear repelling.</l><l n="37">And Bruce, as soon as he had slain</l><l n="38">The Gordon, sail&rsquo;d away to Spain<del>,</del> <add place="rmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">;&sol;</add></l><l n="39">And fought with rage incessant</l><l n="40">Against the Moorish Crescent.</l></lg><pb n="49"><milestone n="49" unit="page"><lb><lb><lg n="6"><l n="41"><add place="lmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">&sol;,</add> But many days<add place="belowline" rend="ink" resp="ww">^</add>and many months,</l><l n="42">And many years ensuing,</l><l n="43">This wretched Knight did vainly seek</l><l n="44">The death that he was wooing:</l><l n="45"><del>&sol;,</del> <del>So</del><add place="belowline" rend="ink" resp="ww">^</add><add hand="dw" place="aboveline" rend="ink" resp="ww">And</add> coming back across the wave,</l><l n="46">Without a groan on Ellen&rsquo;s grave</l><l n="47">His body he extended,</l><l n="48">And there his sorrow ended.</l></lg><lg n="7"><l n="49"><add place="rmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">&sol;,</add> Now ye<add place="belowline" rend="ink" resp="ww">^</add>who willingly have heard</l><l n="50">The tale I have been telling,</l><l n="51">May in Kirkonnel church-yard view</l><l n="52">The grave of lovely Ellen:</l><l n="53">By Ellen&rsquo;s side the Bruce is laid<del>,</del> <add place="rmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">;&sol;</add></l><l n="54">And, for the stone upon his head,</l><l n="55">May no rude hand deface it,</l><l n="56">And its forlorn <add place="belowline" rend="ink" resp="ww">^</add>Hic jacet.</l></lg><p><add hand="dw" place="rmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">H<hi>ic jacet</hi>,<lb>these two words<lb>in small capitals</add></p></body></text><pb><text><body><milestone n="50" unit="page"><lb><lb><head rend="ms."><add hand="dw" rend="ink" resp="ww"><del>a Reverie</del></add></head><lg n="1"><l n="1">Strange fits of passion I have known<del>,</del> <add place="rmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">:&sol;</add></l><l n="2">And I will dare to tell,</l><l n="3"><add place="lmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">&sol;L</add> But in the <del>l</del>over&rsquo;s ear alone,</l><l n="4">What once to me befel.</l></lg><lg n="2"><l n="5">When she I lov&rsquo;d, was strong and gay</l><l n="6">And like a rose in June,</l><l n="7">I to her cottage bent my way,</l><l n="8">Beneath the evening <del>m</del>oon. <add place="rmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">M&sol;</add></l></lg><lg n="3"><l n="9"><add place="lmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">&sol;M</add> Upon the <del>m</del>oon I fix&rsquo;d my eye,</l><l n="10">All over the wide lea<del>;</del> <add place="rmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">:&sol;</add></l><l n="11"><add place="lmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">&sol;H&sol;&mdash;</add> My <del>h</del>orse trudg&rsquo;d on^ and we drew nigh</l><l n="12">Those paths so dear to me.</l></lg><pb><milestone n="51" unit="page"><lb><lb><lg n="4"><l n="13">And now we reach&rsquo;d the orchard plot<del>,</del> <add place="rmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">;&sol;</add></l><l n="14">And, as we climb&rsquo;d the hill,</l><l n="15">Towards the roof of Lucy&rsquo;s cot</l><l n="16"><add place="lmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">&sol;M</add> The <del>m</del>oon descended still.</l></lg><lg n="5"><l n="17">In one of those sweet dreams I slept,</l><l n="18">Kind Nature&rsquo;s gentlest boon!</l><l n="19">And, all the while, my eyes I kept</l><l n="20">On the descending <del>m</del>oon. <add place="rmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">M&sol;</add></l></lg><lg n="6"><l n="21"><add place="lmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">&sol;H</add> My <del>h</del>orse mov&rsquo;d on; hoof after hoof</l><l n="22"><add place="rmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">&sol;,</add>He rais&rsquo;d<add place="belowline" rend="ink" resp="ww">^</add>and never stopp&rsquo;d:</l><l n="23">When down behind the cottage roof</l><l n="24"><add place="lmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">&sol;P</add> At once the <del>p</del>lanet dropp&rsquo;d.</l></lg><lg n="7"><l n="25">What fond and wayward thoughts will slide</l><l n="26">Into a Lover&rsquo;s head&mdash;</l><l n="27">&ldquo;O mercy!&rdquo; to myself I cried,</l><l n="28">&ldquo;If Lucy should be dead!&rdquo;</l></lg></body></text><pb><text><body><milestone n="52" unit="page"><lb><lb><head><emph><del>SONG. </del></emph> <add place="rmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">&sol;D</add></head><lg n="1"><l n="1">She dwelt among th&rsquo; untrodden ways</l><l n="2" rend="indent">  Beside the springs of Dove,</l><l n="3">A Maid whom there were none to praise<add place="belowline" rend="ink" resp="ww">^</add> <add place="rmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">,&sol;</add></l><l n="4" rend="indent">   And very few to love.</l></lg><lg n="2"><l n="5">A Violet by a mossy stone</l><l n="6" rend="indent">Half-hidden from the Eye!</l><l n="7"><add place="lmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">d</add> &mdash;Fair<del>,</del> as a star<add place="belowline" rend="ink" resp="ww">^</add>when only one <add place="rmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">,&sol;</add></l><l n="8" rend="indent">  Is shining in the sky!</l></lg><lg n="3" type="stanza"><l n="9">She<emph><del>liv&rsquo;d</del></emph> <add place="aboveline" hand="dw" rend="ink" resp="ww">*liv&rsquo;d</add> unknown, and few could know </l><l n="10" rend="indent">  When Lucy ceas&rsquo;d to be;</l><l n="11">But she is in her Grave, and Oh!</l><l n="12" rend="indent">  The difference to me.</l></lg><p rend="ms."><add rend="ink" resp="ww" place="pagebottom">*not in Italics</add></p></body></text><pb><text><body><milestone n="55" unit="page"><lb><lb><lg n="2" type="stanza"><l n="11">&ldquo;Dost thou presume my course to block?</l><l n="12"><add>&ldquo;</add> Off, off! or, puny Thing!</l><l n="13"><add>&ldquo;</add> I&rsquo;ll hurl thee headlong with the rock</l><l n="14"><add>&ldquo;</add> To which thy fibres cling.&rdquo;</l><l n="15">The Flood was tyrannous and strong;</l><l n="16">The patient Briar suffer&rsquo;d long,</l><l n="17">Nor did he utter groan or sigh,</l><l n="18">Hoping the danger would be pass&rsquo;d:</l><l n="19">But seeing no relief, at last</l><l n="20">He ventur&rsquo;d to reply.</l></lg><lg n="3" type="stanza"><l n="21">&ldquo;Ah!&rdquo; said the Briar, &ldquo;Blame me not!</l><l n="22"><add>&ldquo;</add> Why should we dwell in strife?</l><l n="23"><add>&ldquo;</add> We who in this, our natal spot,</l><l n="24"><add>&ldquo;</add> Once liv&rsquo;d a happy life!</l><l n="25"><add>&ldquo;</add> You stirr&rsquo;d me on my rocky bed&mdash;</l><l n="26"><add>&ldquo;</add> What pleasure thro&rsquo; my veins you spread!</l><l n="27"><add>&ldquo;</add> The Summer long from day to day</l><l n="28"><add>&ldquo;</add> My leaves you freshen&rsquo;d and bedew&rsquo;d;</l><l n="29"><add>&ldquo;</add> Nor was it common gratitude</l><l n="30"><add>&ldquo;</add> That did your cares repay.</l></lg><pb><milestone n="56" unit="page"><lb><lb><lg n="4" type="stanza"><l n="31"><add>&ldquo;</add> When Spring came on with bud and bell,</l><l n="32"><add>&ldquo;</add> Among these rocks did I</l><l n="33"><add>&ldquo;</add> Before you hang my wreath to tell</l><l n="34"><add>&ldquo;</add> That gentle days were nigh!</l><l n="35"><add>&ldquo;</add> And in the sultry summer hours</l><l n="36"><add>&ldquo;</add> I shelter&rsquo;d you with leaves and flowers;</l><l n="37"><add>&ldquo;</add> And in my leaves<add place="belowline" rend="ink" resp="ww">^</add>now shed and gone<add place="belowline" rend="ink" resp="ww">^</add> <add place="rmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">,&sol;,&sol;</add></l><l n="38"><add place="lmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">&sol;;&sol;L</add><add>&ldquo;</add>The <del>l</del>innet lodg&rsquo;d<add place="belowline" rend="ink" resp="ww">^</add>and for us two</l><l n="39"><add place="rmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">&sol;,</add><add>&ldquo;</add> Chaunted his pretty songs<add place="belowline" rend="ink" resp="ww">^</add>when you <add place="rmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">Y&sol;</add></l><l n="40"><add place="rmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> Had little voice or none.</l></lg><lg n="5" type="stanza"><l n="41"><add>&ldquo;</add> But now proud thoughts are in your breast&mdash;</l><l n="42"><add>&ldquo;</add> What grief is mine you see.</l><l n="43"><add>&ldquo;</add> Ah! would you think, ev&rsquo;n yet how blest</l><l n="44"><add>&ldquo;</add> Together we might be!</l><l n="45"><add>&ldquo;</add> Though of both leaf and flower bereft,</l><l n="46"><add>&ldquo;</add> Some ornaments to me are left&mdash;</l><l n="47"><add>&ldquo;</add> Rich store of scarlet hips is mine,</l><l n="48"><add>&ldquo;</add> With which I in my humble way</l><l n="49"><add>&ldquo;</add> Would deck you many a Winter&rsquo;s day,</l><l n="50"><add>&ldquo;</add> A happy Eglantine!&rdquo;</l></lg><pb><milestone n="57" unit="page"><lb><lg n="6" type="stanza"><l n="51">What more he said, I cannot tell.</l><l n="52">The stream came thundering down the dell<add place="belowline" rend="ink" resp="ww">^</add> <add place="rmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">,&sol;</add></l><l n="63">And gallop&rsquo;d loud and fast;</l><l n="64">I listen&rsquo;d, nor aught else could hear,</l><l n="65"><add place="belowline" rend="ink" resp="ww">^</add><add place="rmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">&mdash;</add> The Briar quak&rsquo;d<add place="belowline" rend="ink" resp="ww">^</add>and much I fear,</l><l n="66">Those accents were his last.</l></lg></body></text><pb><text><body><milestone n="58" unit="page"><lb><lb><head><emph>The OAK and the BROOM,<lb><lb><hi rend="small">A PASTORAL.</hi></emph></head><lg n="1" type="stanza"><l n="1">His simple truths did Andrew glean</l><l n="2">Beside the babbling rills;</l><l n="3">A careful student he had been</l><l n="4">Among the woods and hills.</l><l n="5"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&sol;,</add>One winter&rsquo;s night<add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add>when through the Trees</l><l n="6">The wind was thundering, on his knees</l><l n="7">His youngest born did Andrew hold:</l><l n="8">And while the rest, a ruddy quire<add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">,&sol;</add></l><l n="9">Were seated round their blazing fire,</l><l n="10">This Tale the Shepherd told.</l></lg><pb><milestone n="59" unit="page"><lb><lb><lg><l n="11">I saw a crag, a lofty stone</l><l n="12">As ever tempest beat!</l><l n="13">Out of its head an Oak had grown,</l><l n="14">A Broom out of its feet.</l><l n="15">The time was March, a chearful noon&mdash;</l><l n="16">The thaw-wind with the breath of June</l><l n="17">Breath&rsquo;d gently from the warm South-west;</l><l n="18"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&sol;,</add> When<add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add>in a voice sedate with age<add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">,&sol;</add></l><l n="19">This Oak, half giant and half sage,</l><l n="20">His neighbour thus address&rsquo;d.</l></lg><lg n="3" type="stanza"><l n="21"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add>Eight weary weeks, thro&rsquo; rock and clay,</l><l n="22"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> Along this mountain&rsquo;s edge</l><l n="23"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> The Frost hath wrought both night and day,</l><l n="24"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> Wedge driving after wedge.</l><l n="25"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&sol;!</add> <add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> Look up<del>,</del> and think, above your head</l><l n="26"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> What trouble surely will be bred;</l><l n="27"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> Last night I heard a crash&mdash;&rsquo;tis true,</l><l n="28"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> The splinters took another road&mdash;</l><l n="29"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> I see them yonder&mdash;what a load</l><l n="30"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> For such a Thing as you!</l></lg><pb><milestone n="60" unit="page"><lb><lb><lg n="4" type="stanza"><l n="31"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> You are preparing as before</l><l n="32"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> To deck your slender shape;</l><l n="33"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> And yet, just three years back&mdash;no more&mdash;</l><l n="34"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> You had a strange escape.</l><l n="35"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add>Down from yon Cliff  a fragment broke,</l><l n="36"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> It came, you know, with fire and smoke</l><l n="37 "><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> And<add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add><add hand="dw" place="aboveline" resp="ww">hitherward it  bent its way.</add> <del>hither did it bend its way.</del></l><l n="38"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> This pond&rsquo;rous <del>b</del>lock was caught by me, <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">B&sol;</add></l><l n="39"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> And o&rsquo;er your head, as you may see,</l><l n="40"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> &rsquo;Tis hanging to this day<del>.</del> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">!&sol;</add></l></lg><lg n="5" type="stanza"><l n="41"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> The Thing had better been asleep,</l><l n="42"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> Whatever thing it were,</l><l n="43"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> Or Breeze, or Bird, or <del>fleece of Sheep,</del> <add hand="dw" place="aboveline" resp="ww">Dog, or Sheep,</add></l><l n="44"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> That first did plant you there.</l><l n="45"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> For you and your green twigs decoy</l><l n="56"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> The little witless Shepherd-boy</l><l n="57"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> To come and slumber in your bower;</l><l n="58"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&sol;,</add><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> And<add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add>trust me, on some sultry noon,</l><l n="59"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> Both you and he, Heaven knows how soon!</l><l n="60"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> Will perish in one hour.</l></lg><pb><milestone n="61" unit="page"><lb><lb><lg n="6" type="stanza"><l n="51"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add>From me this friendly warning take&rdquo;&mdash;</l><l n="52">&mdash;The Broom began to doze,</l><l n="53">And thus to keep herself awake</l><l n="54">Did gently interpose.</l><l n="55"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> &ldquo; My thanks for your discourse are due;</l><l n="56"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> That it is true, and more than true,</l><l n="56"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> I know and I have known it long;</l><l n="58"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> Frail is the bond, by which we hold</l><l n="59"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> Our being, be we young or old,</l><l n="60"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> Wise, foolish, weak or strong.</l></lg><lg n="7" type="stanza"><l n="61"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> Disasters, do the best we can,</l><l n="62"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> Will reach both great and small;</l><l n="63"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> And he is oft the wisest man,</l><l n="64"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> Who is not wise at all.</l><l n="65"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> For me, why should I wish to roam?</l><l n="66"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> This spot is my paternal home,</l><l n="67"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> It is my pleasant Heritage;</l><l n="68"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> My Father many a happy year</l><l n="69"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> Here spread his careless blossoms, here</l><l n="70"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> Attain&rsquo;d a good old age.</l></lg><pb><milestone n="62" unit="page"><lb><lb><lg n="8" type="stanza"><l n="71"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> Even such as his may be my lot.</l><l n="72"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> What cause have I to haunt</l><l n="73"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> My heart with terrors? Am I not</l><l n="74"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> In truth a favor&rsquo;d plant!</l><l n="75"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> The Spring for me a garland weaves</l><l n="76"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> Of yellow flowers and verdant leaves<del>,</del><add place="rmargin" resp="ww"> ;&sol;</add></l><l n="77"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> And, when the Frost is in the sky,</l><l n="78"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> My branches are so fresh and gay</l><l n="79"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> That You might look<add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add><del>on</del> me and say<add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">at&sol;,&sol;</add></l><l n="80"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&sol;P</add> <add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> This <del>p</del>lant can never die.</l></lg><lg n="9" type="stanza"><l n="81"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&sol;B</add> <add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> The <del>b</del>utterfly, all green and gold,</l><l n="82"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> To me hath often flown,</l><l n="83"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> Here in my Blossoms to behold</l><l n="84"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> Wings lovely as his own.</l><l n="85"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> When grass is chill with rain or dew,</l><l n="86"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> Beneath my shade the mother <del>e</del>we <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">E&sol;</add></l><l n="87"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&sol;L</add> <add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> Lies with her infant <del>l</del>amb; I see</l><l n="79"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> The love, they to each other make,</l><l n="89"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> And the sweet joy, which they partake,</l><l n="90"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> It is a joy to me.&rdquo;</l></lg><pb><milestone n="63" unit="page"><lb><lb><lg n="10" type="stanza"><l n="91">Her voice was blithe, her heart was light;</l><l n="92">The Broom might have pursued</l><l n="93">Her speech, until the stars of night</l><l n="94">Their journey had renew&rsquo;d.</l><l n="95">But in the branches of the Oak</l><l n="96">Two Ravens now began to croak</l><l n="97">Their nuptial song, a gladsome air;</l><l n="98">And to her own green bower the breeze</l><l n="99">That instant brought two stripling Bees</l><l n="100">To feed and murmur there.</l></lg><lg n="11" type="stanza"><l n="101">One night the Wind came from the North</l><l n="102">And blew a furious blast<del>,</del> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">;&sol;</add></l><l n="103">At break of day I ventur&rsquo;d forth</l><l n="104">And near the Cliff I pass&rsquo;d.</l><l n="105">The storm had fall&rsquo;n upon the Oak</l><l n="106">And struck him with a mighty stroke,</l><l n="107">And whirl&rsquo;d and whirl&rsquo;d him far away;</l><l n="108">And in one hospitable Cleft</l><l n="109">The little careless Broom was left</l><l n="110">To live for many a day.</l></lg><p><add hand="dw" place="pagebottom" resp="ww">Before the above Poem Insert the <lb>&ldquo;Forsaken Indian&rdquo; from the first<lb>volume</add></p></body></text><pb><text><body><milestone n="64" unit="page"><lb><lb><head><emph>LUCY GRAY. </emph><lb><lb></head><lg n="1" type="stanza"><l n="1">Oft I had heard of Lucy Gray<del>,</del> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">;&sol;</add></l><l n="2"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&sol;,</add> And<add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add>when I cross&rsquo;d the Wild,</l><l n="3">I chanc&rsquo;d to see at break of day</l><l n="4">The solitary Child.</l></lg><lg n="2" type=""><l n="5">No Mate, no comrade Lucy knew;</l><l n="6">She dwelt on a <add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add><del>wide</del> Moor, <add hand="dw" place="rmargin" resp="ww">wide</add></l><l n="7"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&mdash;</add><add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add> The sweetest Thing that ever grew</l><l n="8">Beside a human door!</l></lg><lg n="3" type="stanza"><l n="9">You yet may spy the Fawn at play,</l><l n="10">The Hare upon the Green;</l><l n="11">But the sweet face of Lucy Gray</l><l n="12">Will never more be seen.</l></lg><pb><milestone n="65" unit="page"><lb><lb><lg n="4" type="stanza"><l n="13">&ldquo;To-night will be a stormy night<del>,</del><add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add><add place="rmargin" resp="ww">&mdash;</add></l><l n="14"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> You to the Town must go<del>,</del> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">;&sol;</add></l><l n="15"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> And take a lantern, Child, to light</l><l n="16"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> Your Mother thro&rsquo; the snow.&rdquo;</l></lg><lg n="5" type="stanza"><l n="17">&ldquo;That, Father! will I gladly do;</l><l n="18"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> &rsquo;Tis scarcely afternoon&mdash;</l><l n="19"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> The Minster-clock has just struck two,</l><l n="20"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> And yonder is the Moon.&rdquo;</l></lg><lg n="6" type="stanza"><l n="21">At this the Father rais&rsquo;d his hook</l><l n="22">And snapp&rsquo;d a faggot-band;</l><l n="23">He plied his work, and Lucy took</l><l n="24">The lantern in her hand.</l></lg><lg n="7" type="stanza"><l n="25">Not blither is the mountain roe<del>,</del> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">:&sol;</add></l><l n="26">With many a wanton stroke</l><l n="27">Her feet disperse the powd&rsquo;ry snow<add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">,&sol;</add></l><l n="28">That rises up like smoke.</l></lg><pb><milestone n="66" unit="page"><lb><lb><lg n="8"><l n="29">The storm came on before its time<del>,</del> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">:&sol;</add></l><l n="30">She wander&rsquo;d up and down<del>,</del> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">;&sol;</add></l><l n="31">And many a hill did Lucy climb<add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">,&sol;</add></l><l n="32">But never reach&rsquo;d the Town.</l></lg><lg n="9" type="stanza"><l n="33">The wretched Parents all that night</l><l n="34">Went shouting far and wide;</l><l n="35">But there was neither sound nor sight</l><l n="36">To serve them for a guide.</l></lg><lg n="10" type="stanza"><l n="37">At day-break on a hill they stood</l><l n="38">That overlook&rsquo;d the Moor;</l><l n="39"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&sol;w</add> And thence they saw the Bridge of <del>W</del>ood<add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">,&sol;</add></l><l n="40">A furlong from their door.</l></lg><lg n="11" type="stanza"><l n="41">And now they homeward turn&rsquo;d, and cry&rsquo;d</l><l n="42">&ldquo;In Heaven we all shall meet! <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">&rdquo;</add><add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add></l><l n="43"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&mdash;</add><add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add> When in the snow the Mother spied</l><l n="44">The print of Lucy&rsquo;s feet.</l></lg><pb><milestone n="67" unit="page"><lb><lb><lg n="12" type="stanza"><l n="45">Then downward from the steep hill&rsquo;s edge</l><l n="46">They track&rsquo;d the footmarks small;</l><l n="47">And through the broken hawthorn-hedge,</l><l n="48">And by the long stone-wall; </l></lg><lg n="13" type="stanza"><l n="49">And then an open field they cross&rsquo;d<del>,</del> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">:&sol;</add></l><l n="50">The marks were still the same;</l><l n="51">They track&rsquo;d them on, nor ever lost<del>,</del> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">;&sol;</add></l><l n="52">And to the Bridge they came.</l></lg><lg n="14" type="stanza"><l n="53">They follow&rsquo;d from the snowy bank</l><l n="54">The footmarks, one by one,</l><l n="55">Into the middle of the plank<del>,</del> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">;&sol;</add></l><l n="56">And further there were none.</l></lg><lg n="15"><l n="57"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&mdash;</add><add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add> Yet some maintain that to this day</l><l n="58">She is a living Child<del>,</del> <add place="lmargin" resp="ww">;&sol;</add></l><l n="59">That you may see sweet Lucy Gray</l><l n="60">Upon the lonesome Wild.</l></lg><pb><milestone n="68" unit="page"><lb><lb><lg n="16" type="stanza"><l n="61">O&rsquo;er rough and smooth she trips along,</l><l n="62">And never looks behind;</l><l n="63">And sings a solitary song</l><l n="64">That whistles in the wind.</l></lg></body></text><pb><text><body><div type=""><p>To the Printer.  Here print the Poem<lb>which follows this.<lb>Tis said that some have died for Love &amp;c</p></div><milestone n="69" unit="page"><lb><div><head><emph>The IDLE SHEPHERD-BOYS, </emph><lb><lb><hi rend="small">or</hi><lb><lb><emph>DUNGEON-GILL FORCE</emph>,*<lb><lb><hi rend="small"><emph>A PASTORAL.</emph></hi><lb></head><lg n="1" type="stanza"><head>I.</head><l n="1">The valley rings with mirth and joy<del>,</del> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">;&sol;</add></l><l n="2">Among the hills the Echoes play</l><l n="3">A never, never ending song</l><l n="4">To welcome in the May.</l><l n="5">The Magpie chatters with delight;</l></lg><note>*Gill in the dialect of Cumberland and Westmoreland is <lb>a short and for the most part<add place="belowline" resp="ww ">^</add>a steep narrow valley, with  <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">,&sol;</add><lb>a stream running through it.  <add resp="ww">&sol;</add>Force is the word univer- <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">&sol;Force</add><lb>sally employed in these dialects for Waterfall. <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">&sol;in Italics</add></note><pb n="70"><milestone n="70" unit="page"><lb><lb><l n="6">The mountain Raven&rsquo;s youngling Brood</l><l n="7">Have left the Mother and the Nest<del>,</del> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">;&sol;</add></l><l n="8">And they go rambling east and west</l><l n="9">In search of their own food<del>,</del> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">;&sol;</add></l><l n="10">Or thro&rsquo; the glittering Vapors dart</l><l n="11">In very wantonness of <del>H</del>eart. <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">h&sol;</add></l><lg n="2" type="stanza"><head>II.</head><l n="12">Beneath a rock, upon the grass,</l><l n="13">Two Boys are sitting in the sun;</l><l n="14">It seems they have no work to do<add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">,&sol;</add></l><l n="15">Or that their work is done.</l><l n="16">On pipes of sycamore they play</l><l n="17">The fragments of a Christmas Hymn<del>,</del> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">;&sol;</add></l><l n="18"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&sol;,</add> Or with that plant<add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add>which in our dale</l><l n="19">We call Stag-horn, or Fox&rsquo;s Tail<add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">,&sol;</add></l><l n="20">Their rusty Hats they trim:</l><l n="21"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&sol;,</add> And thus<add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add>as happy as the Day,</l><l n="22">Those Shepherds wear the time away.</l></lg><pb n="71"><milestone n="71" unit="page"><lb><lb><lg n="3" type="stanza"><head>III.</head><l n="23">Along the river&rsquo;s stony marge</l><l n="24"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&sol;S</add> The <del>s</del>and-lark chaunts a joyous song;</l><l n="25"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&sol;T</add> The <del>t</del>hrush is busy in the <del>W</del>ood, <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">w&sol;</add></l><l n="26">And carols loud and strong.</l><l n="27">A thousand lambs are on the rocks,</l><l n="28">All newly born! both earth and sky</l><l n="29"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&sol;;</add> Keep jubilee<del>,</del> and more than all,</l><l n="30">Those Boys with their green Coronal<del>,</del> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">;&sol;</add></l><l n="31">They never hear the cry,</l><l n="32">That plaintive cry! which up the hill</l><l n="33">Comes from the depth of Dungeon-Gill.</l></lg><lg n="4" type="stanza"><head>IV.</head><l n="34">Said Walter, leaping from the ground,</l><l n="35">&ldquo;Down to the stump of yon old yew</l><l n="36" rend="interlinear"><add hand="dw" place="aboveline" resp="ww">We&rsquo;ll for this Whistle run a race.&rdquo;</add></l><l n="36"><add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add><del>&ldquo;I&rsquo;ll run with you a race.&rdquo;&mdash;No more&mdash;</del></l><l n="37"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&mdash;</add><add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add>Away the Shepherds flew.</l><l n="38"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&sol;&mdash;</add> They leapt<del>,</del> they ran<del>,</del> and when they came <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">&mdash;&sol;</add></l></lg><pb n="72"><milestone n="72" unit="page"><lb><lb><lg n="4" part="F" type="stanza"><l n="39">Right opposite to Dungeon-Gill,</l><l n="40"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&sol;d</add> Seeing<del>,</del> that he should lose the prize,</l><l n="41">&ldquo;Stop!&rdquo; to his comrade Walter cries&mdash;</l><l n="42">James stopp&rsquo;d with no good will:</l><l n="43">Said Walter then, &ldquo;Your task is here,</l><l n="44"> <add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> &rsquo;Twill keep you working half a year.</l></lg><lg n="5" type="stanza"><head>V.</head><l n="45" rend="ms."><add hand="dw" resp="ww">&ldquo;Now cross where I shall cross&mdash;come on</add></l><l n="46" rend="ms."><add hand="dw" resp="ww"> &ldquo;And follow me where I hall lead&mdash;&rdquo;</add></l><l n="45"><del>Till you have cross&rsquo;d where I shall cross,</del></l><l n="46"><del>Say that you&rsquo;ll neither sleep nor eat.&rdquo;</del></l><l n="47">James proudly took him at his word,</l><l n="48">But did not like the <del>feat.</del> <add hand="dw" place="rmargin" resp="ww">deed.</add></l><l n="49">It was a spot, which you may see</l><l n="50">If ever you to Langdale go:</l><l n="51">Into a chasm a mighty Block</l><l n="52"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&sol;B</add> Hath fallen, and made a <del>b</del>ridge of rock<del>;</del> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">:&sol;</add></l><l n="53">The gulph is deep below<del>,</del> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">;&sol;</add></l><l n="54">And in a bason black and small</l><l n="55">Receives a lofty Waterfall.</l></lg><pb n="73"><milestone n="73" unit="page"><lb><lb><lg n="6" type="stanza"><head>VI.</head><l n="56">With staff in hand across the cleft</l><l n="57">The Challenger began his march;</l><l n="58">And now, all eyes and feet, hath gain&rsquo;d</l><l n="59">The middle of the arch.</l><l n="60">When list! he hears a piteous moan&mdash;</l><l n="61"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&sol;&mdash;</add> Again!<add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add>his heart within him dies&mdash;</l><l n="62">His pulse is stopp&rsquo;d, his breath is lost,</l><l n="63">He totters, pale as any ghost,</l><l n="64">And, looking down, he spies</l><l n="65">A Lamb, that in the pool is pent</l><l n="66">Within that black and frightful <del>r</del>ent. <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">R&sol;</add></l></lg><lg n="7" type="stanza"><head>VII.</head><l n="67">The Lamb had slipp&rsquo;d into the stream,</l><l n="68">And safe without a bruise or wound</l><l n="69">The Cataract had borne him down</l><l n="70">Into the gulph profound.</l><l n="71"><add place="rmargin" resp="ww">&sol;D</add> His <del>d</del>am had seen him when he fell,</l></lg><pb n="74"><milestone n="74" unit="page"><lb><lb><lg n="7" part="F" type="stanza"><l n="72">She saw him down the torrent borne;</l><l n="73">&sol;, And^while with all a mother&rsquo;s love</l><l n="74">She from the lofty rocks above</l><l n="75">Sent forth a cry forlorn,</l><l n="76">The Lamb, still swimming round and round^ ,&sol;</l><l n="77">Made answer to that plaintive sound.</l></lg><lg n="8" type="stanza"><head>VIII.</head><l n="78">When he had learnt, what thing it was,</l><l n="79">That sent this rueful cry;  I ween,</l><l n="80">The Boy recover&rsquo;d heart, and told</l><l n="81">The sight which he had seen.</l><l n="82">Both gladly now deferr&rsquo;d their task;</l><l n="83">Nor was there wanting other aid&mdash;</l><l n="84">A Poet, one who loves the brooks</l><l n="85">Far better than the sages&rsquo; books,</l><l n="86">By chance had thither stray&rsquo;d;</l><l n="87">And there the helpless Lamb he found</l><l n="88">By those huge rocks encompass&rsquo;d round.</l></lg><pb n="75"><milestone n="75" unit="page"><lb><lb><lg n="9" type="stanza"><head>IX.</head><l n="89">He drew it gently from the pool,</l><l n="90">And brought it forth into the light:</l><l n="91">The Shepherds met him with his <del>c</del>harge^ C ,&sol;</l><l n="92">An unexpected sight!</l><l n="93">Into their arms the Lamb they took,</l><l n="94">Said they, &ldquo;He&rsquo;s neither maim&rsquo;d nor scarr&rsquo;d&rdquo;&mdash;</l><l n="95">Then up the steep ascent they hied</l><l n="96">And placed him at his Mother&rsquo;s side;</l><l n="97">And gently did the Bard</l><l n="98">Those idle Shepherd-boys upbraid,</l><l n="99">And bade them better mind their trade.</l></lg><p> print the preceding<lb> i.e. Dungeon Gill Force</p></div></body></text><pb><text><body><milestone n="76" unit="page"><lb><lb><lb><lb><lg n="1" type="stanza"><l n="1">&rsquo;Tis said, that some have died for love:</l><l n="2">And here and there a church-yard grave is found</l><l n="3">In the cold North&rsquo;s unhallow&rsquo;d ground,</l><l n="4"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&sol;M</add> Because the wretched <del>m</del>an himself had slain,</l><l n="5">His love was such a grievous pain.</l><l n="6">And there is one whom I five years have known;</l><l n="7">He dwells alone</l><l n="8"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&sol;:</add> Upon Helvellyn&rsquo;s side<del>.</del></l><l n="9">He loved&mdash;&mdash;The pretty Barbara died,</l><l n="10">And thus he makes his moan:</l><l n="11">Three years had Barbara in her grave been laid</l><l n="12">When thus his moan he made.</l></lg><pb><milestone n="77" unit="page"><lb><lb><lg n="2" type="stanza"><l n="13"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&sol;d"</add><add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add> Oh<del>!</del> move thou Cottage from behind that oak<add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">!&sol;</add></l><l n="14">Or let the aged tree uprooted lie,</l><l n="15">That in some other way yon smoke</l><l n="16">May mount into the sky!</l><l n="17">The clouds pass on; they from the Heavens depart:</l><l n="18">I look&mdash;the sky is empty space;</l><l n="19">I know not what I trace;</l><l n="20"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&sol;,</add> But<add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add>when I cease to look, my hand is on my heart.</l></lg><lg n="3" type="stanza"><l n="21">O! what a weight is in these shades!  Ye leaves,</l><l n="22">When will that dying murmur be suppress&rsquo;d?</l><l n="23">Your sound my heart of peace bereaves,</l><l n="24">It robs my heart of rest.</l><l n="25">Thou Thrush, that singest loud and loud and free,</l><l n="26">Into yon row of willows flit,</l><l n="27">Upon that alder sit;</l><l n="28">Or sing another song, or chuse another tree<add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">.&sol;</add></l></lg><pb><milestone n="78" unit="page"><lb><lb><lg n="4" type="stanza"><l n="29"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&sol;R</add> Roll back, sweet <del>r</del>ill! back to thy mountain bounds,</l><l n="30">And there for ever be thy waters chain&rsquo;d!</l><l n="31">For thou dost haunt the air with sounds</l><l n="32">That cannot be sustain&rsquo;d;</l><l n="33">If still beneath that pine-tree&rsquo;s ragged bough</l><l n="34">Headlong yon waterfall must come,</l><l n="35">Oh let it then be dumb!&mdash;</l><l n="36"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&sol;R</add> Be any thing, sweet <del>r</del>ill, but that which thou art now.</l></lg><lg n="5" type="stanza"><l n="37">Thou Eglantine whose arch so proudly towers</l><l n="38">(Even like a rainbow spanning half the vale)</l><l n="39">Thou one fair shrub, oh! shed thy flowers,</l><l n="40">And stir not in the gale.</l><l n="41">For thus to see thee nodding in the air,</l><l n="42">To see thy arch thus stretch and bend,</l><l n="43">Thus rise and thus descend,</l><l n="44">Disturbs me, till the sight is more than I can bear.<add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add><add place="rmargin" resp="ww">&rdquo;</add></l></lg><pb><milestone n="79" unit="page"><lb><lb><lg n="6" type="stanza"><l n="45">The<del>m</del>an who makes this feverish complaint <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">M&sol;</add></l><l n="46">Is one of giant stature, who could dance</l><l n="47">Equipp&rsquo;d from head to foot in iron mail.</l><l n="48">Ah gentle Love! if ever thought was thine</l><l n="49">To store up kindred hours for me, thy face</l><l n="50">Turn from me, gentle Love<del>,</del> nor let me walk <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">!&sol;</add></l><l n="51">Within the sound of Emma&rsquo;s voice, or know</l><l n="52">Such happiness as I have known to-day.</l></lg></body></text><pb><text><body><milestone n="80" unit="page"><lb><lb><head><emph>POOR SUSAN.</emph><lb></head><lg n="1" type="stanza"><l n="1">At the corner of Wood-Street, when day-light appears,</l><l n="2">There&rsquo;s a Thrush that sings loud, it has sung for three years:</l><l n="3"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&sol;,</add> Poor Susan has pass&rsquo;d by the spot<add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add>and has heard</l><l n="4">In the silence of morning the song of the <del>b</del>ird. <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">&sol;B</add></l></lg><lg n="2" type="stanza"><l n="5">&rsquo;Tis a note of enchantment; what ails her? She sees</l><l n="6">A mountain ascending, a vision of trees;</l><l n="7">Bright volumes of vapour through Lothbury glide,</l><l n="8">And a river flows on through the vale of Cheapside.</l></lg><lg n="3" type="stanza"><l n="9">Green pastures she views in the midst of the dale,</l><l n="10">Down which she so often has tripp&rsquo;d with her pail<del>,</del> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">;&sol;</add></l><l n="11">And a single small cottage, a nest like a dove&rsquo;s,</l><l n="12"><add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add><add hand="dw" place="lmargin" resp="ww">only</add> The <del>only</del> one<add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add><del>d</del>welling on earth that she loves. <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">D&sol;</add></l></lg><pb><milestone n="81" unit="page"><lb><lb><lg n="4" type="stanza"><l n="13">She looks, and her heart is in Heaven<del>,</del> but they fade, <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">:&mdash;&sol;</add></l><l n="14">The mist and the river, the hill and the shade;</l><l n="15">The stream will not flow, and the hill will not rise,</l><l n="16">And the colours have all pass&rsquo;d away from her eyes.</l></lg><lg n="5" type="stanza"><l n="17"><del>Poor Outcast! return&mdash;to receive thee once more</del></l><l n="18"><del>The house of thy Father will open its door<del resp="ww">,</del></del> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">;&sol;</add></l><l n="19"><del>And thou once again, in thy plain russet gown,</del></l><l n="20"><del>May&rsquo;st hear the thrush sing from a tree of its own.</del></l></lg></body></text><pb><text><body><milestone n="82" unit="page"><lb><lb><head><emph>INSCRIPTION <lb><lb>For the Spot where the HERMITAGE stood on St. Herbert&rsquo;s <lb>Island, Derwent-Water.</emph></head><l n="1"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&sol;T</add> If <del>t</del>hou in the dear love of some one <del>f</del>riend <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">F&sol;</add></l><l n="2">Hast been so happy, that thou know&rsquo;st what thoughts</l><l n="3">Will, sometimes, in the happiness of love</l><l n="4">Make the heart sink, then wilt thou reverence</l><l n="5">This quiet spot.&mdash;&mdash;St. Herbert hither came<add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">,&sol;</add></l><l n="6">And here, for many seasons, from the world</l><l n="7">Remov&rsquo;d, and the affections of the world</l><l n="8">He dwelt in solitude.  <del>He living here,</del> <add hand="dw" place="aboveline" resp="ww">But he had left</add></l><l n="9"><del>This island&rsquo;s sole inhabitant! had left</del></l><l n="10">A Fellow-labourer, whom the good Man lov&rsquo;d</l><l n="11"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&sol;.&sol;A</add> As his own soul<del>;</del> <del>a</del>nd<add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add>when within his cave <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">,&sol;</add></l><l n="12">Alone he knelt before the crucifix</l><l n="13"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&sol;L</add> While o&rsquo;er the <del>l</del>ake the cataract of Lodore</l><pb><milestone n="83" unit="page"><lb><lb><l n="14">Peal&rsquo;d to his orisons, and when he pac&rsquo;d</l><l n="15">Along the beach of this small isle and thought</l><l n="16">Of his Companion, he <del>had pray&rsquo;d</del> <add place="overwrite" resp="ww">would pray</add> that both</l><l n="17">Might die in the same moment.  Nor in vain</l><l n="18">So pray&rsquo;d he:&mdash;as our Chronicles report,</l><l n="19">Though here the Hermit number&rsquo;d his last day<del>s</del>, <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">d&sol;</add></l><l n="20">Far from St. Cuthbert his beloved <del>f</del>riend, <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">F&sol;</add></l><l n="20"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&sol;M</add> Those holy <del>m</del>en both died in the same hour.</l></body></text><pb><text><body><milestone n="84" unit="page"><head><add hand="dw" resp="ww">Lines written with a pencil upon a<lb>Stone in the wall of the House (an Out-<lb>-house on the Island at Grasmere.</add><lb><lb> <del><emph>INSCRIPTION <lb><lb>For the House (an Outhouse) on the Island at Grasmere.</emph></del></head><l n="1">Rude is this Edifice, and Thou hast seen</l><l n="2">Buildings, albeit rude, that have maintain&rsquo;d</l><l n="3">Proportions more harmonious, and approach&rsquo;d</l><l n="4">To somewhat of a closer fellowship</l><l n="5">With the ideal grace.  Yet as it is</l><l n="6">Do take it in good part; for he, the poor</l><l n="7">Vitruvius of our village, had no help</l><l n="8"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&sol;C</add> From the great <del>c</del>ity; never on the leaves</l><l n="9">Of red Morocco folio saw display&rsquo;d</l><l n="10">The skeletons and pre-existing ghosts</l><l n="11">Of Beauties yet unborn, the rustic Box,</l><l n="12">Snug Cot, with Coach-house, Shed and Hermitage.</l><l n="13"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&sol;P</add> It is a homely <del>p</del>ile, yet to these walls</l><pb><milestone n="85" unit="page"><lb><lb><l n="14">The heifer comes in the snow-storm, and here</l><l n="15">The new-dropp&rsquo;d lamb finds shelter from the wind.</l><l n="16">And hither does one Poet sometimes row</l><l n="17"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&sol;P</add> His <del>p</del>innace, a small vagrant <del>b</del>arge, up-piled <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">B&sol;</add></l><l n="18">With plenteous store of heath and wither&rsquo;d fern,</l><l n="19"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">(</add><add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add> A lading which he with his sickle cuts</l><l n="21">Among the mountains, <add resp="ww">)</add><add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add>  and beneath this roof</l><l n="22">He makes his summer couch, and here at noon</l><l n="23">Spreads out his limbs, while, yet <del>unborn</del><add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add><add hand="dw" place="aboveline" resp="ww">unshorn</add>, the <del>s</del>heep <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">S&sol;</add></l><l n="24">Panting beneath the burthen of their wool</l><l n="25">Lie round him, even as if they were a part</l><l n="26"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&sol;H</add> Of his own <del>h</del>ousehold: nor, while from his bed</l><l n="27">He through that door-place looks toward the lake</l><l n="28">And to the stirring breezes, does he want</l><l n="29">Creations lovely as the work of sleep,</l><l n="30">Fair sights, and visions of romantic joy.</l></body></text><pb><text><body><milestone n="86" unit="page"><lb><lb><head><emph>To a SEXTON.</emph></head><lg n="1" type="stanza"><l n="1">Let thy wheel-barrow alone.</l><l n="2">Wherefore, Sexton, piling still</l><l n="3"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&sol;B</add> In thy <del>b</del>one-house bone on bone?</l><l n="4">&rsquo;Tis already like a hill</l><l n="5">In a field of battle made,</l><l n="6">Where three thousand skulls are laid.</l><l n="7">&mdash;&mdash;These died in peace each with the other,</l><l n="8">Father, Sister, Friend, and Brother.</l></lg><lg n="2" type="stanza" part="I"><l n="9">Mark the spot to which I point!</l><l n="10">From this platform eight feet square</l><l n="11">Take not even a finger-joint:</l><l n="12">Andrew&rsquo;s whole fire-side is there.</l></lg><pb n="94"><milestone n="87" unit="page"><lb><lb><lg n="2" part="F" type="stanza"><l n="13">Here, alone, before thine eyes,</l><l n="14">Simon&rsquo;s sickly Daughter lies<add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">,&sol;</add></l><l n="15">From weakness, now, and pain defended,</l><l n="16">Whom he twenty winters tended.</l></lg><lg n="3" type="stanza"><l n="17">Look but at the gardener&rsquo;s pride<del>,</del> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">&mdash;&sol;</add></l><l n="18">How he glories, when he sees</l><l n="19"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&sol;L</add> Roses, <del>l</del>ilies, side by side,</l><l n="20">Violets in families<del>.</del> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">!&sol;</add></l><l n="21">By the heart of Man, his tears,</l><l n="22">By his hopes and by his fears,</l><l n="23">Thou, old Grey-beard! art the Warden</l><l n="24">Of a far superior garden.</l></lg><lg n="4" part="I" type="stanza"><l n="25">Thus then, each to other dear,</l><l n="26">Let them all in quiet lie,</l><l n="27">Andrew there and Susan here,</l><l n="28">Neighbours in mortality.</l></lg><pb n="95"><milestone n="88" unit="page"><lb><lb><lg n="4" part="F" type="stanza"><l n="29"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&sol;,</add> And<add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add>should I live through sun and rain</l><l n="30">Seven widow&rsquo;d years without my Jane,</l><l n="31">O Sexton, do not then remove her,</l><l n="32">Let one grave hold the Lov&rsquo;d and Lover!</l></lg></body></text><pb><text><body><milestone n="89" unit="page"><lb><lb><head><emph>ANDREW  JONES. </emph><lb></head><lg n="1" type="stanza"><l n="1"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> I hate that Andrew Jones: he&rsquo;ll breed</l><l n="2"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> His children up to waste and pillage.</l><l n="3"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&sol;,</add><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> I wish the press-gang<add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add> or the drum</l><l n="4"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&sol;,</add> <add hand="ww" place="aboveline" resp="ww">would</add><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add><add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add> With its <del>tantara sound </del><add hand="ww" place="aboveline" resp="ww">rattling </add><add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add><add hand="ww" place="aboveline" resp="ww">music</add>  would come<del>,</del> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">d&sol;</add></l><l n="5">And sweep him from the village! <add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add><add place="rmargin" resp="ww">&rdquo;</add></l></lg><lg n="2" type="stanza"><l n="6">I said not this, because he loves</l><l n="7">Through the long day to swear and tipple;</l><l n="8">But for the poor dear sake of one</l><l n="9">To whom a foul deed he had done,</l><l n="10">A friendless Man, a travelling Cripple!</l></lg><pb n="90"><milestone n="90" unit="page"><lb><lb><lg n="3" type="stanza"><l n="11">For this poor crawling helpless wretch</l><l n="12">Some Horseman who was passing by<del>,</del> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">d&sol;</add></l><l n="13">A penny on the ground had thrown;</l><l n="14">But the poor Cripple was alone</l><l n="15">And could not stoop&mdash;no help was nigh.</l></lg><lg n="4" type="stanza"><l n="16">Inch-thick the dust lay on the ground<add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">,&sol;</add></l><l n="17">For it had long been droughty weather :</l><l n="18">So with his staff the Cripple wrought</l><l n="19">Among the dust till he had brought</l><l n="20">The halfpennies together.</l></lg><lg n="5" type="stanza"><l n="21">It chanc&rsquo;d that Andrew pass&rsquo;d that way</l><l n="22">Just at that time; and there he found</l><l n="23">The Cripple in the mid-day heat</l><l n="24">Standing alone, and at his feet</l><l n="25">He saw the penny on the ground.</l></lg><pb n="91"><milestone n="91" unit="page"><lb><lb><lg n="6" type="stanza"><l n="26">He <add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add><del>stopp&rsquo;d</del><add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add><add hand="dw" place="aboveline" resp="ww">stoop&rsquo;d&mdash;</add> and took the penny up:</l><l n="27">And when the Cripple nearer drew,</l><l n="28">Quoth Andrew, &ldquo;Under half-a-crown,</l><l n="29"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> What a man finds is all his own,</l><l n="30"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> And so, my Friend, good day to you.&rdquo;</l></lg><lg n="7" type="stanza"><l n="31">And<emph>hence</emph> I said, that Andrew&rsquo;s boys</l><l n="32">Will all be train&rsquo;d to waste and pillage;</l><l n="33">And wish&rsquo;d the press-gang, or the drum</l><l n="34"><del>With its tantara sound, would</del> <add place="aboveline" hand="dw" resp="ww">Would with its rattling music come</add></l><l n="35">And sweep him from the village!</l></lg></body></text><pb><text><body><milestone n="92" unit="page"><lb><p>This Poem not to be<lb>printed here.</p><head><emph>The TWO THIEVES, <lb><lb>Or the last Stage of AVARICE. <lb></emph></head><lg n="1" type="stanza"><l n="1">Oh now that the genius of Bewick were mine<add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">,&sol;</add></l><l n="2">And the skill which he learn&rsquo;d on the Banks of the Tyne<del>;</del> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">!&sol;</add></l><l n="3">When the Muses might deal with me just as they chose<add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">,&sol;</add></l><l n="4">For I&rsquo;d take my last leave both of verse and of prose.</l></lg><lg n="2" type="stanza"><l n="5">What feats would I work with my magical hand!</l><l n="6">Book-learning and books should be banish&rsquo;d the land<add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">:&sol;</add></l><l n="7">And for hunger and thirst and such troublesome calls<add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">!&sol;</add></l><l n="8"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&sol;A</add> Every <del>a</del>le-house should then have a feast on its walls.</l></lg><pb rend="93"><milestone n="93" unit="page"><lb><lb><lg n="3" type="stanza"><l n="9">The Traveller would hang his wet clothes on a chair<add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">;&sol;</add></l><l n="10">Let them smoke, let them burn, not a straw would he care<del>,</del> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">;&sol;</add></l><l n="11">For the Prodigal Son, Joseph&rsquo;s Dream and his Sheaves,</l><l n="12">Oh what would they be to my tale of two Thieves!</l></lg><lg n="4" type="stanza"><l n="13">Little Dan is unbreech&rsquo;d, he is three birth-days old<del>,</del> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">;&sol;</add></l><l n="14">His Grandsire that age more than thirty times told<del>,</del> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">;&sol;</add></l><l n="15"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">\</add> There<del>&rsquo;s</del> <add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add><add hand="dw" place="aboveline" resp="ww">are</add> ninety good seasons of fair and foul weather</l><l n="16">Between them, and both go a stealing together.</l></lg><lg n="5" type="stanza"><l n="17">With chips is the Carpenter strewing his floor?</l><l n="18">Is a cart-load of peats at an old Woman&rsquo;s door?</l><l n="19">Old Daniel his hand to the treasure will slide,</l><l n="20">And his Grandson&rsquo;s as busy at work by his side.</l></lg><lg n="6"><l n="21">Old Daniel begins, he stops short<add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add> and his eye <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">&mdash;&sol;</add></l><l n="22">Through the lost look of dotage is cunning and sly.</l><l n="23">&rsquo;Tis a look which at this time is hardly his own,</l><l n="24">But tells a plain tale of the days that are flown.</l></lg><pb n="94"><milestone n="94" unit="page"><lb><lb><lg n="7" type="stanza"><l n="25">Dan once had a heart which was mov&rsquo;d by the wires</l><l n="26">Of manifold pleasures and many desires:</l><l n="27">And what if he cherish&rsquo;d his purse? &rsquo;Twas no more</l><l n="28">Than treading a path trod by thousands before.</l></lg><lg n="8" type="stanza"><l n="29"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&sol;;</add> &rsquo;Twas a path trod by thousands<del>,</del> but Daniel is one</l><l n="30">Who went something farther than others have gone<del>;</del> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">:&sol;</add></l><l n="31">And now with old Daniel you see how it fares<add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">;&sol;</add></l><l n="32">You see to what end he has brought his grey hairs.</l></lg><lg n="9" type="stanza"><l n="33"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&sol;P &sol;:</add> The <del>p</del>air sally forth hand in hand<del>;</del> ere the sun</l><l n="34">Has peer&rsquo;d o&rsquo;er the beeches their work is begun:</l><l n="35"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&sol;,</add> And yet<add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add>into whatever sin they may fall,</l><l n="36">This Child but half knows it and that not at all.</l></lg><lg n="10" type="stanza"><l n="37">They hunt through the street with deliberate tread,</l><l n="37">And each in his turn is both leader and led;</l><l n="39"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&sol;,</add> And<add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add>wherever they carry their plots and their wiles,</l><l n="40">Every face in the village is dimpled with smiles.</l></lg><pb n="95"><milestone n="95" unit="page"><lb><lb><lg n="11" type="stanza"><l n="41">Neither check&rsquo;d by the rich nor the needy they roam<del>,</del> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">;&sol;</add></l><l n="42">For grey-headed Dan has a daughter at home<del>;</del> ,&sol;</l><l n="43">Who will gladly repair all the damage that&rsquo;s done<del>,</del> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">;&sol;</add></l><l n="44">And three, were it ask&rsquo;d, would be render&rsquo;d for one.</l></lg><lg n="12"><l n="45">Old Man! whom so oft I with pity have ey&rsquo;d,</l><l n="46">I love thee and love the sweet <del>b</del>oy at thy side: <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">B&sol;</add></l><l n="47">Long yet may&rsquo;st thou live, for a teacher we see</l><l n="48">That lifts up the veil of our nature in thee.</l></lg></body></text><pb n="96"><text><body><milestone n="96" unit="page"><lb><lb><p>This Poem not to be printed<lb>here.</p><lg n="1" type="verseparagraph"><l n="1">A whirl-blast from behind the hill</l><l n="2">Rush&rsquo;d o&rsquo;er the wood with startling sound:</l><l n="3">Then all at once the air was still,</l><l n="4">And showers of hail-stones patter&rsquo;d round.</l><l n="5">Where leafless Oaks tower&rsquo;d high above,</l><l n="6">I sate within an undergrove</l><l n="7">Of tallest hollies, tall and green<del>,</del> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">;&sol;</add></l><l n="8">A fairer bower was never seen.</l><l n="9">From year to year the spacious floor</l><l n="10">With wither&rsquo;d leaves is cover&rsquo;d o&rsquo;er,</l><l n="11">You could not lay a hair between:</l><l n="12">And all the year the bower is green.</l><l n="13">But see! where&rsquo;er the hailstones drop</l><l n="14">The wither&rsquo;d leaves all skip and hop,</l><l n="15">There&rsquo;s not a breeze&mdash;no breath of air&mdash;</l><l n="16">Yet here, and there, and every where</l><pb n="97"><milestone n="97" unit="page"><lb><lb><l n="17">Along the floor, beneath the shade</l><l n="18">By those embowering hollies made,</l><l n="19">The leaves in myriads jump and spring,</l><l n="20">As if with pipes and music rare</l><l n="21">Some Robin Good-fellow were there,</l><l n="22">And all those leaves, that jump and spring,</l><l n="23">Were each a joyous, living thing.</l></lg><lg n="2" type="stanza"><l n="24">Oh! grant me Heaven a heart at ease<add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">,&sol;</add></l><l n="25">That I may never cease to find,</l><l n="26">Even in appearances like these</l><l n="27">Enough to nourish and to stir my mind!</l></lg></body></text><pb n="98"><text><body><milestone n="98" unit="page"><lb><lb><head><emph>S O N G </emph><lb><lb><hi rend="small">for the</hi><lb><lb><emph>WANDERING JEW. </emph></head><lg n="1" type="stanza"><l n="1">Though the torrents from their fountains</l><l n="2">Roar down many a craggy steep,</l><l n="3">Yet they find among the mountains</l><l n="4">Resting-places calm and deep.</l></lg><lg n="2" type="stanza"><l n="5">Though almost with eagle pinion</l><l n="6">O&rsquo;er the rocks the Chamois roam,</l><l n="7">Yet he has some small dominion</l><l n="8"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&sol;, &sol;,</add> Which<add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add>no doubt<add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add>he calls his home.</l></lg><lg n="3"><l n="9">If on windy days the Raven</l><l n="10">Gambol like a dancing skiff,</l><l n="11">Not the less he loves his haven</l><l n="12">On the bosom of the cliff.</l></lg></body></text><pb n="103"><text><body><milestone n="103" unit="page"><lb><lb><head><emph>R U T H.</emph></head><lg n="1" type="stanza"><l n="1">When Ruth was left half desolate,</l><l n="2">Her Father took another Mate;</l><l n="3"><add hand="dw" place="lmargin" resp="ww">Ruth</add> And <del>so</del> <add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add><add place="aboveline" resp="ww">Ruth</add>, not seven years old,</l><l n="4"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">A</add> <del>The</del> A slighted Child at her own will</l><l n="5">Went wandering over dale and hill<add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">,&sol;</add></l><l n="6">In thoughtless freedom bold.</l></lg><lg n="2" type="stanza"><l n="7">And she had made a <del>p</del>ipe of straw<add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">P&sol; ,&sol;</add></l><l n="8">And from that oaten <del>p</del>ipe could draw <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">P&sol;</add></l><l n="9">All And sounds of winds and floods;</l><l n="10"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&sol;B</add> Had built a <del>b</del>ower upon the green,</l><l n="11">As if she from her birth had been</l><l n="12">An Infant of the woods.</l></lg><lg n="3" type="stanza"><l><add hand="dw" resp="ww">Beneath her Father&rsquo;s roof, alone</add></l><l><add hand="dw" resp="ww">She seem&rsquo;d to live; her thoughts her own;</add></l><l><add hand="dw" resp="ww">Herself her own delight:</add></l><l><add hand="dw" resp="ww">Pleas&rsquo;d with herself, nor sad nor gay,</add></l><l><add hand="dw" resp="ww">She pass&rsquo;d her time: and in this way</add></l><l><add hand="dw" resp="ww">Grew up <del>in</del> to Woman&rsquo;s height.</add></l></lg><pb n="104"><milestone n="104" unit="page"><lb><lb><lg n="3" type="stanza"><l n="13">There came a Youth from Georgia&rsquo;s shore<del>,</del> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">&mdash;&sol;</add></l><l n="14">A military Casque he wore</l><l n="15">With splendid feathers drest;</l><l n="16">He brought them from the Cherokees;</l><l n="17">The feathers nodded in the breeze</l><l n="18">And made a gallant crest.</l></lg><lg n="4" type="stanza"><l n="19">From Indian blood you deem him sprung:</l><l n="20">Ah no! he spake the English tongue<add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">,&sol;</add></l><l n="21">And bare a Soldier&rsquo;s name;</l><l n="22"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&sol;,</add> And<add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add>when America was free</l><l n="23">From battle and from jeopardy<add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">,&sol;</add></l><l n="24">He cross the ocean came.</l></lg><lg n="5" type="stanza"><l n="25">With hues of genius on his cheek</l><l n="26">In finest tones the Youth could speak.</l><l n="27">&mdash;While he was yet a Boy</l><l n="28">The moon, the glory of the sun,</l><l n="29">And streams that murmur as they run</l><l n="30">Had been his dearest joy.</l></lg><pb n="105"><milestone n="105" unit="page"><lb><lb><lg n="6" type="stanza"><l n="31">He was a lovely Youth! I guess</l><l n="32">The panther in the wilderness</l><l n="33">Was not so fair as he;</l><l n="34">And when he chose to sport and play,</l><l n="35">No dolphin ever was so gay</l><l n="36">Upon the tropic sea.</l></lg><lg n="7" type="stanza"><l n="37">Among the Indians he had fought<del>,</del> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">;&sol;</add></l><l n="38">And with him many tales he brought</l><l n="39">Of pleasure and of fear<del>,</del> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">;&sol;</add></l><l n="40">Such tales as told to any Maid</l><l n="41">By such a Youth in the green shade</l><l n="42">Were perilous to hear.</l></lg><lg n="8" type="stanza"><l n="43">He told of Girls, a happy rout<del>,</del> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">!&sol;</add></l><l n="44">Who quit their fold with dance and shout</l><l n="45">Their pleasant Indian Town</l><l n="46">To gather strawberries all day long,</l><l n="47">Returning with a choral song</l><l n="48">When day-light is gone down.</l></lg><pb n="106"><milestone n="106" unit="page"><lb><lb><lg n="9" type="stanza"><l n="49">He spake of plants divine and strange</l><l n="50"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&sol;hour</add> That ev&rsquo;ry<add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add><del>day</del> their blossoms change,</l><l n="51">Ten thousand lovely hues!</l><l n="52">With budding, fading, faded flowers</l><l n="53">They stand the wonder of the bowers</l><l n="54">From morn to evening dews.</l></lg><l rend="ms."><add resp="ww">Of march & ambush siege &</add></l><lg n="10" type="stanza"><l n="55">He told of the Magnolia,&dagger; spread</l><l n="56">High as a cloud, high over head!</l><l n="57">The Cypress and her spire,</l><l n="58"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&sol;&mdash;</add> <add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add>Of *flowers that with one scarlet gleam</l><l n="59">Cover a hundred leagues and seem</l><l n="60">To set the hills on fire.</l></lg><note>&dagger;Magnolia grandiflora.</note><note>*The splendid appearance of these scarlet flowers, which <lb>are scattered with such profusion over the Hills in the <lb>Southern parts of North America is frequently mentioned <lb>by Bartram in his Travels.</note><pb rend=""><lg><l><add hand="dw" resp="ww">Whatever in those climes I found</add></l><l><add hand="dw" resp="ww"><add hand="dw" resp="ww">Irregular in sight or sound</add></add></l><l><add hand="dw" resp="ww">Did to my mind impart</add></l><l><add hand="dw" resp="ww">A kindred impulse, seem&rsquo;d allied</add></l><l><add hand="dw" resp="ww">To my own powers & justified</add></l><l><add hand="dw" resp="ww">The workings of my heart.</add></l></lg><lg><l><add hand="dw" resp="ww">Nor less to feed unhallow&rsquo;d thought</add></l><l><add hand="dw" resp="ww">The beauteous forms of Nature wrought</add></l><l><add hand="dw" resp="ww">Fair trees and lovely flowers</add></l><l><add hand="dw" resp="ww">The breezes their own languor lent</add></l><l><add hand="dw" resp="ww">The stars had feelings which they sent</add></l><l><add hand="dw" resp="ww">Into those magic bowers</add></l></lg><lg><l><add hand="dw" resp="ww">If in my worst pursuits I ween</add></l><l><add hand="dw" resp="ww">That often there did intervene</add></l><l><add hand="dw" resp="ww">Pure hopes of high intent</add></l><l><add hand="dw" resp="ww">My passions amid forms so fair</add></l><l><add hand="dw" resp="ww">And stately, wanted not their share</add></l><l><add hand="dw" resp="ww">Of noble sentiment.</add></l></lg><lg><l><add hand="dw" resp="ww">So was it then <del>an</del> and so i s now:</add></l><l><add hand="dw" resp="ww">For, Ruth, with thee I know not how</add></l><l><add hand="dw" resp="ww">I feel my spirit burn</add></l><l><add hand="dw" resp="ww">Even as the East when day comes forth</add></l><pb><l><add hand="dw" resp="ww">The <del>daylight</del> <add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add><add hand="dw" place="aboveline" resp="ww">morning</add> doth return.</add></l></lg><lg><l><add hand="dw" resp="ww">It is a purer, better mind</add></l><l><add hand="dw" resp="ww">O Maiden, innocent and kind!</add></l><l><add hand="dw" resp="ww">What sights I <emph>might</emph> have seen!</add></l><l><add hand="dw" resp="ww">Even now upon my eyes they break</add></l><l><add hand="dw" resp="ww">And <del>thenthe youth</del> <add place="aboveline">he again</add> began to speak</add></l><l><add hand="dw" resp="ww">Of Lands where he had been.</add></l></lg><lg><l><add hand="dw" resp="ww">He told of the Magnolia, spread</add></l><l><add hand="dw" resp="ww">High as a cloud, high over head;</add></l><l><add hand="dw" resp="ww">The Cypress and her spire;</add></l><l><add hand="dw" resp="ww">&mdash;Of flowers that with one scarlet g</add></l><l><add hand="dw" resp="ww">Cover a hundred leagues and seem</add></l><l><add hand="dw" resp="ww">To set the hills on fire.</add></l></lg><pb n="107"><milestone n="107" unit="page"><lb><lb><lg type="stanza" n="11"><l n="61">The Youth of green Savannahs spake,</l><l n="62">And many an endless<add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add>endless lake<add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">,&sol; ,&sol;</add></l><l n="63">With all its fairy crowds</l><l n="64"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&sol;,</add> Of islands<add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add>that together lie</l><l n="65">As quietly as spots of sky</l><l n="66">Among the evening clouds:</l></lg><lg n="12" type="stanza"><l n="67">And then he said, &ldquo;How sweet it were</l><l n="68">A fisher or a hunter there,</l><l n="69">A gardener in the shade,</l><l n="70">Still wandering with an easy mind</l><l n="71">To build a household fire<add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add>and find <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">,&sol;</add></l><l n="72">A home in every glade.</l></lg><lg n="13" type="stanza"><l n="73">What days and what sweet years! Ah me!</l><l n="74"> Our life were life indeed, with thee</l><l n="75">So pass&rsquo;d in quiet bliss,</l><l n="76">And all the while&rdquo; said he &ldquo;to know</l><l n="77">That we were in a world of woe,</l><l n="78">On such an earth as this!</l></lg><pb n="108"><milestone n="108" unit="page"><lb><lb><lg n="14" type="stanza"><l n="79">And then he sometimes interwove</l><l n="80">Dear thoughts about a Father&rsquo;s love,</l><l n="81">&ldquo;For there,&rdquo; said he, &ldquo;are spun</l><l n="82">Around the heart such tender ties<add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">,&sol;</add></l><l n="83">That our own children to our eyes</l><l n="84">Are dearer than the sun.</l></lg><lg n="15" type="stanza"><l n="85">Sweet Ruth! and could you go with me</l><l n="86">My helpmate in the woods to be,</l><l n="87">Our shed at night to rear;</l><l n="88">Or run, my own adopted <del>b</del>ride, <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">B</add></l><l n="89"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">H</add> A sylvan <del>h</del>untress at my side</l><l n="90">And drive the flying deer.</l></lg><lg n="16" type="stanza"><l n="91">Beloved Ruth!&rdquo; No more he said<add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">.&sol;</add></l><l n="92">Sweet Ruth alone at midnight shed</l><l n="93">A solitary tear,</l><l n="94">She thought again&mdash;and did agree</l><l n="95">With him to sail across the sea,</l><l n="96">And drive the flying deer.</l></lg><pb n="109"><milestone n="109" unit="page"><lb><lb><lg n="17" type="stanza"><l n="97">&ldquo;And now, as fitting is and right,</l><l n="98">We in the Church our faith will plight,</l><l n="99">A Husband and a Wife.&rdquo;</l><l n="100">Even so they did; and I may say</l><l n="101">That to sweet Ruth that happy day</l><l n="102">Was more than human life.</l></lg><lg n="18" type="stanza"><l n="103">Through dream and vision did she sink,</l><l n="104">Delighted all the while to think</l><l n="105"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&sol;,</add> That<add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add>on those lonesome floods<add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">,&sol;</add></l><l n="106">And green Savannahs<add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add>she should share <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">,&sol;</add></l><l n="107">His board with lawful joy, and bear</l><l n="108">His name in the wild woods.</l></lg><lg n="19" type="stanza"><l n="109">But, as you have before been told,</l><l n="110">This Stripling, sportive<add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add>gay<add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add>and bold, <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">,&sol; ,&sol;</add></l><l n="111">And, with his dancing crest,</l><l n="112">So beautiful, through savage lands</l><l n="113">Had roam&rsquo;d about with vagrant bands</l><l n="114">Of Indians in the West.</l></lg><pb n="110"><milestone n="110" unit="page"><lb><lb><lg n="20" type="stanza"><l n="115">The wind, the tempest roaring high,</l><l n="116">The tumult of a tropic sky</l><l n="117">Might well be dangerous food</l><l n="118">For him, a Youth to whom was given</l><l n="119">So much of earth so much of Heaven,</l><l n="120">And such impetuous blood.</l></lg><lg n="21" type="stanza"><l n="121"><add place="rmargin" resp="ww">&sol;</add>Whatever in those climes <del>he</del> <add place="aboveline" resp="ww">I</add> found</l><l n="122">Irregular in sight or sound</l><l n="123">Did to his mind impart</l><l n="124">A kindred impulse, seem&rsquo;d allied</l><l n="125">To his own powers, and justified</l><l n="126">The workings of his heart.</l></lg><lg n="22" type="stanza"><l n="127">Nor less to feed <del>voluptuous</del> <add hand="dw" place="aboveline" resp="ww">unhallow&rsquo;d </add>thought</l><l n="128">The beauteous forms of Nature wrought,</l><l n="129">Fair trees and lovely flowers;</l><l n="130">The breezes their own languor lent<del>,</del> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">;&sol;</add></l><l n="131">The stars had feelings which they sent</l><l n="132">Into those magic bowers.</l></lg><pb n="111"><milestone n="111" unit="page"><lb><lb><lg n="23" type="stanza"><l n="133">Yet, in his worst pursuits, I ween,</l><l n="134">That sometimes there did intervene</l><l n="135">Pure hopes of high intent:</l><l n="136"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&sol;,</add> <del>For passions link&rsquo;d to</del><add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add><add place="aboveline" resp="ww">My passions amid</add> forms so fair</l><l n="137">And stately, <del>needs must have</del> <add place="aboveline" resp="ww">sometimes had </add>their share</l><l n="138">Of noble sentiment.</l></lg><lg n="24" type="stanza"><l n="139"><del>But ill he liv&rsquo;d</del><add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add><add place="aboveline" resp="ww">Ill did he live</add>, much evil saw</l><l n="139" rend="ms."><add place="belowline" resp="ww">Ill did he live much evil saw</add></l><l n="140">With men to whom no better law</l><l n="141">Nor better life was known;</l><l n="142">Deliberately and undeceiv&rsquo;d</l><l n="143">Those wild men&rsquo;s vices he receiv&rsquo;d,</l><l n="144">And gave them back his own.</l></lg><lg n="25" type="stanza"><l n="145">His genius and his moral frame</l><l n="146">Were thus impair&rsquo;d, and he became</l><l n="147">The slave of low desires;</l><l n="148"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&sol;M</add> A <del>m</del>an who without self-controul</l><l n="149">Would seek what the degraded soul</l><l n="150">Unworthily admires.</l></lg><pb n="112"><milestone n="112" unit="page"><lb><lb><lg n="26" type="stanza"><l n="151">And yet he with no feign&rsquo;d delight</l><l n="152">Had woo&rsquo;d the Maiden, day and night</l><l n="153">Had lov&rsquo;d her, night and morn;</l><l n="154">What could he less than love a Maid</l><l n="155">Whose heart with so much nature play&rsquo;d<add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">?&sol;</add></l><l n="156"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&sol;.</add> So kind and so forlorn<del>?</del></l></lg><lg n="27" type="stanza"><l n="157">But now the pleasant dream was gone<del>,</del> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">;&sol;</add></l><l n="158">No hope, no wish remain&rsquo;d, not one,</l><l n="159">They stirr&rsquo;d him now no more<del>,</del> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">;&sol;</add></l><l n="160">New objects did new pleasure give,</l><l n="161">And once again he wish&rsquo;d to live</l><l n="162">As lawless as before.</l></lg><lg n="28" type="stanza"><l n="163"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&sol;,</add>Meanwhile<add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add>as thus with him it fared,</l><l n="164">They for the voyage were prepared</l><l n="165">And went to the sea-shore<del>,</del> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">;&sol;</add></l><l n="166">But, when they thither came, the Youth</l><l n="167">Deserted his poor Bride, and Ruth</l><l n="168">Could never find him more.</l></lg><pb n="113"><milestone n="113" unit="page"><lb><lb><lg n="29" type="stanza"><l n="169">&ldquo;God help thee Ruth!&rdquo;&mdash;Such pains she had</l><l n="170">That she in half a year was mad</l><l n="171">And in a prison hous&rsquo;d<del>,</del> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">;&sol;</add></l><l n="172">And there, exulting in her wrongs,</l><l n="173">Among the music of her songs</l><l n="174">She fearfully carouz&rsquo;d.</l></lg><lg n="30" type="stanza"><l n="175">Yet sometimes milder hours she knew,</l><l n="176">Nor wanted sun, nor rain, nor dew,</l><l n="177">Nor pastimes of the May,</l><l n="178"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&mdash;</add><add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add>They all were with her in her cell<del>,</del> <add place="lmargin" resp="ww">;&sol;</add></l><l n="179">And a wild brook with chearful knell</l><l n="180">Did o&rsquo;er the pebbles play.</l></lg><lg n="31" type="stanza"><l n="181">When Ruth three seasons thus had lain</l><l n="182">There came a respite to her pain,</l><l n="183">She from her prison fled;</l><l n="184">But of the Vagrant none took thought<del>,</del> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">;&sol;</add></l><l n="185">And where it liked her best she sought</l><l n="186">Her shelter and her bread.</l></lg><pb n="114"><milestone n="114" unit="page"><lb><lb><lg n="32" type="stanza"><l n="187">Among the fields she breath&rsquo;d again:</l><l n="188">The master-current of her brain</l><l n="189">Ran permanent and free<del>,</del> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">;&sol;</add></l><l n="190"><del>And to the pleasant</del><add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add><add place="aboveline" resp="ww">And coming to the</add> Banks of Tone*</l><l n="191"><del>She took her way, to</del><add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add><add place="aboveline" resp="ww">There did she rest &</add> dwell alone</l><l n="192">Under the greenwood tree.</l></lg><lg n="33"><l n="193"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">pain</add><add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add>The engines of her<add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add><del>grief</del>, the tools</l><l n="194">That shap&rsquo;d her sorrow, rocks and pools,</l><l n="195">And airs that gently stir</l><l n="196">The vernal leaves, she loved them still,</l><l n="197">Nor ever tax&rsquo;d them with the ill</l><l n="198">Which had been done to her.</l></lg><note>*The Tone is a River of Somersetshire<add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add>at no great dis- <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">,&sol;</add><lb>tance from the Quantock Hills. These Hills, which <lb>are alluded to a few Stanzas below, are extremely beau-<lb>tiful, and in most places richly covered with Coppice <lb>woods.</note><pb n="115"><milestone n="115" unit="page"><lb><lb><lg n="34"><l n="199">A Barn her <emph>winter</emph> bed supplies<del>,</del> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">;&sol;</add></l><l n="200">But till the warmth of summer skies</l><l n="201">And summer days is gone,</l><l n="202">(And in this tale we all agree)</l><l n="203">She sleeps beneath the greenwood tree,</l><l n="204">And other home hath none.</l></lg><p>X</p><lg n="35"><l n="205">If she is press&rsquo;d by want of food</l><l n="206">She from her dwelling in the wood</l><l n="207">Repairs to a road side<del>,</del> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">;&sol;</add></l><l n="208">And there she begs at one steep place,</l><l n="209">Where up and down with easy pace</l><l n="210">The horsemen-travellers ride.</l></lg><lg n="31"><l n="211"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&sol;P</add> That oaten <del>p</del>ipe of hers is mute<add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">,&sol;</add></l><l n="212"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&sol;;</add> Or thrown away<del>,</del> but with a flute</l><l n="213">Her loneliness she cheers<del>;</del> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">.&sol;</add></l><l n="214">This flute made of a hemlock stalk</l><l n="215">At evening in his homeward walk</l><l n="216">The Quantock Woodman hears.</l></lg><lg rend="ms."><l><add hand="dw" resp="ww">*The Neighbours grieve for her, & say</add></l><l><add hand="dw" resp="ww">That she will, long before her day,</add></l><l><add hand="dw" resp="ww">Be broken down & old.</add></l><l><add hand="dw" resp="ww">Sore aches she needs must have! but less</add></l><l><add hand="dw" resp="ww">Of mind, than body&rsquo;s wretchedness,</add></l><l><add hand="dw" resp="ww">From damp, & rain, & cold.</add></l></lg><pb n="116"><milestone n="116" unit="page"><lb><lb><lg n="37"><l n="217"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&sol;,</add> I, too<add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add>have pass&rsquo;d her on the hills</l><l n="218">Setting her little water-mills</l><l n="219">By spouts and fountains wild<del>,</del> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">&mdash;&sol;</add></l><l n="220">Such small machinery as she turn&rsquo;d</l><l n="221">Ere she had wept, ere she had mourn&rsquo;d<add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">,&sol;</add></l><l n="222">A young and happy Child!</l></lg><lg n="38" type="stanza"><l n="223">Farewel! and when thy days are told</l><l n="224">Ill-fated Ruth! in hallow&rsquo;d mold</l><l n="225">Thy corpse shall buried be<del>,</del> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">;&sol;</add></l><l n="226">For thee a funeral bell shall ring,</l><l n="227">And all the congregation sing</l><l n="228">A Christian psalm for thee.</l></lg></body></text><pb n="121"><text><body><milestone n="121" unit="page"><lb><lb><lg n="3" type="stanza"><l n="9">&mdash;When through this little wreck of fame,</l><l n="10">Cypher and syllable<del>,</del> thine eye <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">!&sol;</add></l><l n="11">Has travell&rsquo;d down to Matthew&rsquo;s name,</l><l n="12">Pause with no common sympathy.</l></lg><lg n="4" type="stanza"><l n="13">And<add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add>if a sleeping tear should wake<add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">,&sol;</add></l><l n="14">Then be it neither check&rsquo;d nor stay&rsquo;d:</l><l n="15">For Matthew a request I make</l><l n="16">Which for himself he had not made.</l></lg><lg n="5" type="stanza"><l n="17">Poor Matthew, all his frolics o&rsquo;er,</l><l n="18">Is silent as a standing pool<del>,</del> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">;&sol;</add></l><l n="19">Far from the chimney&rsquo;s merry roar,</l><l n="20">And murmur of the village school.</l></lg><lg n="6"><l n="21">The sighs which Matthew heav&rsquo;d were sighs</l><l n="22">Of one tir&rsquo;d out with fun and madness;</l><l n="23">The tears which came to Matthew&rsquo;s eyes</l><l n="24">Were tears of light, the oil of gladness.</l></lg><pb n="122"><milestone n="122" unit="page"><lb><lb><lg n="7" type="stanza"><l n="25"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">,&sol; ,&sol;</add> Yet<add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add>sometimes<add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add>when the secret cup</l><l n="26">Of still and serious thought went round<add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">,&sol;</add></l><l n="27">It seem&rsquo;d as if he drank it up<del>,</del> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">&mdash;&sol;</add></l><l n="28">He felt with spirit so profound.</l></lg><lg n="8" type="stanza"><l n="29">&mdash;Thou soul of God&rsquo;s best earthly mould<del>,</del> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">!&sol;</add></l><l n="30"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&sol;!</add> Thou happy soul<del>,</del> and can it be</l><l n="31">That these two words of glittering gold</l><l n="32">Are all that must remain of thee?</l></lg></body></text><pb n="123"><text><body><milestone n="123" unit="page"><lb><lb><head><hi rend="small">the</hi><lb><lb><emph>Two APRIL MORNINGS. </emph></head><lg n="1" type="stanza"><l n="1">We walk&rsquo;d along, while bright and red</l><l n="2">Uprose the morning sun<del>,</del> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">;&sol;</add></l><l n="3">And Matthew stopp&rsquo;d, he look&rsquo;d, and said,</l><l n="4">&ldquo;The will of God be done!&rdquo;</l></lg><lg n="2" type="stanza"><l n="5">A village Schoolmaster was he,</l><l n="6">With hair of glittering grey;</l><l n="7">As blithe a man as you could see</l><l n="8">On a spring holiday.</l></lg><lg n="9"><l n="9">And on that morning, through the grass,</l><l n="10">And by the steaming rills,</l><l n="11">We travell&rsquo;d merrily<add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add>to pass <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">,&sol;</add></l><l n="12">A day among the hills.</l></lg><pb n="124"><milestone n="124" unit="page"><lb><lb><lg n="4" type="stanza"><l n="13">&ldquo;Our work,&rdquo; said I, &ldquo;was well begun;</l><l n="14">&ldquo;Then, from thy breast what thought,</l><l n="15">&ldquo; Beneath so beautiful a sun,</l><l n="16">&ldquo; So sad a sigh has brought?<add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add><add resp="ww">&rdquo;</add></l></lg><lg n="5" type="stanza"><l n="17">A second time did Matthew stop<del>,</del> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">;&sol;</add></l><l n="18"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&sol;,</add>And<add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add>fixing still his eye</l><l n="19">Upon the eastern mountain-top<add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">,&sol;</add></l><l n="20">To me he made reply.</l></lg><lg n="6" type="stanza"><l n="21"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> Yon cloud with that long purple cleft</l><l n="22"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> Brings fresh into my mind</l><l n="23"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> A day like this which I have left</l><l n="24"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> Full thirty years behind.</l></lg><lg n="7" type="stanza"><l n="25"><del>And on that slope of springing corn</del></l><l n="26"><del>The self-same crimson hue</del></l><l n="27"><del>Fell from the sky that April morn,</del></l><l n="28"><del>The same which now I view!</del></l></lg><lg n="7" type="stanza" rend="ms."><l n="25"><add hand="dw" resp="ww">&ldquo;And just above yon slope of corn</add></l><l n="26"><add hand="dw" resp="ww">&ldquo;Such colours, and no other,</add></l><l n="27"><add hand="dw" resp="ww">&ldquo;Were in the sky, that April Morn</add></l><l n="28"><add hand="dw" resp="ww">&ldquo;Of this the very brother.</add></l></lg><pb n="125"><milestone n="125" unit="page"><lb><lb><lg n="8" type="stanza"><l n="29"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> With rod and line my silent sport</l><l n="30"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> I plied by Derwent&rsquo;s wave<del>,</del> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">;&sol;</add></l><l n="31"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> And, coming to the church, stopp&rsquo;d short</l><l n="32"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> Beside my Daughter&rsquo;s grave.</l></lg><lg n="9" type="stanza"><l n="33"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> Nine summers had she scarcely seen<add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">,&sol;</add></l><l n="34"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> The pride of all the vale;</l><l n="35"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo; </add>And then she sang!&mdash;she would have been</l><l n="36"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo; </add>A very nightingale.</l></lg><lg n="10"><l n="37"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> Six feet in earth my Emma lay<del>,</del> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">;&sol;</add></l><l n="38"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> And yet I lov&rsquo;d her more,</l><l n="39"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> For so it seem&rsquo;d, than till that day</l><l n="40"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> I e&rsquo;er had lov&rsquo;d before.</l></lg><lg n="11" type="stanza"><l n="41"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> And, turning from her grave, I met</l><l n="42"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> Beside the church-yard Yew</l><l n="43"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> A blooming Girl, whose hair was wet</l><l n="44"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> With points of morning dew.</l></lg><pb n="126"><milestone n="126" unit="page"><lb><lb><lg n="12" type="stanza"><l n="45"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> A basket on her head she bare<del>,</del> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">;&sol;</add></l><l n="46"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> Her brow was smooth and white<del>,</del> <del>;</del><add place="rmargin" resp="ww">:&sol;</add></l><l n="47"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> To see a Child so very fair,</l><l n="48"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> It was a pure delight!</l></lg><lg n="13" type="stanza"><l n="49"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> No fountain from its rocky cave</l><l n="50"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> E&rsquo;er tripp&rsquo;d with foot so free<del>,</del> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">;&sol;</add></l><l n="51"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> She seem&rsquo;d as happy as a wave</l><l n="52"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> That dances on the sea.</l></lg><lg n="14" type="stanza"><l n="53"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> There came from me a sigh of pain</l><l n="54"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> Which I could ill confine;</l><l n="55"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> I look&rsquo;d at her and look&rsquo;d again<del>;</del> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">:&sol;</add></l><l n="56"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> &mdash;And did not wish her mine.<add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add>&rdquo;</l></lg><lg n="15" type="stanza"><l n="57">Matthew is in his grave, yet now</l><l n="58">Methinks I see him stand,</l><l n="59">As at that moment, with his bough</l><l n="60">Of wilding in his hand.</l></lg></body></text><pb n="127"><text><body><milestone n="127" unit="page"><lb><lb><head><emph>The FOUNTAIN, <lb><lb>A Conversation. </emph></head><lg n="1" type="stanza"><l n="1">We talk&rsquo;d with open heart, and tongue</l><l n="2">Affectionate and true<del>,</del> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">;&sol;</add></l><l n="3">A pair of Friends, though I was young,</l><l n="4">And Matthew seventy-two.</l></lg><lg n="2" type="stanza"><l n="5">We lay beneath a spreading oak,</l><l n="6">Beside a mossy seat<del>,</del> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">;&sol;</add></l><l n="7">And from the turf a fountain broke,</l><l n="8">And gurgled at our feet.</l></lg><lg n="3" type="stanza"><l n="9">&ldquo; Now, Matthew<del>,</del> let us try to match <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">!&sol;</add></l><l n="10"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> This water&rsquo;s pleasant tune</l><l n="11"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> With some old Border-song, or <del>c</del>atch <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">C&sol;</add></l><l n="12">That suits a summer&rsquo;s noon.</l></lg><pb n="128"><milestone n="128" unit="page"><lb><lb><lg n="4" type="stanza"><l n="13"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> Or of the Church-clock and the chimes</l><l n="14"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> Sing here beneath the shade,</l><l n="15"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> That half-mad thing of witty rhymes</l><l n="16"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> Which you last April made! <add resp="ww">&rdquo;</add></l></lg><lg n="5" type="stanza"><l n="17"><del>On</del> <add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add><add place="aboveline" resp="ww">In</add> silence Matthew lay, and eyed</l><l n="18">The spring beneath the tree;</l><l n="19">And thus the dear old Man replied,</l><l n="20">The grey-hair&rsquo;d Man of glee.</l></lg><lg n="6" type="stanza"><l n="21"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> Down to the vale this water steers,</l><l n="22"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> How merrily it goes!</l><l n="23"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> &rsquo;Twill murmur on a thousand years,</l><l n="24"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> And flow as now it flows.</l></lg><lg n="7" type="stanza"><l n="25"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> And here, on this delightful day,</l><l n="26"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> I cannot chuse but think</l><l n="27"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> How oft, a vigorous Man, I lay</l><l n="28"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> Beside this Fountain&rsquo;s brink.</l></lg><pb n="129"><milestone n="129" unit="page"><lb><lb><lg n="8" type="stanza"><l n="29"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> My eyes are dim with childish tears,</l><l n="30"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> My heart is idly stirr&rsquo;d,</l><l n="31"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> For the same sound is in my ears,</l><l n="32"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> Which in those days I heard.</l></lg><lg n="9"><l n="33"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> Thus fares it still in our decay:</l><l n="34"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> And yet the wiser mind</l><l n="35"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> Mourns less for what age takes away</l><l n="36"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> Than what it leaves behind.</l></lg><lg n="10" type="stanza"><l n="37"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&sol;B</add><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> The <del>b</del>lackbird in the summer trees,</l><l n="38"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&sol;L &ldquo;</add> The lark upon the hill,</l><l n="39"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> Let loose their carols when they please,</l><l n="40"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> Are quiet when they will.</l></lg><lg n="11" type="stanza"><l n="41"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> With Nature never do <emph>they</emph> wage</l><l n="42"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> A foolish strife; they see</l><l n="43"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> A happy youth, and their old age</l><l n="44"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> Is beautiful and free:</l></lg><pb n="130"><milestone n="130" unit="page"><lb><lb><lg n="12" type="stanza"><l n="45"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> But we are press&rsquo;d by heavy laws<del>,</del> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">;&sol;</add></l><l n="46"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> And often, glad no more,</l><l n="47"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> We wear a face of joy, because</l><l n="48"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> We have been glad of yore.</l></lg><lg n="13" type="stanza"><l n="49"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> If there is one who need bemoan</l><l n="50"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> His kindred laid in earth,</l><l n="51"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> The houshold hearts that were his own,</l><l n="52"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> It is the man of mirth.</l></lg><lg n="14" type="stanza"><l n="53"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> My days, my Friend, are almost gone,</l><l n="54"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> My life has been approv&rsquo;d,</l><l n="55"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> And many love me<del>,</del> but by none <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">;&sol;</add></l><l n="56"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> Am I enough belov&rsquo;d.&rdquo;</l></lg><lg n="15" type="stanza"><l n="57"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> Now both himself and me he wrongs,</l><l n="58"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> The man who thus complains!</l><l n="59"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> I live and sing my idle songs</l><l n="60"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> Upon these happy plains,</l></lg></body></text><pb n="133"><text id="Nutting"><body><milestone n="133" unit="page"><lb><lb><lg n="1" part="M" type="verseparagraph"><l n="10">Motley accoutrement<del>s</del>! of power to smile <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">d&sol;</add></l><l n="11">At thorns, and brakes, and brambles, and, in truth,</l><l n="12">More ragged than need was.  Among the woods,</l><l n="13">And o&rsquo;er the pathless rocks, I forc&rsquo;d my way</l><l n="14">Until, at length, I came to one dear nook</l><l n="15">Unvisited, where not a broken bough</l><l n="16">Droop&rsquo;d with its wither&rsquo;d leaves, ungracious sign</l><l n="17">Of devastation, but the hazels rose</l><l n="18">Tall and erect, with milk-white clusters hung,</l><l n="19">A virgin scene!&mdash;A little while I stood,</l><l n="20">Breathing with such suppression of the heart</l><l n="21">As joy delights in; and with wise restraint</l><l n="22">Voluptuous, fearless of a rival, eyed</l><l n="23">The banquet, or beneath the trees I sate</l><l n="24">Among the flowers, and with the flowers I play&rsquo;d;</l><l n="25">A temper known to those, who, after long</l><l n="26">And weary expectation, have been bless&rsquo;d</l><l n="27">With sudden happiness beyond all hope.&mdash;</l><l n="28">&mdash;Perhaps it was a bower beneath whose leaves</l><l n="29">The violets of five seasons re-appear</l></lg><pb><milestone n="134" unit="page"><lb><lb><lg n="1" part="M" type="verseparagraph"><l n="30">And fade, unseen by any human eye<del>,</del> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">;&sol;</add></l><l n="31">Where fairy water-breaks do murmur on</l><l n="32">Forever, and I saw the sparkling foam,</l><l n="33">And with my cheek on one of those green stones</l><l n="34">That, fleec&rsquo;d with moss, beneath the shady trees,</l><l n="35"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&sol;,</add>Lay round me<add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add>scatter&rsquo;d like a flock of sheep,</l><l n="36">I heard the murmur and the murmuring sound,</l><l n="37">In that sweet mood when pleasure loves to pay</l><l n="38"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">;</add> Tribute to ease<del>,</del> and, of its joy secure<add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">,&sol;</add></l><l n="39">The heart luxuriates with indifferent things,</l><l n="40">Wasting its kindliness on stocks and stones,</l><l n="41">And on the vacant air. Then up I rose,</l><l n="42">And dragg&rsquo;d to earth both branch and bough, with crash</l><l n="43">And merciless ravage; and the shady nook</l><l n="44">Of hazels, and the green and mossy bower<add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">,&sol;</add></l><l n="45">Deform&rsquo;d and sullied, patiently gave up</l><l n="46">Their quiet being: and<add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add>unless I now <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">,&sol;</add></l><l n="47">Confound my present feelings with the past,</l><l n="48">Even then, when from the bower I turn&rsquo;d away<del>,</del> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">d&sol;</add></l><l n="49">Exulting, rich beyond the wealth of kings<add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">,&sol;</add></l></lg><pb><milestone n="135" unit="page"><lb><lb><lg n="1" type="verseparagraph" part="F"><l n="50">I felt a sense of pain when I beheld</l><l n="51">The silent trees and the intruding sky.&mdash;</l></lg><lb><lg n="2" type="verseparagraph"><l n="52">    Then, dearest Maiden! move along these shades</l><l n="53"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&sol;;</add> In gentleness of heart<add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add>with gentle hand</l><l n="54">Touch,&mdash;&mdash;for there is a Spirit in the woods.</l></lg></body></text><pb n="136"><text><body><milestone n="136" unit="page"><lb><lb><lg n="1" type="stanza"><l n="1">Three years she grew in sun and shower,</l><l n="2">Then Nature said, &ldquo;A lovelier flower</l><l n="3">On earth was never sown;</l><l n="4">This Child I to myself will take<del>,</del> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">;&sol;</add></l><l n="5">She shall be mine, and I will make</l><l n="6">A Lady of my own.</l></lg><lg n="2" type="stanza"><l n="7" rend="ms."><add hand="dw" resp="ww">Her teacher I myself will be,</add></l><l n="7"><del>Myself will to my darling be</del></l><l n="8"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&sol;;</add> <del>Both law and impulse</del><del>,</del><add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add><add hand="dw" place="aboveline" resp="ww">She is my darling;&mdash;</add>and with me</l><l n="9"><add place="rmargin" resp="ww">&sol;,</add> The Girl<add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add>in rock and plain,</l><l n="10">In earth and heaven, in glade and bower,</l><l n="11">Shall feel an overseeing power</l><l n="12">To kindle or restrain.</l></lg><pb n="137"><milestone n="137" unit="page"><lb><lb><lg n="3" type="stanza"><l n="13">She shall be sportive as the <del>f</del>awn <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">F&sol;</add></l><l n="14">That wild with glee across the lawn</l><l n="15">Or up the mountain springs<del>,</del> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">;&sol;</add></l><l n="16">And hers shall be the breathing balm,</l><l n="17">And hers the silence and the calm</l><l n="18">Of mute insensate things.</l></lg><lg n="4" type="stanza"><l n="19"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&sol;C</add> The floating <del>c</del>louds their state shall lend</l><l n="20"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&sol;;</add> To her<del>,</del> for her the willow bend<del>,</del> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">;&sol;</add></l><l n="21">Nor shall she fail to see</l><l n="22">Even in the motions of the <del>s</del>torm <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">S&sol;</add></l><l n="23" rend="ms."><add hand="dw" place="aboveline" resp="ww">Grace that shall mould the Maiden&rsquo;s form</add></l><l n="23"><del>A beauty that shall mould her form</del></l><l n="24">By silent sympathy.</l></lg><lg n="3" type="stanza"><l n="25"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">SS</add> The <del>s</del>tars of midnight shall be dear</l><l n="26"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">;</add> To her<del>,</del> and she shall lean her ear</l><l n="27">In many a secret place</l><l n="28"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&sol;R</add> Where <del>r</del>ivulets dance their wayward round,</l><l n="29">And beauty born of murmuring sound</l><l n="30">Shall pass into her face.</l></lg><pb n="138"><milestone unit="page" n="138"><lb><lb><lg n="6" type="stanza"><l n="31">And vital feelings of delight</l><l n="32">Shall rear her form to stately height,</l><l n="33">Her virgin bosom swell<del>,</del> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">;&sol;</add></l><l n="34">Such thoughts to Lucy I will give</l><l n="35">While she and I together live</l><l n="36">Here in this happy <del>d</del>ell. &rdquo;<add place="belowline" resp="ww">^&sol;</add> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">D&sol;</add></l></lg><lg n="7" type="stanza"><l n="37">Thus Nature spake&mdash;The work was done&mdash;</l><l n="38">How soon my Lucy&rsquo;s race was run!</l><l n="39">She died and left to me</l><l n="40">This heath, this calm and quiet scene<del>,</del> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">;&sol;</add></l><l n="41">The memory of what has been,</l><l n="42">And never more will be.</l></lg></body></text><pb n="139"><text><body><milestone n="139" unit="page"><lb><lb><head><emph>The PET-LAMB, <lb><lb><hi rend="small">A PASTORAL. </hi></emph></head><lg n="1" type="stanza"><l n="1">The dew was falling fast, the stars began to blink;</l><l n="2"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&sol;:</add> I heard a voice<del>,</del> it said, <add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add>&ldquo;Drink, pretty Creature, drink!<add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add><add resp="ww">&rdquo;</add></l><l n="3">And, looking o&rsquo;er the hedge, before me I espied,</l><l n="4">A snow-white mountain Lamb with a Maiden at its side.</l></lg><lg n="2" type="stanza"><l n="5">No other sheep were near, the Lamb was all alone,</l><l n="6">And by a slender cord was tether&rsquo;d to a stone;</l><l n="7">With one knee on the grass did the little Maiden kneel,</l><l n="8">While to that Mountain Lamb she gave its evening meal.</l></lg><lg n="3" type="stanza"><l n="9">The Lamb while from her hand he thus his supper took</l><l n="10">Seem&rsquo;d to feast with head and ears<del>,</del> and his tail with pleasure shook. <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">;&sol;</add></l><l n="11">&ldquo;Drink, pretty Creature, drink,&rdquo; she said in such a tone</l><l n="12">That I almost receiv&rsquo;d her heart into my own.</l></lg><pb n="140"><milestone n="140" unit="page"><lb><lb><lg n="4" type="stanza"><l n="13">&rsquo;Twas little Barbara Lewthwaite, a Child of beauty rare<del>,</del> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">!&sol;</add></l><l n="14">I watch&rsquo;d them with delight, they were a lovely pair.</l><l n="15"><del>And</del> <del>n</del>Now with <add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add><add place="aboveline" hand="dw" resp="ww">her</add> empty Can the Maiden turn&rsquo;d away<del>,</del> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">;&sol;</add></l><l n="16">But ere ten yards were gone her footsteps did she stay.</l></lg><lg n="5" type="stanza"><l n="5"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&sol;;</add> Towards the Lamb she look&rsquo;d<del>,</del> and from that shady place</l><l n="18">I unobserv&rsquo;d could see the workings of her face:</l><l n="19">If Nature to her tongue could measur&rsquo;d numbers bring</l><l n="20">Thus, thought I, to her Lamb that little Maid <del>would</del> <add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add><add place="aboveline" resp="ww">might</add> sing.</l></lg><lg n="6" type="stanza"><l n="21">&ldquo;What ails thee, Young One? What? Why pull so at thy cord?</l><l n="22"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> Is it not well with thee? Well both for bed and board?</l><l n="23"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> Thy plot of grass is soft, and green as grass can be<del>,</del> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">;&sol;</add></l><l n="24"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> Rest little Young One, rest; <del>what is&rsquo;t that aileth thee?</del><add hand="dw" place="aboveline" resp="ww"><del>why bleat so
after
me?</del></add><add hand="dw" place="belowline" resp="ww">what is&rsquo;t that aileth thee?</add></l></lg><lg n="7" type="stanza"><l n="25"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> What is it thou would&rsquo;st seek? What is wanting to thy heart?</l><l n="26"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> Thy limbs are they not strong? And beautiful thou art:</l><l n="27"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&sol;; &ldquo;</add> This grass is tender grass<del>,</del> these flowers they have no peers<del>,</del> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">;</add></l><l n="28"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> And that green corn all day is rustling in thy ears<del>.</del> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">!&sol;</add></l></lg><pb n="141"><milestone n="141" unit="page"><lb><lb><lg n="8" type="stanza"><l n="29"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> If the Sun <del>is</del><add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add>shining hot, do but stretch thy woollen chain, <add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add><add place="rmargin" resp="ww">be&sol;</add></l><l n="30"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> This beech is standing by, its covert thou can&rsquo;st gain<del>,</del> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">;</add></l><l n="31"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> For rain and mountain storms<add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add>the like thou need&rsquo;st not fear<del>,</del> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">!&sol;&mdash;&sol;</add></l><l n="32"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> The rain and storm are things which scarcely can come here.</l></lg><lg n="9" type="stanza"><l n="33"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> Rest, little Young One, rest; thou hast forgot the day</l><l n="34"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> When my Father found thee first in places far away:</l><l n="35"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> Many flocks are on the hills, but thou wert own&rsquo;d by none<del>,</del> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">;&sol;</add></l><l n="36"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> And by thy Mother from thy side for evermore was gone.</l></lg><lg n="10" type="stanza"><l n="37"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> He took thee in his arms, and in pity brought thee home<del>,</del> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">:&sol;</add></l><l n="38"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> A blessed day for thee! then whither would&rsquo;st thou roam?</l><l n="39"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&sol;N &ldquo;</add> A faithful <del>n</del>urse thou hast, the <del>d</del>am that did thee yean <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">D&sol;</add></l><l n="40"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> Upon the mountain tops no kinder could have been.</l></lg><lg n="11" type="stanza"><l n="41"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> Thou know&rsquo;st that twice a day I have brought thee in this Can</l><l n="42"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> Fresh water from the brook as clear as ever ran<del>;</del> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">:&sol;</add></l><l n="43"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> And twice in the day when the ground is wet with dew</l><l n="44"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> I bring thee draughts of milk, warm milk it is and new.</l></lg><pb n="142"><milestone n="142" unit="page"><lb><lb><lg n="12" type="stanza"><l n="45"><add place="lmargin">&ldquo;</add> Thy limbs will shortly be twice as stout as they are now<del>,</del> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">,&sol;</add></l><l n="46"><add place="lmargin"><add place="lmargin">&ldquo;</add></add> Then I&rsquo;ll yoke thee to my cart like a pony in the plough<del>,</del> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">;</add></l><l n="47"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&sol;P&sol;; &ldquo;</add> My <del>p</del>laymate thou shalt be<del>,</del> and when the wind is cold</l><l n="48"><add place="lmargin">&ldquo;</add> Our hearth shall be thy bed, our house shall be thy fold.</l></lg><lg n="13" type="stanza"><l n="49"><add place="lmargin">&ldquo;</add> It will not, will not rest!&mdash;poor Creature can it be</l><l n="50"><add place="lmargin">&ldquo;</add> That &rsquo;tis thy Mother&rsquo;s heart which is working so in thee?</l><l n="51"><add place="lmargin">&ldquo;</add> Things that I know not of belike to thee are dear,</l><l n="52"><add place="lmargin">&ldquo;</add>  And dreams of things which thou can&rsquo;st neither see nor hear.</l></lg><lg n="14" type="stanza"><l n="53"><add place="lmargin">&ldquo;</add> Alas the mountain tops that look so green and fair!</l><l n="54"><add place="lmargin">&ldquo;</add>  I&rsquo;ve heard of fearful winds and darkness that come there<del>,</del> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">;&sol;</add></l><l n="55"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&sol;B &ldquo;</add>The little brooks, that seem all pastime and all play,</l><l n="56"><add place="lmargin">&ldquo;</add> When they are angry, roar like <del>l</del>ions for their prey. <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">L&sol;</add></l></lg><lg n="15"><l n="57"><del><add place="lmargin">&ldquo;</add> Here thou need&rsquo;st not dread the raven in the sky,</del></l><l n="58"><del><add place="lmargin">&ldquo;</add> He will not come to thee, our Cottage is hard by,</del> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">;&sol;</add></l><l n="59" rend="ms."><add place="dw" resp="ww"><del>Why bleat so after me? why pull so</del></add></l><l n="59"><del>Night and day thou art safe as living thing can be,</del></l><l n="60"><del>Be happy then and rest, what is&rsquo;t that aileth thee?</del></l></lg><lg n="15" type="stanza" rend="ms."><l n="57"><add hand="dw" resp="ww">&ldquo;Here thou needst not dread the raven in <lb>the sky,</add></l><l n="58" rend="ms."><add hand="dw" resp="ww">&ldquo;Night and day thou <add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add><add place="aboveline" resp="ww">art safe,&mdash;</add> our Cottage is hard by,</add></l><l n="59" rend="ms."><add hand="dw" resp="ww">&ldquo;Why bleat so after me? why pull so at <lb>thy chain?</add></l><l n="60" rend="ms."><add hand="dw" resp="ww">&ldquo;Sleep&mdash;& at break of day I will come to thee <lb>again.&rdquo;</add></l></lg><pb n="143"><milestone n="143" unit="page"><lb><lb><lg n="16" type="stanza"><l n="61"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&mdash;</add><add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add> As homeward through the lane I went with lazy feet,</l><l n="62">This song to myself did I oftentimes repeat<del>,</del> <add place="rmargin" resp="w">;&sol;</add></l><l n="63">And it seem&rsquo;d<add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add>as I retrac&rsquo;d the ballad line by line<add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">,&sol; ,&sol;</add></l><l n="64">That but half of it was hers, and one half of it was mine.</l></lg><lg n="17" type="stanza"><l n="65">Again, and once again did I repeat the song<del>,</del> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">;&sol;</add></l><l n="66"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&sol;,</add> &ldquo;Nay&rdquo;<add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add> said I, &ldquo;more than half to the Damsel must belong,</l><l n="67">For she look&rsquo;d with such a look, and she spake with such a tone,</l><l n="68">That I almost receiv&rsquo;d her heart into my own.&rdquo;</l></lg><p></p></body></text><pb n="144"><text><body><milestone n="144" unit="page"><lb><lb><head><emph>Written in GERMANY, <lb><lb>On one of the coldest days of the Century. </emph><note><emph>I must apprize the Reader that the stoves in North Germany <lb>generally have the impression of a galloping Horse upon <lb>them, this being part of the Brunswick Arms. </emph></note></head><lg n="1" type="stanza"><l n="1">A fig for your languages, German and Norse<del>,</del> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">!&sol;</add></l><l n="2">Let me have the song of the Kettle<del>,</del> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">;&sol;</add></l><l n="3">And the tongs and the poker, instead of that <del>h</del>orse <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">H&sol;</add></l><l n="4">That gallops away with such fury and force</l><l n="5">On this dreary dull plate of black metal.</l></lg><lg n="2" type="stanza"><l n="6">Our earth is no doubt made of excellent stuff<del>,</del> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">;&sol;</add></l><l n="7"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&sol;:</add>But her pulses beat slower and slower<del>,</del></l><l n="8">The weather in Forty was cutting and rough,</l><l n="9"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&sol;G</add> And then, as Heaven knows, the <del>g</del>lass stood low enough<del>,</del> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">;&sol;</add></l><l n="10">And <emph>now</emph> it is four degrees lower.</l></lg><pb n="145"><milestone n="145" unit="page"><lb><lb><lg n="3" type="stanza"><l n="11">Here&rsquo;s a Fly, a disconsolate creature<add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add>perhaps, <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">,&sol;</add></l><l n="12">A child of the field, or the grove<del>,</del> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">;&sol;</add></l><l n="13"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&sol;,</add> And<add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add>sorrow for him! this dull treacherous heat</l><l n="14">Has seduc&rsquo;d the poor fool from his winter retreat,</l><l n="15">And he creeps to the edge of my stove.</l></lg><lg n="4" type="stanza"><l n="16">Alas! how he fumbles about the domains</l><l n="17">Which this comfortless oven environ<del>,</del> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">;&sol;</add></l><l n="18">He cannot find out in what track he must crawl,</l><l n="19">Now back to the tiles, and now back to the wall,</l><l n="20">And now on the brink of the iron.</l></lg><lg n="5" type="stanza"><l n="21">Stock-still there he stands like a traveller bemaz&rsquo;d<del>,</del> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">;</add></l><l n="22">The best of his skill he has tried;</l><l n="23">His feelers methinks I can see him put forth</l><l n="24">To the East and the West, and the South and the North,</l><l n="25">But he finds neither <del>g</del>uide-post nor <del>g</del>uide. <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">G&sol; G</add></l></lg><pb n="146"><milestone n="146" unit="page"><lb><lb><lg n="6" type="stanza"><l n="26">See! his spindles sink under him, foot, leg and thigh<del>,</del> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">;&sol;</add></l><l n="27">His eyesight and hearing are lost<del>,</del> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">;&sol;</add></l><l n="28">Between life and death his blood freezes and thaws<del>,</del> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">;&sol;</add></l><l n="29">And his two pretty pinions of blue dusky gauze</l><l n="30">Are glued to his sides by the frost.</l></lg><lg n="7" type="stanza"><l n="31"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&sol;&mdash;</add> No Brother, no Friend has he near him<del>,</del> while I</l><l n="32">Can draw warmth from the cheek of my Love<del>,</del> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">;&sol;</add></l><l n="33">As blest and as glad in this desolate gloom,</l><l n="34">As if green summer grass were the floor of my room,</l><l n="35">And woodbines were hanging above.</l></lg><lg n="8" type="stanza"><l n="36">Yet, God is my witness, thou small helpless Thing<del>,</del> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">!&sol;</add></l><l n="37">Thy life I would gladly sustain</l><l n="38">Till summer comes up from the South, and with crowds</l><l n="39">Of thy brethren a march thou should&rsquo;st sound through the clouds,</l><l n="40">And back to the forests again.</l></lg></body></text><pb n="147"><text><body><milestone n="147" unit="page"><lb><lb><head><emph>The CHILDLESS FATHER. </emph></head><lg n="1" type="stanza"><l n="1"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> Up, Timothy, up with your Staff and away!</l><l n="2"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> Not a soul in the village this morning will stay;</l><l n="3"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add>The Hare has just started from Hamilton&rsquo;s grounds,</l><l n="4"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> And Skiddaw is glad with the cry of the hounds. <add resp="ww">&rdquo;</add></l></lg><lg n="2" type="stanza"><l n="5">&mdash;Of coats and of jackets <del>both</del> grey, <del>red</del> <add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add><add hand="dw" place="aboveline" resp="ww">scarlet,</add> and green,</l><l n="6">On the slopes of the pastures all colours were seen<del>,</del> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">;&sol;</add></l><l n="7">With their comely blue aprons<add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add>and caps white as snow, <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">,&sol;</add></l><l n="8"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&sol;G</add> The <del>g</del>irls on the hills made a holiday show.</l></lg><lg n="3" type="stanza"><l n="9">The bason of box-wood,*<note>*In several parts of the North of England, when a funeral <lb>takes place, a bason full of Sprigs of Box-wood is placed at <lb>the door of the house from which the Coffin is taken up, and <lb>each person who attends the funeral ordinarily takes a Sprig <lb>of this Box-wood, and throws it into the grave of the deceased.</note> just six months
before,</l><l n="10">Had stood on the table at Timothy&rsquo;s door<del>,</del> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">;&sol;</add></l><pb n="148"><milestone n="148" unit="page"><lb><lb><l n="11">A Coffin through Timothy&rsquo;s threshold had pass&rsquo;d<del>,</del> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">;&sol;</add></l><l n="12">One Child did it bear and that Child was his last.</l></lg><lg n="4" type="stanza"><l n="13">Now fast up the dell came the noise and the fray,</l><l n="14">The horse and the horn, and the hark! hark away!</l><l n="15">Old Timothy took up his Staff, and he shut</l><l n="16">With a leisurely motion the door of his hut.</l></lg><lg n="5" type="stanza"><l n="17">Perhaps to himself at that moment he said,</l><l n="18">&ldquo;The key I must take, for my Ellen is dead<add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add>&rdquo; <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">.&sol;</add></l><l n="19">But of this in my ears not a word did he speak,</l><l n="20">And he went to the chase with a tear on his cheek.</l></lg></body></text><pb n="151"><text><body><milestone n="151" unit="page"><lb><lb><head><emph>The OLD CUMBERLAND BEGGAR, <lb><lb><hi rend="small">A  DESCRIPTION. </hi></emph><note><p><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&sol;O&sol;M</add> The class of Beggars to which the <del resp="ww">o</del>ld <del resp="ww">m</del>an here described <lb>belongs, will probably soon be extinct.  It consisted of <lb>poor, and, mostly, old and infirm persons, who confined <lb>themselves to a stated round in their neighbourhood, and <lb>had certain fixed days, on which, at different houses, <lb>they regularly received <del>charity</del> <add hand="dw" place="aboveline" resp="ww">alms</add>; sometimes in money, but <lb>mostly in provisions. </p></note> </head><lg n="1" part="I" type="verseparagraph"><l n="1">I saw an aged Beggar in my walk,</l><l n="2">And he was seated by the highway side</l><l n="3">On a low structure of rude masonry</l><l n="4">Built at the foot of a huge hill, that they</l><l n="5">Who lead their horses down the steep rough road</l><l n="6">May thence remount at ease. The aged <del>m</del>an <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">M&sol;</add> </l><l n="7">Had placed his staff across the broad smooth stone</l></lg><pb><milestone n="152" unit="page"><lb><lb><lg n="1" part="F" type="verseparagraph"><l n="8">That overlays the pile, and from a bag</l><l n="9">All white with flour the dole of village dames,</l><l n="10">He drew his scraps and fragments, one by one,</l><l n="11">And scann&rsquo;d them with a fix&rsquo;d and serious look</l><l n="12">Of idle computation. In the sun,</l><l n="13">Upon the second step of that small pile,</l><l n="14">Surrounded by those wild unpeopled hills,</l><l n="15">He sate, and eat his food in solitude<del>;</del> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">:&sol;</add></l><l n="16">And ever, scatter&rsquo;d from his palsied hand,</l><l n="17"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&sol;,</add> That<add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add>still attempting to prevent the waste,</l><l n="18">Was baffled still, the crumbs in little showers</l><l n="19">Fell on the ground, and the small mountain birds,</l><l n="20">Not venturing yet to peck their destin&rsquo;d meal,</l><l n="21">Approach&rsquo;d within the length of half his staff.</l></lg><lg n="2" part="I" type="verseparagraph"><l n="22"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&sol;;</add> Him from my childhood have I known<del>,</del> and then</l><l n="23">He was so old, he seems not older now;</l><l n="24">He travels on, a solitary <del>m</del>an, <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">M&sol;</add></l></lg><pb><milestone n="153" unit="page"><lb><lb><lg n="2" part="M" type="verseparagraph"><l n="25">So helpless in appearance, that for him</l><l n="26"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&sol;H</add> The sauntering <del>h</del>orseman-traveller does not throw</l><l n="27">With careless hand his alms upon the ground,</l><l n="28">But stops, that he may safely lodge the coin</l><l n="29">Within the old Man&rsquo;s hat; nor quits him so,</l><l n="30">But still when he has given his horse the rein</l><l n="31">Towards the aged Beggar turns a look,</l><l n="32">Sidelong and half-reverted. She who tends</l><l n="33"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&sol;T</add> The <del>t</del>oll-gate, when in summer at her door</l><l n="34">She turns her wheel, if on the road she sees</l><l n="35">The aged Beggar coming, quits her work,</l><l n="36">And lifts the latch for him that he may pass.</l><l n="37">The Post-boy when his rattling wheels o&rsquo;ertake</l><l n="38">The aged Beggar, in the woody lane, </l><l n="39">Shouts to him from behind, and, if perchance</l><l n="40">The old Man does not change his course, the Boy</l><l n="41">Turns with less noisy wheels to the road-side,</l><l n="42">And passes gently by, without a curse</l></lg><pb><milestone n="154" unit="page"><lb><lb><lg n="2" part="M" type="verseparagraph"><l n="43">Upon his lips, or anger at his heart.</l><l n="44">He travels on, a solitary Man,</l><l n="45">His age has no companion. On the ground</l><l n="46">His eyes are turn&rsquo;d, and, as he moves along,</l><l n="47"><emph>They</emph> move along the ground; and<add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add>evermore, <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">,&sol;</add></l><l n="48">Instead of common and habitual sight</l><l n="49">Of fields with rural works, of hill and dale,</l><l n="50">And the blue sky, one little span of earth</l><l n="51">Is all his prospect. Thus, from day to day,</l><l n="52">Bowbent, his eyes for ever on the ground,</l><l n="53"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&sol;;</add> He plies his weary journey<del>,</del> seeing still,</l><l n="54">And never knowing that he sees, some straw,</l><l n="55">Some scatter&rsquo;d leaf, or marks which, in one track,</l><l n="56">The nails of cart or chariot wheel have left</l><l n="57">Impress&rsquo;d on the white road, in the same line,</l><l n="58">At distance still the same. Poor Traveller!</l><l n="59"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&sol;;</add> His staff trails with him<del>,</del> scarcely do his feet</l><l n="60">Disturb the summer dust<del>,</del> he is so still <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">;</add></l></lg><pb><milestone n="155" unit="page"><lb><lb><lg n="2" part="F" type="verseparagraph"><l n="61"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&sol;,</add> In look and motion<add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add>that the cottage curs,</l><l n="62">Ere he have pass&rsquo;d the door, will turn away<add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">,&sol;</add></l><l n="63">Weary of barking at him. Boys and <del>g</del>irls, <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">G&sol;</add></l><l n="64"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">M&sol;Y</add> The vacant and the busy, <del>m</del>aids and <del>y</del>ouths,</l><l n="65">And<del>u</del>rchins newly breech&rsquo;d<add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add>all pass him by: <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">U&sol;,&sol;</add></l><l n="66"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&sol;W</add> Him even the slow-pac&rsquo;d <del>w</del>aggon leaves behind.</l></lg><lg n="3" part="I" type="verseparagraph"><l n="67"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&sol;M</add> But deem not this <del>m</del>an useless.&mdash;&mdash;Statesmen! ye</l><l n="68">Who are so restless in your wisdom, ye</l><l n="69">Who have a broom still ready in your hands</l><l n="70">To rid the world of nuisances; ye proud,</l><l n="71">Heart-swoln, while in your pride ye contemplate</l><l n="72">Your talents, power, and wisdom, deem him not</l><l n="73">A burthen of the earth. &rsquo;Tis Nature&rsquo;s law</l><l n="74">That none, the meanest of created things,</l><l n="75">Or forms created the most vile and brute,</l><l n="76">The dullest or most noxious, should exist</l><l n="77">Divorced from good<del>,</del> a spirit and pulse of good, <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">&mdash;&sol;</add></l></lg><pb><milestone n="156" unit="page"><lb><lb><lg n="3" part="M" type="verseparagraph"><l n="78">A life and soul to every mode of being</l><l n="79">Inseparably link&rsquo;d.  While thus he creeps</l><l n="80">From door to door, the Villagers in him</l><l n="81">Behold a record which together binds</l><l n="82">Past deeds and offices of charity</l><l n="83">Else unremember&rsquo;d, and so keeps alive</l><l n="84">The kindly mood in hearts which lapse of years,</l><l n="85">And that half-wisdom half-experience gives</l><l n="86">Make slow to feel, and by sure steps resign</l><l n="87">To selfishness and cold oblivious cares.</l><l n="88">Among the farms and solitary huts<add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">,&sol;</add></l><l n="89">Hamlets, and thinly-scattered villages,</l><l n="90">Where&rsquo;er the aged Beggar takes his rounds,</l><l n="91">The mild necessity of use compels</l><l n="92">To acts of love; and habit does the work</l><l n="93">Of reason, yet prepares that after joy</l><l n="94">Which reason cherishes. And thus the soul,</l><l n="95">By that sweet taste of pleasure unpursu&rsquo;d<add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">,&sol;</add></l></lg><pb><milestone n="157" unit="page"><lb><lb><lg n="3" part="M" type="verseparagraph"><l n="96">Doth find itself insensibly dispos&rsquo;d</l><l n="97">To virtue and true goodness.  Some there are,</l><l n="98">By their good works exalted, lofty minds</l><l n="99">And meditative, authors of delight</l><l n="100">And happiness, which to the end of time</l><l n="101">Will live, and spread, and kindle; minds like these,</l><l n="102">In childhood, from this solitary <del>b</del>eing, <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">&sol;B</add></l><l n="103"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&sol;W</add> This helpless <del>w</del>anderer, have perchance receiv&rsquo;d,</l><l n="104">(A thing more precious far than all that books</l><l n="105">Or the <orig>s</orig>olicitudes of love can do!)</l><l n="106">That first mild touch of sympathy and thought,</l><l n="107">In which they found their kindred with a world</l><l n="108">Where want and sorrow were. The easy <del>m</del>an <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">M&sol;</add></l><l n="109">Who sits at his own door, and like the pear</l><l n="110">Which overhangs his head from the green wall,</l><l n="111">Feeds in the sunshine; the robust and young,</l><l n="112">The prosperous and unthinking, they who live</l><l n="113">Shelter&rsquo;d, and flouri<orig rend="longs">s</orig>h in a little grove</l></lg><pb n="107"><milestone n="158" unit="page"><lb><lb><lg n="3" type="verseparagraph" part="F"><l n="114">Of their own kindred, all behold in him</l><l n="115">A silent monitor, which on their minds</l><l n="116">Must needs impress a transitory thought</l><l n="117">Of self-congratulation, to the heart</l><l n="118">Of each recalling his peculiar boons,</l><l n="119">His charters and exemptions; and<add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add>perchance, <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">,&sol;</add></l><l n="120">Though he to no one give the fortitude</l><l n="121">And circumspection needful to preserve</l><l n="122">His present blessings, and to husband up</l><l n="123">The respite of the season, he, at least,</l><l n="124">And &rsquo;tis no vulgar service, makes them felt.</l></lg><lg n="4" part="I" type="verseparagraph"><l n="125">Yet further.&mdash;&mdash;Many, I believe, there are</l><l n="126">Who live a life of virtuous decency,</l><l n="127">Men who can hear the Decalogue and feel</l><l n="128"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&sol;; </add>No self-reproach<del>,</del> who of the moral law</l><l n="129">Establish&rsquo;d in the land where they abide</l><l n="130"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&sol;;</add> Are strict observers<del>,</del> and not negligent,</l></lg><pb><milestone n="159" unit="page"><lb><lb><lg n="4" part="M" type="verseparagraph"><l n="131">Meanwhile, in any tenderness of heart</l><l n="132">Or act of love to those with whom they dwell,</l><l n="133">Their kindred, and the children of their blood.</l><l n="134">Praise be to such, and to their slumbers peace!</l><l n="135">&mdash;But of the poor man ask, the abject poor,</l><l n="136">Go and demand of him, if there be here,</l><l n="137">In this cold abstinence from evil deeds,</l><l n="138">And these inevitable charities,</l><l n="139">Wherewith to satisfy the human soul.</l><l n="140">No&mdash;man is dear to man: the poorest poor</l><l n="141">Long for some moments in a weary life</l><l n="142">When they can know and feel that they have been</l><l n="143">Themselves the fathers and the dealers out</l><l n="144">Of some small blessings, have been kind to such</l><l n="145">As needed kindness, for this single cause,</l><l n="146">That we have all of us one human heart.</l><l n="147">&mdash;Such pleasure is to one kind Being known</l><l n="148">My Neighbour, when with punctual care, each week</l></lg><pb><milestone n="160" unit="page"><lb><lb><lg n="4" part="F" type="verseparagraph"><l n="149">Duly as Friday comes, though press&rsquo;d herself</l><l n="150">By her own wants, she from her chest of meal</l><l n="151">Takes one unsparing handful for the scrip</l><l n="152">Of this old Mendicant, and, from her door</l><l n="153">Returning with exhilarated heart,</l><l n="154">Sits by her fire and builds her hope in heav&rsquo;n.</l></lg><lg n="5" part="I" type="verseparagraph"><l n="155">Then let him pass, a blessing on his head!</l><l n="156">And while, in that vast solitude to which</l><l n="157">The tide of things has led him, he appears</l><l n="158">To breathe and live but for himself alone,</l><l n="159">Unblam&rsquo;d, uninjur&rsquo;d, let him bear about</l><l n="160">The good which the benignant law of heaven</l><l n="161"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&sol;;</add> Has hung around him<del>,</del> and, while life is his,</l><l n="162">Still let him prompt the unletter&rsquo;d Villagers</l><l n="163">To tender offices and pensive thoughts.</l><l n="164">Then let him pass, a blessing on his head!</l><l n="165">And, long as he can wander, let him breathe</l></lg><pb><milestone n="161" unit="page"><lb><lb><lg n="5" part="M" type="verseparagraph"><l n="166">The freshness of the vallies<del>,</del> let his blood <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">;&sol;</add></l><l n="167">Struggle with frosty air and winter snows<del>,</del> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">;&sol;</add></l><l n="168">And let the charter&rsquo;d wind that sweeps the heath</l><l n="169">Beat his grey locks against his wither&rsquo;d face.</l><l n="170">Reverence the hope whose vital anxiousness</l><l n="171">Gives the last human interest to his heart.</l><l n="172"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">H<hi>ouse</hi> </add><add place="belowline" resp="ww">small capitals</add> May never <del>House</del>, misnamed of <del>industry</del><del>,</del><add place="rmargin" resp="ww"> !&sol;
I<hi>ndustry </hi></add><add place="belowline" resp="ww">small
capitals</add></l><l n="173">Make him a captive; for that pent-up din,</l><l n="174">Those life-consuming sounds that clog the air,</l><l n="175">Be his the natural silence of old age.</l><l n="176">Let him be free of mountain solitudes<del>,</del><add place="rmargin" resp="ww"> ;&sol;</add></l><l n="177">And have around him, whether heard or not,</l><l n="178">The pleasant melody of woodland birds.</l><l n="179">Few are his pleasures; if his eyes, which now</l><l n="180">Have been so long familiar with the earth,</l><l n="181">No more behold the horizontal sun</l><l n="182">Rising or setting, let the light at least</l><l n="183">Find a free entrance to their languid orbs.</l></lg><pb><milestone n="162" unit="page"><lb><lb><lg n="5" part="F" type="verseparagraph"><l n="184">And let him, <emph>where</emph> and <emph>when</emph> he will, sit down</l><l n="185">Beneath the trees, or by the grassy bank</l><l n="186">Of high-way side, and with the little birds</l><l n="187">Share his chance-gather&rsquo;d meal<del>,</del> and, finally, <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">:&sol;</add></l><l n="188">As in the eye of Nature he has liv&rsquo;d,</l><l n="189">So in the eye of Nature let him die.</l></lg></body></text><pb n="163"><text><body><milestone n="163" unit="page"><lb><lb><head><emph>RURAL ARCHITECTURE. </emph></head><l n="1">There&rsquo;s George Fisher, Charles Fleming, and Reginald Shore,</l><pb n="164"><milestone n="164" unit="page"><lb><lb><lg n="3" type="stanza"><l n="13"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&sol;,</add> Just half a week after<add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add>the Wind sallied forth,</l><l n="14">And, in anger or merriment, out of the North</l><l n="15">Coming on with a terrible pother,</l><l n="16">From the peak of the crag blew the Giant away.</l><l n="17">And what did these School-boys?&mdash;The very next day</l><l n="18">They went and they built up another.</l></lg></body></text><pb n="165"><text><body><milestone n="165" unit="page"><lb><lb><head><emph>A POET&rsquo;s EPITAPH. </emph></head><lg n="1" type="stanza"><l n="1">Art thou a Statesman, in the van</l><l n="2">Of public business train&rsquo;d and bred,</l><l n="3">&mdash;First learn to love one living man;</l><l n="4"><emph>Then</emph> may&rsquo;st thou think upon the dead.</l></lg><lg n="2" type="stanza"><l n="5">A Lawyer art thou?&mdash;draw not nigh;</l><l n="6">Go, carry to some other place</l><l n="7">The hardness of thy coward eye,</l><l n="8">The falshood of thy sallow face.</l></lg><lg n="3" type="stanza"><l n="9"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&sol;M</add> Art thou a <del>m</del>an of purple cheer?</l><l n="10"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&sol;M</add> A rosy <del>m</del>an, right plump to see?</l><l n="11">Approach; yet Doctor, not too near:</l><l n="12">This grave no cushion is for thee.</l></lg><pb n="166"><milestone n="166" unit="page"><lb><lb><lg n="4" type="stanza"><l n="13">Art thou a man of gallant pride,</l><l n="14">A Soldier, and no man of chaff?</l><l n="15">Welcome!&mdash;but lay thy sword aside,</l><l n="16">And lean upon a Peasant&rsquo;s staff.</l></lg><lg n="5" type="stanza"><l n="17">Physician art thou? One, all eyes,</l><l n="18">Philosopher! a fingering slave,</l><l n="19">One that would peep and botanize</l><l n="20">Upon his mother&rsquo;s grave?</l></lg><lg n="6" type="stanza"><l n="21">Wrapp&rsquo;d closely in thy sensual fleece</l><l n="22">O turn aside, and take, I pray,</l><l n="23">That he below may rest in peace,</l><l n="24">Thy pin-point of a soul away!</l></lg><lg n="7" type="stanza"><l n="25">&mdash;A Moralist perchance appears;</l><l n="26">Led, Heaven knows how! to this poor sod:</l><l met="27">And He has neither eyes nor ears;</l><l n="28">Himself his world, and his own God;</l></lg><pb n="167"><milestone n="167" unit="page"><lb><lb><lg n="8" type="stanza"><l n="29">One to whose smooth-rubb&rsquo;d soul can cling</l><l n="30">Nor form nor feeling great nor small<del>,</del> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">;&sol;</add></l><l n="31">A reasoning, self-sufficing thing,</l><l n="32">An intellectual All in All!</l></lg><lg n="9"><l n="33">Shut close the door! press down the latch:</l><l n="34">Sleep in thy intellectual crust<del>,</del> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">!&sol;</add></l><l n="35">Nor lose ten tickings of thy watch,</l><l n="36">Near this unprofitable dust.</l></lg><lg n="10" type="stanza"><l n="37"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&sol;,</add>But who is He<add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add>with modest looks,</l><l n="38">And clad in homely russet brown?</l><l n="39">He murmurs near the running brooks</l><l n="40">A music sweeter than their own.</l></lg><lg n="11" type="stanza"><l n="41">He is retired as noontide dew,</l><l n="42">Or fountain in a noonday grove;</l><l n="43">And you must love him, ere to you</l><l n="44">He will seem worthy of your love.</l></lg><pb n="168"><milestone n="168" unit="page"><lb><lb><lg n="12" type="stanza"><l n="45">The outward shews of sky and earth,</l><l n="46">Of hill and valley he has view&rsquo;d;</l><l n="47">And impulses of deeper birth</l><l n="48">Have come to him in solitude.</l></lg><lg n="13" type="stanza"><l n="49">In common things that round us lie</l><l n="50">Some random truths he can impart<add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">,&sol;</add></l><l n="51"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&mdash;</add><add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add>The harvest of a quiet eye</l><l n="52">That broods and sleeps on his own heart.</l></lg><lg n="14" type="stanza"><l n="53"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&sol;M&sol;B</add> But he is weak, both <del>m</del>an and <del>b</del>oy,</l><l n="54">Hath been an idler in the land;</l><l n="55">Contented if he might enjoy</l><l n="56">The things which others understand.</l></lg><lg n="15" type="stanza"><l n="57">&mdash;Come hither in thy hour of strength<del>,</del> <add ana="rmargin" resp="ww">;&sol;</add></l><l n="58">Come, weak as is a breaking wave!</l><l n="59">Here stretch thy body at full length;</l><l n="60">Or build thy house upon this grave.&mdash;</l></lg></body></text><pb n="171"><text><body><milestone n="171" unit="page"><lb><lb><head><emph>A FRAGMENT. </emph></head><lg n="1" type="stanza"><l n="1">Between two sister moorland rills</l><l n="2">There is a spot that seems to lie</l><l n="3">Sacred to flowrets of the hills,</l><l n="4">And sacred to the sky.</l><l n="5">And in this smooth and open dell</l><l n="6">There is a tempest-stricken tree;</l><l n="7">A corner-stone by lightning cut,</l><l n="8">The last stone of a cottage hut;</l><l n="9">And in this dell you see</l><l n="10">A thing no storm can e&rsquo;er destroy,</l><l n="11">The shadow of a Danish Boy.</l></lg><lg n="2" type="stanza"><l n="12">In clouds above, the <del>l</del>ark is heard, <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">L&sol;</add></l><l n="13">He sings his blithest and his best;</l><pb n="172"><milestone n="172" unit="page"><lb><lb><l n="14">But in this lonesome nook the <del>b</del>ird <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">B&sol;</add></l><l n="15">Did never build his nest.</l><l n="16"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&sol;B</add> No <del>b</del>east, no <del>b</del>ird hath here his home; <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">B&sol;</add></l><l n="17"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&sol;B</add> The <del>b</del>ee&rsquo;s borne on the breezy air</l><l n="18">Pass high above those fragrant bells</l><l n="19">To other flowers, to other dells,</l><l n="20">Nor ever linger there.</l><l n="21">The Danish Boy walks here alone:</l><l n="22">The lovely dell is all his own.</l></lg><lg n="3" type="stanza"><l n="23">A spirit of noon day is he,</l><l n="24">He seems a Form of flesh and blood;</l><l n="25"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">Nor</add><add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add><add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add><del>A</del> piping Shepherd<add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add><del>he might be</del>, <add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add><add place="rmargin" hand="dw" resp="ww">shall he be</add></l><l n="26"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">Nor</add> <add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add><del>A</del> Herd-boy of the wood.</l><l n="27">A regal vest of fur he wears,</l><l n="28">In colour like a raven&rsquo;s wing;</l><l n="29"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&sol;t</add> It fears no<del>r</del> rain, nor wind, nor dew<del>,</del> <add ana="rmargin" resp="ww">;&sol;</add></l><l n="30">But in the storm &rsquo;tis fresh and blue</l><l n="31">As budding pines in Spring;</l><pb n="173"><milestone n="173" unit="page"><lb><lb><l n="32">His helmet has a vernal grace,</l><l n="33">Fresh as the bloom upon his face.</l></lg><lg n="4" type="stanza"><l n="34">Sharp is from his shoulder slung<del>;</del> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">:&sol;</add></l><l n="35">He rests the harp upon his knee<del>,</del> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">;&sol;</add></l><l n="36">And there in a forgotten tongue</l><l n="37">He warbles melody.</l><l n="38">Of flocks <del>and herds both far and near</del> <add place="lmargin" resp="ww" hand="dw">upon the neigh:</add><lb>					<add place="rmargin" resp="ww" hand="dw">bouring hills</add></l><l n="39"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&sol;;</add> He is the darling and the joy<del>,</del></l><l n="40">And often, when no cause appears,</l><l n="41">The mountain ponies prick their ears,</l><l n="42">They hear the Danish Boy,</l><l n="43">While in the dell he sits alone</l><l n="44">Beside the tree and corner-stone.</l></lg><lg n="5" type="stanza"><l n="45"><del resp="ww">When near this blasted tree you pass,</del></l><l n="46"><del resp="ww">Two sods are plainly to be seen</del></l><l n="47"><del resp="ww">Close at its root, and each with grass</del></l><l n="48"><del resp="ww">Is cover&rsquo;d fresh and green.</del></l><pb n="174"><milestone n="174" unit="page"><lb><lb><l n="49"><del resp="ww">Like turf upon a new-made grave</del></l><l n="50"><del resp="ww">These two green sods together lie,</del></l><l n="51"><del resp="ww">Nor heat, nor cold, nor rain, nor wind</del></l><l n="52"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">omit</add> <del resp="ww">Can these two sods together bind,</del></l><l n="53"><del resp="ww">Nor sun, nor earth, nor sky,</del></l><l n="54"><del resp="ww">But side by side the two are laid,</del></l><l n="55"><del resp="ww">As if just sever&rsquo;d by the spade.</del></l></lg><lg n="6" type="stanza"><l n="56">There sits he: in his face you spy</l><l n="57">No trace of a ferocious air,</l><l n="58">Nor ever was a cloudless sky</l><l n="59">So steady or so fair.</l><l n="60">The lovely Danish Boy is blest</l><l n="61">And happy in his flowery cove<del>;</del> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">:&sol;</add></l><l n="62">From bloody deeds his thoughts are far;</l><l n="63">And yet he warbles songs of war;</l><l n="64">They seem like songs of love,</l><l n="65">For calm and gentle is his mien;</l><l n="66">Like a dead Boy he is serene.</l></lg><trailer>* * * * * * * * * *</trailer></body></text><pb n="179"><text><body><milestone n="179" unit="page"><lb><lb><head><emph>POEMS on the NAMING of PLACES. </emph></head><head>I. </head><l n="1">It was an April Morning: fresh and clear</l><l n="2">The Rivulet, delighting in its strength,</l><l n="3">Ran with a young man&rsquo;s speed<del>,</del> and yet the voice <add ana="rmargin" resp="ww">;&sol;</add></l><l n="4">Of waters which the winter had supplied</l><l n="5">Was soften&rsquo;d down into a vernal tone.</l><l n="6">The spirit of enjoyment and desire,</l><l n="7">And hopes and wishes, from all living things</l><l n="8">Went circling, like a multitude of sounds.</l><l n="9">The budding groves appear&rsquo;d as if in haste</l><l n="10">To spur the steps of June; as if their shades</l><l n="11">Of <emph>various</emph> green were hindrances that stood</l><pb><milestone n="180" unit="page"><lb><lb><l n="12">Between them and their object: yet, meanwhile,</l><l n="13">There was such deep contentment in the air</l><l n="14">That every naked ash, and tardy tree</l><l n="15">Yet leafless, seem&rsquo;d as though the countenance</l><l n="16">With which it look&rsquo;d on this delightful day</l><l n="17">Were native to the summer.&mdash;Up the brook</l><l n="18">I roam&rsquo;d in the confusion of my heart,</l><l n="19">Alive to all things and forgetting all.</l><l n="20">At length I to a sudden turning came</l><l n="21">In this continuous glen, where down a rock</l><l n="22">The stream, so ardent in its course before,</l><l n="23">Sent forth such sallies of glad sound, that all</l><l n="24">Which I till then had heard, appear&rsquo;d the voice</l><l n="25">Of common pleasure: beast and bird, the <del>l</del>amb, <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">L&sol;</add></l><l n="26"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&sol;D&sol;L</add> The Shepherd&rsquo;s <del>d</del>og, the <del>l</del>innet and the <del>t</del>hrush <add ana="rmargin" resp="ww">T&sol;</add></l><l n="27"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&sol;W</add> Vied with this <del>w</del>aterfall, and made a song</l><l n="28">Which, while I listen&rsquo;d, seem&rsquo;d like the wild growth</l><l n="29">Or like some natural produce of the air</l><l n="30">That could not cease to be.  Green leaves were here,</l><pb><milestone n="181" unit="page"><lb><lb><l n="31">But &rsquo;twas the foliage of the rocks, the birch,</l><l n="32">The yew, the holly, and the bright green thorn,</l><l n="33">With hanging islands of resplendent furze:</l><l n="34">And on a summit, distant a short space,</l><l n="35">By any who should look beyond the dell,</l><l n="36">A single mountain Cottage might be seen.</l><l n="37">I gaz&rsquo;d and gaz&rsquo;d, and to myself I said,</l><l n="38">&ldquo;Our thoughts at least are ours; and this wild nook,</l><l n="39"><add place="belowline" resp="ww">&sol;^</add><add place="lmargin">&ldquo;</add> My E<hi rend="small">mma</hi>, I will dedicate to thee.&rdquo;</l><l n="40">&mdash;&mdash;Soon did the spot become my other home,</l><l n="41">My dwelling, and my out-of-doors abode.</l><l n="42">And, of the Shepherds who have seen me there,</l><l n="43">To whom I sometimes in our idle talk</l><l n="44">Have told this fancy, two or three, perhaps,</l><l n="45">Years after we are gone and in our graves,</l><l n="46">When they have cause to speak of this wild place,</l><l n="47">May call it by the name of E<hi>mma&rsquo;s dell</hi>.</l></body></text><pb n="182"><text><body><milestone n="182" unit="page"><lb><lb><head>II. <lb><lb><emph>To JOANNA. </emph></head><lg n="1" type="verseparagraph"><l n="1">Amid the smoke of cities did you pass</l><l n="2">&sol;; Your time of early youth<del>,</del> and there you learn&rsquo;d,</l><l n="3">From years of quiet industry, to love</l><l n="4">The living Beings by your own fire-side,</l><l n="5">With such a strong devotion, that your heart</l><l n="6">Is slow towards the sympathies of them</l><l n="7">Who look upon the hills with tenderness,</l><l n="8">And make dear friendships with the streams and groves.</l><l n="9"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&sol;,</add> Yet we<add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add>who are transgressors in this kind,</l><l n="10">Dwelling retired in our simplicity</l><l n="11">Among the woods and fields, we love you well,</l><l n="12">Joanna! and I guess, since you have been</l><pb><milestone n="183" unit="page"><lb><lb><l n="13">So distant from us now for two long years,</l><l n="14">That you will gladly listen to discourse</l><l n="15">However trivial, if you thence are taught</l><l n="16">That they, with whom you once were happy, talk</l><l n="17">Familiarly of you and of old times.</l></lg><lg n="2" type="verseparagraph"><l n="18">While I was seated, now some ten days past,</l><l n="19">Beneath those lofty firs, that overtop</l><l n="20">Their ancient neighbour, the old Steeple tower,</l><l n="21">The Vicar from his gloomy house hard by</l><l n="22">Came forth to greet me, and when he had ask&rsquo;d,</l><l n="23">&ldquo;How fares Joanna, that wild-hearted Maid!</l><l n="24"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> And when will she return to us?&rdquo; he paus&rsquo;d<del>,</del> <add ana="rmargin" resp="ww">;&sol;</add></l><l n="25"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&sol;,</add> And<add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add>after short exchange of village news,</l><l n="26">He with grave looks demanded, for what cause,</l><l n="27">Reviving obsolete Idolatry,</l><l n="28">I like a Runic Priest, in characters</l><l n="29">Of formidable size, had chisel&rsquo;d out</l><l n="30">Some uncouth name upon the native rock,</l><pb><milestone n="184" unit="page"><lb><lb><l n="31">Above the Rotha, by the forest side.</l><l n="32">&mdash;Now, by those dear immunities of heart</l><l n="33">Engender&rsquo;d between malice and true love,</l><l n="33" met="34">I was not loth to be so catechiz&rsquo;d,</l><l n="35">And this was my reply.&mdash;&ldquo;As it befel,</l><l n="36"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> One summer morning we had walk&rsquo;d abroad</l><l n="37"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> At break of day, Joanna and myself.</l><l n="38"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add>&mdash;&rsquo;Twas that delightful season, when the broom,</l><l n="39"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> Full flower&rsquo;d, and visible on every steep,</l><l n="40"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> Along the copses runs in veins of gold.</l><l n="41"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> Our pathway led us on to Rotha&rsquo;s banks<del>,</del> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">;&sol;</add></l><l n="42"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> And when we came in front of that tall rock</l><l n="43"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> Which looks towards the East, I there stopp&rsquo;d short,</l><l n="44"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> And trac&rsquo;d the lofty barrier with my eye</l><l n="45"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> From base to summit; such delight I found</l><l n="46"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> To note in shrub and tree, in stone and flower,</l><l n="47"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> That intermixture of delicious hues,</l><l n="48"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> Along so vast a surface, all at once,</l><l n="49"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> In one impression, by connecting force</l><pb><milestone n="185" unit="page"><lb><lb><l n="50"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> Of their own beauty, imag&rsquo;d in the heart.</l><l n="51"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> &mdash;When I had gaz&rsquo;d perhaps two minutes&rsquo; space,</l><l n="52"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> Joanna, looking in my eyes, beheld</l><l n="53"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> That ravishment of mine, and laugh&rsquo;d aloud.</l><l n="54"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> The rock, like something starting from a sleep,</l><l n="55"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> Took up the Lady&rsquo;s voice, and laugh&rsquo;d again:</l><l n="56"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> That ancient Woman seated on Helm-crag</l><l n="57"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> Was ready with her cavern; Hammar-Scar,</l><l n="58"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> And the tall Steep of Silver-How sent forth</l><l n="59"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> A noise of laughter; southern Loughrigg heard,</l><l n="60"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> And <del>Fairfied</del> <add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add>answer&rsquo;d with a mountain tone: <add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add><add place="rmargin" resp="ww" hand="dw">Fairfield</add></l><l n="61"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> Helvellyn far into the clear blue sky</l><l n="62"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> Carried the Lady&rsquo;s voice,&mdash;old Skiddaw blew</l><l n="63"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> His speaking trumpet;&mdash;back out of the clouds</l><l n="64"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> Of Glaramara southward came the voice;</l><l n="65"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> And Kirkstone toss&rsquo;d it from his misty head.</l><l n="66"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> Now whether,<add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add><add place="" resp="ww">&rdquo;</add> (said I to our cordial Friend</l><l n="67">Who in the hey-day of astonishment</l><l n="68">Smil&rsquo;d in my face)<add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add><add resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> this were in simple truth</l><pb><milestone n="186" unit="page"><lb><lb><l n="69"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> A work accomplish&rsquo;d by the brotherhood</l><l n="70"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> Of ancient mountains, or my ear was touch&rsquo;d</l><l n="71"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> With dreams and visionary impulses,</l><l n="72"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> I s not for me to tell; but sure I am</l><l n="73"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> That there was a loud uproar in the hills.</l><l n="74"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> And, while we both were listening, to my side</l><l n="75"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> The fair Joanna drew, <del>is</del> <add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add><add place="aboveline" resp="ww">as</add> if she wish&rsquo;d</l><l n="76"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> To shelter from some object of her fear.</l><l n="77"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> &mdash;And hence, long afterwards, when eighteen moons</l><l n="78"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> Were wasted, as I chanc&rsquo;d to walk alone</l><l n="79"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> Beneath this rock, at sun-rise, on a calm</l><l n="80"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> And silent morning, I sate down, and there,</l><l n="81"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> I n memory of affections old and true,</l><l n="82"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> I chissel&rsquo;d out in those rude characters</l><l n="83"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> Joanna&rsquo;s name upon the living stone.</l><l n="84"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> And I, and all who dwell by my fire-side  <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">Joanna&rsquo;s Rock</add></l><l n="85"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> Have call&rsquo;d the lovely rock, Joanna&rsquo;s Rock.&rdquo; <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">&sol;small capitals</add></l></lg><lb><lb><note><hi rend="small">NOTE.</hi><lb><lb>In Cumberland and Westmoreland are several Inscriptions, <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">,&sol;</add><lb><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&sol;,</add> upon the native rock<add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add>which<add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add>from the wasting of Time<add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add>and <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">,&sol; ,&sol;</add><pb><milestone n="187" unit="page"><lb><lb>the rudeness of the Workmanship<add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add>had been mistaken for  <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">,&sol;</add><lb>Runic.  They are without doubt Roman. <lb><lb>The Rotha, mentioned in this poem, is the River which<add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">,&sol;</add><lb>flowing through the Lakes of Grasmere and Ryd<del>o</del>le<add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add> falls <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">a&sol; ,&sol;</add><lb>into Wyndermere. On Helm-Crag, that impressive single <lb>Mountain at the head of the Vale of Grasmere, is a Rock <lb>which from mo<orig>s</orig>t points of view bears a striking resem-<lb>blance to an Old Woman cowering.  Close by this rock is <lb>one of those Fissures or Caverns, which in the language <lb>of the Country are called Dungeons. <del>The other Mountains <lb>either immediately surround the Vale of Grasmere, or <lb>belong to the same Cluster. </del><lb><del><add hand="dw" resp="ww">though at a considerable distance<lb>from it, belong to the same Cluster.</add></del><lb><add hand="dw" resp="ww">Most of the mountains here mentioned<lb>immediately surround the vale of<lb>Grasmere; of the others, some are at<lb>a considerable distance, but they<lb>belong to the same cluster.</add></note></body></text><pb><text><body><milestone n="188" unit="page"><lb><lb><head>III. </head><l n="1">There is an Eminence,&mdash;of these our hills</l><l n="2">The last that parleys with the setting sun.</l><l n="3">We can behold it from our Orchard-seat<del>,</del> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">;&sol;</add></l><l n="4">And, when at evening we pursue our walk</l><l n="5">Along the public way, this Cliff, so high</l><l n="6">Above us, and so distant in its height,</l><l n="7">Is visible, and often seems to send</l><l n="8">Its own deep quiet to restore our hearts.</l><l n="9">The meteors make of it a favorite haunt:</l><l n="10">The star of Jove, so beautiful and large</l><l n="11">In the mid heav&rsquo;ns, is never half so fair</l><l n="12">As when he shines above it.  &rsquo;Tis in truth</l><l n="13">The loneliest place we have among the clouds.</l><pb><milestone n="189" unit="page"><lb><lb><l n="14">And She who dwells with me, whom I have lov&rsquo;d</l><l n="15">With such communion, that no place on earth</l><l n="16">Can ever be a solitude to me,</l><l n="17">Hath said, this lonesome Peak shall bear my Name.</l></body></text><pb n="190"><text><body><milestone n="190" unit="page"><lb><lb><head>IV. </head><l n="1">A narrow girdle of rough stones and crags,</l><l n="2">A rude and natural causeway, interpos&rsquo;d</l><l n="3">Between the water and a winding slope</l><l n="4">Of copse and thicket, leaves the eastern shore</l><l n="5">Of Grasmere safe in its own privacy.</l><l n="6">And there, myself and two beloved Friends,</l><l n="7">One calm September morning, ere the mist</l><l n="8">Had altogether yielded to the sun,</l><l n="9">Saunter&rsquo;d on this retir&rsquo;d and difficult way.</l><l n="10">&mdash;&mdash;Ill suits road with one in haste, but we</l><l n="11">Play&rsquo;d with our time; and, as we stroll&rsquo;d along,</l><l n="12">It was our occupation to observe</l><l n="13">Such objects as the waves had toss&rsquo;d ashore,</l><pb><milestone n="191" unit="page"><lb><lb><l n="14">Feather, or leaf, or weed, or wither&rsquo;d bough,</l><l n="15">Each on the other heap&rsquo;d along the line</l><l n="16">Of the dry wreck. And<add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add>in our vacant mood, <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">,&sol;</add></l><l n="17">Not seldom did we stop to watch some tuft</l><l n="18">Of dandelion seed or thistle&rsquo;s beard,</l><l n="19">Which, seeming lifeless half, and half impell&rsquo;d</l><l n="20">By some internal feeling, skimm&rsquo;d along</l><l n="21">Close to the surface of the lake that lay</l><l n="22">Asleep in a dead calm<del>,</del> ran closely on <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">&mdash;&sol;</add></l><l n="23">Along the dead calm lake, now here, now there,</l><l n="24">In all its sportive wanderings all the while</l><l n="25">Making report of an invisible breeze</l><l n="26">That was its wings, its chariot, and its horse,</l><l n="27">Its very playmate, and its moving soul.</l><l n="28">&mdash;&mdash;And often, trifling with a privilege</l><l n="29">Alike indulg&rsquo;d to all, we paus&rsquo;d, one now,</l><l n="30">And now the other, to point out, perchance</l><l n="31">To pluck, some flower or water-weed, too fair</l><l n="32">Either to be divided from the place</l><pb><milestone n="192" unit="page"><lb><lb><l n="33">On which it grew, or to be left alone</l><l n="34">To its own beauty. Many such there are,</l><l n="35"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&sol;F &sol;F</add> Fair <del>f</del>erns and <del>f</del>lowers, and chiefly that tall<add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add><del>plant</del> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">Fern</add></l><l n="36">So stately, of the Queen Osmunda nam&rsquo;d<del>,</del> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">;&sol;</add></l><l n="37">Plant lovelier in its own retir&rsquo;d abode</l><l n="38">On Grasmere&rsquo;s beach, than Naid by the side</l><l n="39">Of Grecian brook, or Lady of the Mere</l><l n="40">Sole-sitting by the shores of old Romance.</l><l n="41">&mdash;&mdash;So fared we that sweet morning: from the fields<add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">,&sol;</add></l><l n="42">Meanwhile, a noise was heard, the busy mirth</l><l n="43">Of Reapers, Men and Women, Boys and Girls.</l><l n="44">Delighted much to listen to those sounds,</l><l n="45"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&sol;,</add> And<add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add>in the fashion which I have describ&rsquo;d,</l><l n="46">Feeding unthinking fancies, we advanc&rsquo;d</l><l n="47">Along the indented shore; when suddenly,</l><l n="48">Through a thin veil of glittering haze, we saw</l><l n="49">Before us on a point of jutting land</l><l n="50">The tall and upright figure of a Man</l><l n="51">Attir&rsquo;d in peasant&rsquo;s garb, who stood alone</l><pb><milestone n="193" unit="page"><lb><lb><l n="52">Angling beside the margin of the lake.</l><l n="53">That way we turn&rsquo;d our steps; nor was it long,</l><l n="54"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&sol;,</add>Ere<add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add>making ready comments on the sight</l><l n="55">Which then we saw, with one and the same voice</l><l n="56">We all cried out, that he must be indeed</l><l n="57">An idle man, who thus could lose a day</l><l n="58">Of the mid harvest, when the labourer&rsquo;s hire</l><l n="59">Is ample, and some little might be stor&rsquo;d</l><l n="60">Wherewith to chear him in the winter time. </l><l n="61">Thus talking of that Peasant we approach&rsquo;d</l><l n="62">Close to the spot where with his rod and line</l><l n="63">He stood alone; whereat he turn&rsquo;d his head</l><l n="64">To greet us&mdash;and we saw a <del>m</del>an worn down <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">&sol;M</add></l><l n="65">By sickness, gaunt and lean, with sunken cheeks</l><l n="66">And wasted limbs, his legs so long and lean</l><l n="67">That for my single self I look&rsquo;d at them,</l><l n="68">Forgetful of the body they sustain&rsquo;d.&mdash;</l><l n="69">Too weak to labour in the harvest field,</l><l n="70"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&sol;M</add> The <del>m</del>an was using his best skill to gain</l><pb><milestone n="194" unit="page"><lb><lb><l n="71">A pittance from the dead unfeeling lake</l><l n="72">That knew not of his wants. I will not say</l><l n="73">What thoughts immediately were ours, nor how</l><l n="74">The happy idleness of that sweet morn,</l><l n="75">With all its lovely images, was chang&rsquo;d</l><l n="76">To serious musing and to self-reproach.</l><l n="77">Nor did we fail to see within ourselves</l><l n="78">What need there is to be reserv&rsquo;d in speech,</l><l n="79">And temper all our thoughts with charity.</l><l n="80">&mdash;Therefore, unwilling to forget that day,</l><l n="81">My Friend, Myself, and She who then receiv&rsquo;d</l><l n="82">The same admonishment, have call&rsquo;d the place</l><l n="83">By a memorial name, uncouth indeed</l><l n="84">As e&rsquo;er by Mariner was given to Bay</l><l n="85">Or Foreland on a new-discover&rsquo;d coast,</l><l n="86">And P<hi rend="small">oint</hi> R<hi rend="small">ash-judgment</hi> is the Name it bears.</l></body></text><pb n="195"><text><body><milestone n="195" unit="page"><lb><lb><head>V. <lb><lb><emph>To M. H.</emph></head><l n="1">Our walk was far among the ancient trees :</l><l n="2">There was no road, nor any wood-man&rsquo;s path<del>,</del> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">;&sol;</add></l><l n="3">But the thick umbrage, checking the wild growth</l><l n="4">Of weed and sapling, on the soft green turf</l><l n="5">Beneath the branches of itself had made</l><l n="6">A track which brought us to a slip of lawn,</l><l n="7">And a small bed of water in the woods.</l><l n="8">All round this pool both flocks and herds might drink</l><l n="9">On its firm margin, even as from a <del>w</del>ell<add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">W&sol; ,&sol;</add></l><l n="10"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&sol;S</add> Or some <del>s</del>tone-bason which the Herdsman&rsquo;s hand</l><l n="11">Had shap&rsquo;d for their refreshment<del>,</del> nor did sun <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">:&sol;</add></l><pb><milestone n="196" unit="page"><lb><lb><l n="12">Or wind from any quarter ever come<add place="rmargin" resp="ww"><add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">,&sol;</add></add></l><l n="13"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&sol;,</add></add> But as a blessing<add><add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add></add>to this calm recess,</l><l n="14">This glade of water and this one green field.</l><l n="15">The spot was made by Nature for herself:</l><l n="16">The travellers know it not, and &rsquo;twill remain</l><l n="17">Unknown to them; but it is beautiful,</l><l n="18">And if a man should plant his cottage near,</l><l n="19">Should sleep beneath the shelter of its trees,</l><l n="20">And blend its waters with his daily meal,</l><l n="21">He would so love it that in his death-hour</l><l n="22">Its image would survive among his thoughts<del>,</del> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww"><add place="rmargin" resp="ww">:&sol;</add></add></l><l n="23">And, therefore, my sweet M<hi rend="small">ary</hi>, this still nook</l><l n="24">With all its beeches we have named from You.</l><lb><note><add resp="ww">After the above Poems Insert the <lb>following. 1st &ldquo;Lines written when<lb>Sailing in a Boat at Evening&rdquo; See 1st <lb>vol Page 101.<lb>2nd &ldquo;Remembrance of Collins&rdquo; 1st vol P. 103<lb>3rd &ldquo;The two Thieves&rdquo; from Page 92<lb>of this second volume.<lb>4th the Poem entitled Louisa<lb>which I shall here insert as<lb>follows-</add></note></body></text><pb n="199"><text><body><milestone n="199" unit="page"><lb><lb><head><emph>MICHAEL, <lb><lb><hi rend="small">A PASTORAL POEM. </hi></emph></head><lg n="1" type="verseparagraph" part="I"><l n="1">If from the public way you turn your steps</l><l n="2">Up the tumultuous brook of Green-head Gill,</l><l n="3">You will suppose that with an upright path</l><l n="4">Your feet must struggle; in such bold ascent</l><l n="5">The pastoral Mountains front you, face to face.</l><l n="6">But, courage! for beside that boisterous Brook</l><l n="7">The mountains have all open&rsquo;d out themselves,</l><l n="8">And made a hidden valley of their own.</l><l n="9">No habitation there is seen; but such</l><l n="10">As journey thither find themselves alone</l><l n="11">With a few sheep, with rocks and stones, and kites</l><l n="12">That overhead are sailing in the sky.</l></lg><pb><milestone n="200" unit="page"><lb><lb><lg n="1" part="M" type="verseparagraph"><l n="13">It is in truth an utter solitude, </l><l n="14">Nor should I have made mention of this Dell</l><l n="15">But for one object which you might pass by,</l><l n="16">Might see and notice not. Beside the brook</l><l n="17">There is a straggling heap of unhewn stones!</l><l n="18">And to that place a story appertains,</l><l n="19">Which, though it be ungarnish&rsquo;d with events,</l><l n="20">Is not unfit, I deem, for the fire-side,</l><l n="21">Or for the summer shade. It was the first,</l><l n="22">The earliest of those tales that spake to me</l><l n="23">Of Shepherds, dwellers in the vallies, men</l><l n="24">Whom I already lov&rsquo;d, not verily</l><l n="25">For their own sakes, but for the fields and hills</l><l n="26">Where was their occupation and abode.</l><l n="27">And hence this Tale, while I was yet a <del>b</del>oy <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">B&sol;</add></l><l n="28">Careless of books, yet having felt the power</l><l n="29">Of Nature, by the gentle agency</l><l n="30">Of natural objects led me on to feel</l><l n="31">For passions that were not my own, and think</l></lg><pb><milestone n="201" unit="page"><lb><lb><lg n="1" part="F" type="verseparagraph"><l n="32"><add place="inline" resp="ww">(</add><add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add> At random and imperfectly indeed <add place="inline" resp="ww">)</add><add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add></l><l n="33"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&sol;,</add> On man<del>;</del> the heart of man<add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add><add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add>and human life. <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">,&sol;</add></l><l n="34">Therefore, although it be a history</l><l n="35">Homely and rude, I will relate the same</l><l n="36">For the delight of a few natural hearts,</l><l n="37">And with yet fonder feeling, for the sake</l><l n="38">Of youthful Poets, who among these Hills</l><l n="39">Will be my second self when I am gone.</l></lg><lb><lb><lg n="2" part="I" type="verseparagraph"><l n="40">U<hi rend="small">PON</hi> the Forest-side in Grasmere Vale</l><l n="41">There dwelt a Shepherd, Michael was his name,</l><l n="42"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">O&sol;M</add> An <del>o</del>ld <del>m</del>an, stout of heart, and strong of limb.</l><l n="43">His bodily frame had been from youth to age</l><l n="44">Of an unusual strength: his mind was keen</l><l n="45">Intense and frugal, apt for all affairs,</l><l n="46">And in his Shepherd&rsquo;s calling he was prompt</l><l n="47">And watchful more than ordinary men.</l></lg><pb><milestone n="202" unit="202"><lb><lb><lg n="2" part="F" type="verseparagraph"><l n="48">Hence he had learn&rsquo;d the meaning of all winds,</l><l n="49"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&sol;;</add> Of blasts of every tone<del>,</del> and<add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add>often-times<add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">,&sol;,&sol;</add></l><l n="50">When others heeded not, He heard the South</l><l n="51">Make subterraneous music, like the noise</l><l n="52">Of Bagpipers on distant Highland hills;</l><l n="53">The Shepherd, at such warning, of his flock</l><l n="54">Bethought him, and he to himself would say<add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">,&sol;</add></l><l n="55"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&sol;&ldquo;</add><add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add> The winds are now devising work for me!<add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add><add place="lrmargin" resp="ww"> &rdquo;&sol;</add></l><l n="56"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&sol;, &sol;,</add> And<add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add>truly<add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add>at all times the storm, that drives</l><l n="57">The Traveller to a shelter, summon&rsquo;d him</l><l n="58">Up to the mountains: he had been alone</l><l n="59">Amid the heart of many thousand mists<add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add><add place="rmargin" resp="ww"> ,&sol;</add></l><l n="60">That came to him and left him on the heights.</l><l n="61">So liv&rsquo;d he till his eightieth year was pass&rsquo;d.</l></lg><lg n="3" part="I" type="verseparagraph"><l n="62">And grossly that man errs, who should suppose</l><l n="63">That the green Valleys, and the Streams and Rocks</l><l n="64">Were things indifferent to the Shepherd&rsquo;s thoughts. </l><l n="65">Fields, where with chearful spirits he had breath&rsquo;d</l></lg><pb><milestone n="203" unit="page"><lb><lb><lg part="F" type="verseparagraph"><l n="66">The common air; the hills, which he so oft</l><l n="67">Had climb&rsquo;d with vigorous steps; which had impress&rsquo;d</l><l n="68">So many incidents upon his mind</l><l n="69">Of hardship, skill or courage, joy or fear;</l><l n="70">Which like a book preserv&rsquo;d the memory</l><l n="71">Of the dumb animals, whom he had sav&rsquo;d,</l><l n="72">Had fed or shelter&rsquo;d, linking to such acts,</l><l n="73">So grateful in themselves, the certainty</l><l n="74">Of honorable gains; these fields, these hills<add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add><add place="rmargin" resp="ww"> ,&sol;</add></l><l n="75">Which were his living Being, even more</l><l n="76"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&sol;n</add> Tha<add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add><del>n</del> his own <del>B</del>lood&mdash;what could they less? had laid <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">b&sol;</add></l><l n="77">Strong hold on his affections, were to him</l><l n="78">A pleasurable feeling of blind love,</l><l n="79">The pleasure which there is in life itself.</l></lg><lg n="4" part="I" type="verseparagraph"><l n="80">He had not passed his days in singleness.</l><l n="81">He had a Wife, a comely Matron, old</l><l n="82">Though younger than himself full twenty years.</l><l n="83">She was a woman of a stirring life</l></lg><pb><milestone n="204" unit="page"><lb><lb><lg part="M"><l n="84">Whose heart was in her house: two wheels she had</l><l n="85">Of antique form, this large for spin<add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add>ing wool, <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">n&sol;</add></l><l n="86">That small for flax, and if one wheel had rest,</l><l n="87">It was because the other was at work.</l><l n="88">The Pair had but one Inmate in their house,</l><l n="89">An only Child, who had been born to them</l><l n="90">When Michael telling o&rsquo;er his years began</l><l n="91">To deem that he was old, in Shepherd&rsquo;s phrase,</l><l n="92">With one foot in the grave. This only <del rend="ink" resp="ww">s</del>on, <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">S&sol;</add></l><l n="93"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww"><add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add>Sheep-dogs</add> With two brave<add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add><del rend="ink" resp="ww">sheep dogs</del> tried in many a storm,</l><l n="94">The one of an inestimable worth,</l><l n="95">Made all their Household. I may truly say,</l><l n="96">That they were as a proverb in the vale</l><l n="97">For endless industry. When day was gone,</l><l n="98">And from their occupations out of doors</l><l n="99">The Son and Father were come home, even then</l><l n="100"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&sol;;</add> Their labour did not cease<del rend="ink" resp="ww">,</del> unless when all</l><l n="101">Turn&rsquo;d to their cleanly supper-board, and there<add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">,&sol;</add></l><l n="102">Each with a mess of pottage and skimm&rsquo;d milk,</l></lg><pb><milestone n="205" unit="page"><lb><lb><lg part="F"><l n="103">Sate round their basket pil&rsquo;d with oaten cakes,</l><l n="104">And their plain home-made cheese. Yet when their meal</l><l n="105">Was ended, L<hi rend="small">UKE</hi> (for so the Son was nam&rsquo;d)</l><l n="106">And his old Father, both betook themselves</l><l n="107">To such convenient work, as might employ</l><l n="108">Their hands by the fire-side; perhaps to card</l><l n="109">Wool for the House-wife&rsquo;s spindle, or repair</l><l n="110">Some injury done to sickle, flail, or scythe,</l><l n="111">Or other implement of house or field.</l></lg><lg n="5" part="I" type="verseparagraph"><l n="112">Down from the cieling by the chimney&rsquo;s edge,</l><l n="113">Which in our ancient uncouth country style</l><l n="114">Did with a huge projection overbrow</l><l n="115">Large space beneath, as duly as the light</l><l n="116">Of day grew dim, the House-wife hung a <del rend="ink" resp="ww">l</del>amp; <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">L&sol;</add></l><l n="117">An aged utensil, which had perform&rsquo;d</l><l n="118">Service beyond all others of its kind.</l><l n="119">Early at evening did it burn and late,</l><l n="120">Surviving Comrade of uncounted Hours</l></lg><pb><milestone n="206" unit="page"><lb><lb><lg part="M"><l n="121">Which going by from year to year had found</l><l n="122">And left the Couple neither gay perhaps</l><l n="123">Nor chearful, yet with objects and with hopes<add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww"> ,&sol;</add></l><l n="124">Living a life of eager industry.</l><l n="125">And now, when L<hi rend="small">UKE</hi> was in his eighteenth year,</l><l n="126">There by the light of this old <del rend="ink" resp="ww">l</del>amp they sate, <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">L&sol;</add></l><l n="127">Father and Son, while late into the night</l><l n="128">The House-wife plied her own peculiar work,</l><l n="129">Making the cottage thro&rsquo; the silent hours</l><l n="130">Murmur as with the sound of summer flies.</l><l n="131">Not with a waste of words, but for the sake</l><l n="132">Of pleasure, which I know that I shall give</l><l n="133">To many living now, I of this Lamp</l><l n="134">Speak thus minutely: for there are no few</l><l n="135">Whose memories will bear witness to my tale.</l><l n="136">The Light was famous in its neighbourhood,</l><l n="137">And was a public Symbol of the life,</l><l n="138">The thrifty Pair had liv&rsquo;d. For, as it chanc&rsquo;d,</l><l n="139">Their Cottage on a plot of rising ground</l></lg><pb><milestone n="207" unit="page"><lb><lb><lg part="F" type="verseparagraph"><l n="140">Stood single, with large prospect<add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add>North and South, <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">,&sol;</add></l><l n="141">High into Easedale, up to Dunmal-Raise,</l><l n="142">And Westward to the village near the Lake.</l><l n="143">And from this constant light so regular</l><l n="144">And so far seen, the House itself<add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add>by all <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">,&sol;</add></l><l n="145">Who dwelt within the limits of the vale,</l><l n="146">Both old and young, was nam&rsquo;d The Evening Star. <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">E<hi>vening </hi>S<hi>tar</hi></add><lb><add place="rmargin" resp="ww">						small capitals</add></l></lg><lg n="6" part="I" type="verseparagraph"><l n="147">Thus living on through such a length of years,</l><l n="148">The Shepherd, if he lov&rsquo;d himself, must needs</l><l n="149">Have lov&rsquo;d his Help-mate; but to Michael&rsquo;s heart</l><l n="150">This Son of his old age was yet more dear&mdash;</l><l n="151">Effect which might perhaps have been produc&rsquo;d</l><l n="152">By that instinctive tenderness, the same</l><l n="153">Blind Spirit, which is in the blood of all<del rend="ink" resp="ww">,</del> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">&sol;&mdash;</add></l><l n="154">Or that a child, more than all other gifts,</l><l n="155">Brings hope with it, and forward-looking thoughts,</l><l n="156">And stirrings of inquietude, when they</l><l n="157">By tendency of nature needs must fail.</l></lg><pb><milestone n="208" unit="page"><lb><lb><lg n="6" part="F" type="verseparagraph"><l n="158">From such, and other causes, to the thoughts</l><l n="159">Of the old Man his only Son was now</l><l n="160">The dearest object that he knew on earth.</l><l n="161">Exceeding was the love he bare to him,</l><l n="162">His Heart and his Heart&rsquo;s joy!  For oftentimes</l><l n="163">Old Michael, while he was a babe in arms,</l><l n="164">Had done him female service, not alone</l><l n="165">For dalliance and delight, as is the use</l><l n="166">Of Fathers, but with patient mind enforc&rsquo;d</l><l n="167">To acts of tenderness; and he had rock&rsquo;d</l><l n="168">His cradle with a woman&rsquo;s gentle hand.</l></lg><lg n="7" part="I" type="verseparagraph"><l n="169"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&sol;,</add> And<add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add>in a later time, ere yet the Boy</l><l n="170">Had put on Boy&rsquo;s attire, did Michael love,</l><l n="171">Albeit of a stern unbending mind,</l><l n="172">To have the young one in his sight, when he</l><l n="173">Had work by his own door, or when he sate</l><l n="174">With sheep before him on his Shepherd&rsquo;s stool,</l><l n="175">Beneath that large old Oak, which near their door</l></lg><pb><milestone n="209" unit="page"><lb><lb><lg n="7" part="F" type="verseparagraph"><l n="176">Stood, and from its enormous breadth of shade</l><l n="177">Chosen for the Shearer&rsquo;s covert from the sun,</l><l n="178">Thence in our rustic dialect was call&rsquo;d</l><l n="179">The C<hi rend="small">lipping</hi> T<hi rend="small">ree</hi>*, a name which yet it bears.</l><l n="180">There, while they two were sitting in the shade,</l><l n="181">With others round them, earnest all and blithe,</l><l n="182">Would Michael exercise his heart with looks</l><l n="183">Of fond correction and reproof bestow&rsquo;d</l><l n="184">Upon the <del rend="ink" resp="ww">c</del>hild, if he disturb&rsquo;d the sheep</l><l n="185">By catching at their legs, or with his shouts</l><l n="186">Scar&rsquo;d them, while they lay still beneath the shears.</l></lg><lg n="8" part="I" type="verseparagraph"><l n="187">And when by Heaven&rsquo;s good grace the Boy grew up</l><l n="188">A healthy Lad, and carried in his cheek</l><l n="189">Two steady roses that were five years old,</l><l n="190">Then Michael from a winter coppice cut</l><l n="191">With his own hand a sapling, which he hoop&rsquo;d</l></lg><note>* Clipping is the word used in the North of England for <lb>shearing.</note><pb><milestone n="210" unit="page"><lb><lb><lg n="8" part="F" type="verseparagraph"><l n="192">With iron, making it throughout in all</l><l n="193">Due requisites a perfect Shepherd&rsquo;s Staff,</l><l n="194">And gave it to the Boy; wherewith equipp&rsquo;d</l><l n="195">He as a Watchman oftentimes was plac&rsquo;d</l><l n="196">At gate or gap, to stem or turn the flock<del rend="ink" resp="ww">,</del> <add place="lmargin" resp="ww">;&sol;</add></l><l n="197">And to his office prematurely call&rsquo;d</l><l n="198"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">U</add> There stood the <del rend="ink" resp="ww">u</del>rchin, as you will divine,</l><l n="199">Something between a hindrance and a help,</l><l n="200">And for this cause not always, I believe,</l><l n="201">Receiving from his Father hire of praise,</l><l n="202">Though nought was left undone, which staff or voice,</l><l n="203">Or looks, or threatening gestures could perform.</l></lg><lg n="9" part="I" type="verseparagraph"><l n="204">  But soon as Luke, full ten years old, could stand</l><l n="205">Against the mountain blasts, and to the heights,</l><l n="206">Not fearing toil, nor length of weary ways,</l><l n="207">He with his Father daily went, and they</l><l n="208">Were as companions, why should I relate</l><l n="209">That objects which the Shepherd lov&rsquo;d before</l><l n="210">Were dearer now? that from the Boy there came</l><pb><milestone n="*209" unit="page"><lb><lb><l n="211">Feelings and emanations, things which were</l><l n="212">Light to the sun and music to the wind;</l><l n="213">And that the Old Man&rsquo;s heart seem&rsquo;d born again.</l></lg><lg n="10" type="verseparagraph"><l n="214"> Thus in his Father&rsquo;s sight the Boy grew up:</l><l n="215">And now when he had reach&rsquo;d his eighteenth year,</l><l n="216">He was his comfort and his daily hope.</l></lg><pb n="*210"><milestone n="*210" unit="page"><lb><lb><lb><lb><lb><lb><lb><lb><lb><lb><lb><lb><lb><lb><lb><lb><lb><lb><lb><lb><lb><lb><lb><lg n="11" part="I"><l n="217">WHILE in the fashion which I have described</l><l n="218"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&sol;H</add>This simple <del rend="ink" resp="ww">h</del>ousehold thus were living on</l><l n="219">From day to day, to Michael&rsquo;s ear there came</l></lg><pb n="211"><milestone n="211" unit="page"><lb><lb><lg n="11" part="M" type="verseparagraph"><l n="220">Distressful tidings. Long before the time</l><l n="221">Of which I speak, the Shepherd had been bound</l><l n="222">In surety for his Brother&rsquo;s Son, a man</l><l n="223">Of an industrious life, and ample means,</l><l n="224">But unforeseen misfortunes suddenly</l><l n="225">Had press&rsquo;d upon him, and old Michael now</l><l n="226">Was summon&rsquo;d to discharge the forfeiture,</l><l n="227">A grievous penalty, but little less</l><l n="228">Than half his substance. This unlook&rsquo;d for claim<add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add><add place="rmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww"> ,&sol;</add></l><l n="229">At the first hearing, for a moment took</l><l n="230">More hope out of his life than he supposed</l><l n="231">That any old man ever could have lost.</l><l n="232">As soon as he had gather&rsquo;d so much strength</l><l n="233">That he could look his trouble in the face,</l><l n="234">It seem&rsquo;d that his sole refuge was to sell</l><l n="235">A portion of his patrimonial fields.</l><l n="236">Such was his first resolve; he thought again,</l><l n="237">And his heart fail&rsquo;d him. &ldquo;Isabel,&rdquo; said he,</l></lg><pb><milestone n="212" unit="page"><lb><lb><lg n="9" part="M" type="verseparagraph"><l n="238">Two evenings after he had heard the news,</l><l n="239">&ldquo;I have been toiling more than seventy years,</l><l n="240"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add>And in the open sun-shine of God&rsquo;s love</l><l n="241"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add>Have we all liv&rsquo;d, yet if these fields of ours</l><l n="242"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add>Should pass into a Stranger&rsquo;s hand, I think</l><l n="243"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add>That I could not lie quiet in my grave.</l><l n="244"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add>Our lot is a hard lot; the Sun itself</l><l n="245"><add place="lmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add>Has scarcely been more diligent than I,</l><l n="246"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add>And I have liv&rsquo;d to be a fool at last</l><l n="247"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add>To my own family. An evil Man</l><l n="248"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add>That was, and made an evil choice, if he</l><l n="249"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add>Were false to us; and if he were not false,</l><l n="250"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add>There are ten thousand to whom loss like this</l><l n="251"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add>Had been no sorrow. I forgive him&mdash;but</l><l n="252"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add>&rsquo;Twere better to be dumb than to talk thus.</l><l n="253"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add>When I began, my purpose was to speak</l><l n="254"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add>Of remedies and of a chearful hope.</l><l n="256"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add>Our Luke shall leave us, Isabel; the land</l></lg><pb><milestone n="213" unit="page"><lb><lb><lg n="9" part="M" type="verseparagraph"><l n="257"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add>Shall not go from us, and it shall be free<del>,</del></l><l n="258"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add>He shall possess it, free as is the wind</l><l n="259"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add>That passes over it. We have, thou knowest,</l><l n="260"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add>Another Kinsman<del rend="ink" resp="ww">,</del><add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add> he will be our friend <add place="rmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww"><add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add>&mdash;</add></l><l n="261"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add>In this distress. He is a prosperous man,</l><l n="262"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add>Thriving in trade<del rend="ink" resp="ww">,</del> and Luke to him shall go,</l><l n="263"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add>And with his Kinsman&rsquo;s help and his own thrift,</l><l n="264"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add>He quickly will repair this loss, and then</l><l n="265"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add>May come again to us. If here he stay,</l><l n="266"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add>What can be done? Where every one is poor</l><l n="267"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add>What can be gain&rsquo;d?&rdquo;  At this, the old man paus&rsquo;d,</l><l n="268">And Isabel sate silent, for her mind</l><l n="269">Was busy, looking back into past times.</l><l n="270">There&rsquo;s Richard Bateman, thought she to herself,</l><l n="271"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">P</add> He was a <del>p</del>arish-boy&mdash;at the church-door</l><l n="272">They made a gathering for him, shillings, pence,</l><l n="273">And halfpennies, wherewith the Neighbours bought</l><l n="274">A Basket, which they fill&rsquo;d with Pedlar&rsquo;s wares<del rend="ink" resp="ww">,</del> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">;&sol;</add></l><l n="275">And with this Basket on his arm, the Lad</l></lg><pb><milestone n="214" unit="page"><lb><lb><lg n="9" part="F" type="verseparagraph"><l n="276">Went up to London, found a Master there,</l><l n="277">Who out of many chose the trusty Boy</l><l n="278">Togo and overlook his merchandise</l><l n="279">Beyond the seas, where he grew wond&rsquo;rous rich,</l><l n="280">And left estates and monies to the poor,</l><l n="281">And at his birth-place built a Chapel, floor&rsquo;d</l><l n="282">With Marble, which he sent from foreign lands.</l><l n="283">These thoughts, and many others of like sort,</l><l n="284">Pass&rsquo;d quickly thro&rsquo; the mind of Isabel,</l><l n="285">And her face brighten&rsquo;d. The Old Man was glad,</l><l n="286">And thus resum&rsquo;d.  &ldquo;Well! Isabel, this scheme</l><l n="287"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> These two days has been meat and drink to me.</l><l n="288"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> Far more than we have lost is left us yet.</l><l n="289"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> &mdash;We have enough&mdash;I wish indeed that I</l><l n="290"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> Were younger, but this hope is a good hope.</l><l n="291"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> &mdash;Make ready Luke&rsquo;s best garments, of the best</l><l n="292"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> Buy for him more, and let us send him forth</l><l n="293"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> To-morrow, or the next day, or to-night:</l><l n="294"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> &mdash;If he could go, the Boy should go to-night.&rdquo;</l></lg><pb><milestone n="215" unit="page"><lb><lb><lg n="10" part="I" type="verseparagraph"><l n="295">Here Michael ceas&rsquo;d, and to the fields went forth</l><l n="296">With a light heart. The House-wife for five days</l><l n="297">Was restless morn and night, and all day long</l><l n="298">Wrought on with her best fingers to prepare</l><l n="299">Things needful for the journey of her Son.</l><l n="300">But Isabel was glad when Sunday came</l><l n="301"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&sol;:</add> To stop her in her work<del rend="ink" resp="ww">;</del> for, when she lay</l><l n="302">By Michael&rsquo;s side, she for the two last nights</l><l n="303">Heard him, how he was troubled in his sleep:</l><l n="304">And when they rose at morning she could see</l><l n="305">That all his hopes were gone. That day at noon</l><l n="306">She said to Luke, while they two by themselves</l><l n="307">Were sitting at the door, &ldquo;Thou must not go,</l><l n="308"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> We have no other Child but thee to lose,</l><l n="309"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> None to remember&mdash;do not go away,</l><l n="310"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> For if thou leave thy Father he will die.&rdquo;</l><l n="311">The Lad made answer with a jocund voice<del rend="ink" resp="ww">, </del> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">;&sol;</add></l><l n="312">And Isabel, when she had told her fears,</l><l n="313">Recover&rsquo;d heart. That evening her best fare</l></lg><pb><milestone n="216" unit="page"><lb><lb><lg n="10" type="verseparagraph" part="F"><l n="314">Did she bring forth, and all together sate</l><l n="315">Like happy people round a Christmas fire.</l></lg><lg n="11" part="I" type="verseparagraph"><l n="316">Next morning Isabel resum&rsquo;d her work<del rend="ink" resp="ww">,</del> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">;&sol;</add></l><l n="317">And all the ensuing week the house appear&rsquo;d</l><l n="318">As cheerful as a grove in Spring: at length</l><l n="319">The expected letter from their Kinsman came,</l><l n="320">With kind assurances that he would do</l><l n="321">His utmost for the welfare of the Boy,</l><l n="322">To which requests were added that forthwith</l><l n="323">He might be sent to him. Ten times or more</l><l n="324">The letter was read over; Isabel</l><l n="325">Went forth to shew it to the neighbours round:</l><l n="326">Nor was there at that time on English Land</l><l n="327">A prouder heart than Luke&rsquo;s. When Isabel</l><l n="328">Had to her house return&rsquo;d, the Old Man said,</l><l n="329">&ldquo;He shall depart to-morrow.&rdquo; To this word</l><l n="330">The House-wife answer&rsquo;d, talking much of things</l><l n="331">Which, if at such short notice he should go,</l></lg><pb><milestone n="217" unit="page"><lb><lb><lg n="11" part="F" type="verseparagraph"><l n="332">Would surely be forgotten. But at length</l><l n="333">She gave consent, and Michael was at ease.</l></lg><lg n="12" part="I" type="verseparagraph"><l n="334">Near the tumultuous brook of Green-head Gill,</l><l n="335">In that deep Valley, Michael had design&rsquo;d</l><l n="336"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&sol;;</add> To build a Sheep-fold<del rend="ink" resp="ww">,</del> and, before he heard</l><l n="337">The tidings of his melancholy loss,</l><l n="338">For this same purpose he had gathered up</l><l n="339">A heap of stones, which close to the brook side</l><l n="340">Lay thrown together, ready for the work.</l><l n="341">With Luke that evening thitherward he walk&rsquo;d;</l><l n="342">And soon as they had reach&rsquo;d the place he stopp&rsquo;d,</l><l n="343">And thus the Old Man spake to him.  &ldquo;My Son,</l><l n="344"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> To-morrow thou wilt leave me<del rend="ink" resp="ww">;</del> with full heart <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">:&sol;</add></l><l n="345"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> I look upon thee, for thou art the same</l><l n="346"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> That wert a promise to me ere thy birth,</l><l n="347"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> And all thy life hast been my daily joy.</l><l n="348"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> I will relate to thee some little part</l><l n="349"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> Of our two histories; &rsquo;twill do thee good</l></lg><pb><milestone n="218" unit="page"><lb><lb><lg n="11" part="F" type="verseparagraph"><l n="350"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> When thou art from me, even if I should speak</l><l n="351"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> Of things thou canst not know of.&mdash;&mdash;After thou</l><l n="352"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> First cam&rsquo;st into the world, as it befal<del rend="ink" resp="ww">l</del>s <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">d</add></l><l n="353"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> To new-born infants, thou didst sleep away</l><l n="354"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> Two days, and blessings from thy Father&rsquo;s tongue</l><l n="355"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> Then fell upon thee. Day by day pass&rsquo;d on,</l><l n="356"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> And still I lov&rsquo;d thee with encreasing love.</l><l n="357"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> Never to living ear came sweeter sounds</l><l n="358"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> Than when I heard thee by our own fire-side</l><l n="359"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> First uttering without words a natural tune,</l><l n="360"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> When thou, a feeding babe, didst in thy joy</l><l n="361"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> Sing at thy Mother&rsquo;s breast. Month follow&rsquo;d month,</l><l n="362"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> And in the open fields my life was pass&rsquo;d</l><l n="363"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> And in the mountains, else I think that thou</l><l n="364"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> Hadst been brought up upon thy <del rend="ink" resp="ww">f</del>ather&rsquo;s knees. <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">F&sol;</add></l><l n="365"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> &mdash;But we were playmates, Luke; among these hills,</l><l n="366"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> As well thou know&rsquo;st, in us the old and young</l><l n="367"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> Have play&rsquo;d together, nor with me didst thou</l><l n="368"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> Lack any pleasure which a boy can know.&rdquo;</l></lg><pb><milestone n="219" unit="page"><lb><lb><lg n="12" part="I" type="verseparagraph"><l n="369">Luke had a manly heart; but at these words</l><l n="370">He sobb&rsquo;d aloud; the Old Man grasp&rsquo;d his hand,</l><l n="371">And said, &ldquo;Nay do not take it so&mdash;I see</l><l n="372"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> That these are things of which I need not speak.</l><l real="373" n="373"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> &mdash;Even to the utmost I have been to thee</l><l n="374"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> A kind and a good Father: and herein</l><l n="375"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add>I but repay a gift which I myself</l><l n="376"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&sol;; &ldquo;</add>Receiv&rsquo;d at others hands<del rend="ink" resp="ww">,</del> for, though now old</l><l n="377"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> Beyond the common life of man, I still</l><l n="378"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> Remember them who lov&rsquo;d me in my youth.</l><l n="379"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> Both of them sleep together: here they liv&rsquo;d<add place="belowline" resp="ww">^</add><add place="rmargin" rend="ink" resp="ww"> ,&sol;</add></l><l n="380"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> As all their Forefathers had done, and when</l><l n="381"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> At length their time was come, they were not loth</l><l n="382"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> To give their bodies to the family mold.</l><l n="383"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> I wish&rsquo;d that thou should&rsquo;st live the life they liv&rsquo;d.</l><l n="384"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> But &rsquo;tis a long time to look back, my Son,</l><l n="385"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> And see so little gain from sixty years.</l><l n="386"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> These fields were burthen&rsquo;d when they came to me;</l><l n="387"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> &rsquo;Till I was forty years of age, not more</l></lg><pb><milestone n="220" unit="page"><lb><lb><lg n="12" type="verseparagraph" part="M"><l n="388"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> Than half of my inheritance was mine.</l><l n="389"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> I toil&rsquo;d and toil&rsquo;d; God bless&rsquo;d me in my work,</l><l n="390"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> And &rsquo;till these three weeks past the land was free.</l><l n="391"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> &mdash;It looks as if it never could endure</l><l n="392"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> Another Master.  Heaven forgive me, Luke,</l><l n="393"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> If I judge ill for thee, but it seems good</l><l n="394"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> That thou should&rsquo;st go.&rdquo; At this the Old Man paus&rsquo;d<del rend="ink" resp="ww">,</del> <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">;&sol;</add></l><l n="395">Then, pointing to the Stones near which they stood,</l><l n="396">Thus, after a short silence, he resum&rsquo;d:</l><l n="397"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&sol;;&mdash;</add> &ldquo;This was a work for us<del rend="ink" resp="ww">,</del> and now, my Son,</l><l n="398"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> It is a work for me. But, lay one Stone&mdash;</l><l n="399"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> Here, lay it for me, Luke, with thine own hands.</l><l n="400"><del rend="ink" resp="ww">I for the purpose brought thee to this place.</del></l><l n="401"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> Nay, Boy, be of good hope:&mdash;we both may live</l><l n="402"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> To see a better day. At eighty-four</l><l n="403"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> I still am strong and stout;&mdash;do thou thy part,</l><l n="404"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> I will do mine.&mdash;I will begin again</l><l n="405"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> With many tasks that were resign&rsquo;d to thee;</l><l n="406"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> Up to the heights, and in among the storms,</l></lg><pb><milestone n="221" unit="page"><lb><lb><lg n="12" part="M" type="verseparagraph"><l n="407"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> Will I without thee go again, and do</l><l n="408"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> All works which I was wont to do alone,</l><l n="409"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> Before I knew thy face.&mdash;&mdash;Heaven bless thee, Boy!</l><l n="410"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> Thy heart these two weeks has been beating fast</l><l n="411"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> With many hopes&mdash;it should be so&mdash;yes&mdash;yes&mdash;</l><l n="412"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> I knew that thou could&rsquo;st never have a wish</l><l n="413"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> To leave me, Luke, thou hast been bound to me</l><l n="414"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> Only by links of love, when thou art gone</l><l n="415"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> What will be left to us!&mdash;But, I forget</l><l n="416"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> My purposes.  Lay now the corner-stone,</l><l n="417"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> As I requested, and hereafter, Luke,</l><l n="418"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> When thou art gone away, should evil men</l><l n="419"><del>Be thy companions, let this Sheep-fold be</del></l><l n="420"><del>Thy anchor and thy shield; amid all fear</del></l><l n="421"><del>And all temptation, let it be to thee</del></l><l n="422"><del>An emblem of the life thy Fathers liv&rsquo;d,</del></l><l n="423"><del>Who, being innocent, did for that cause</del></l><l n="424"><del>Bestir them in good deeds. Now, fare thee well&mdash;</del></l><l n="425"><del>When thou return&rsquo;st, thou in this place wilt see</del></l><l n="419"><add place="pasteover" resp="ww" hand="dw">Be thy companions think of me, my Son,</add></l><l n="420"><add hand="dw" place="pasteover" resp="ww">And of this moment<del>:</del><add>;</add> hither turn thy thoughts</add></l><l n="421"><add hand="dw" place="pasteover" resp="ww">And God will strengthen thee<add>: a</add>mid all fear</add></l><l n="422"><add hand="dw" place="pasteover" resp="ww">And all temptation, <del>let it be to thee</del> <add hand="dw" place="interlinear" rend="ink" resp="ww">Luke, I pray that thou</add></add></l><l n="423"><add hand="dw" place="pasteover" resp="ww"><del hand="dw" rend="ink" resp="ww">An emblem of the</del><add hand="dw" place="interlinear" rend="ink" resp="ww">May&rsquo;st bear in mind the</add>^life thy Fathers liv&rsquo;d,</add></l><l n="424"><add hand="dw" place="pasteover" resp="ww">Who, being innocent, did for that cause</add></l><l n="425"><add hand="dw" place="pasteover" resp="ww">Bestir them in good deeds. Now, fare thee well:</add></l><l n="426"><add hand="dw" place="pasteover" resp="ww">When thou return&rsquo;st, thou in this place wilt see</add></l></lg><pb><milestone n="222" unit="page"><lb><lb><lg><l n="427"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> A work which is not here<del rend="ink" resp="ww">,</del> a covenant <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">;&sol;</add></l><l n="428"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add> &rsquo;Twill be between us&mdash;&mdash; but whatever fate</l><l n="429"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&sol;d &ldquo;</add>Befal<del rend="ink" resp="ww">l</del> thee, I shall love thee to the last,</l><l n="430"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&ldquo;</add>And bear thy memory with me to the grave.&rdquo;</l></lg><lg n="13" type="verseparagraph"><l n="431"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&sol;:</add> The Shepherd ended here<del rend="ink" resp="ww">;</del> and Luke stoop&rsquo;d down,</l><l n="432">And as his Father had requested, laid</l><l n="433">The first stone of the Sheep-fold; at the sight</l><l n="434">The Old Man&rsquo;s grief broke from him, to his heart</l><l n="435">He press&rsquo;d his Son, he kissed him and wept;</l><l n="436">And to the House together they return&rsquo;d.</l></lg><lg n="437" type="verseparagraph"><l n="437">Next morning, as had been resolv&rsquo;d, the Boy</l><l n="438">Began his journey, and when he had reach&rsquo;d</l><l n="439">The public Way, he put on a bold face;</l><l n="440">And all the Neighbours as he pass&rsquo;d their doors</l><l n="441">Came forth, with wishes and with farewell pray&rsquo;rs,</l><l n="442">That follow&rsquo;d him &rsquo;till he was out of sight.</l></lg><pb><milestone n="223" unit="page"><lb><lb><lg n="15" type="verseparagraph"><l n="443">A good report did from their Kinsman come,</l><l n="444"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">:</add> Of Luke and his well-doing<del rend="ink" resp="ww">;</del> and the Boy</l><l n="445">Wrote loving letters, full of wond&rsquo;rous news,</l><l n="446">Which, as the House-wife phrased it, were throughout</l><l n="447">The prettiest letters that were ever seen.</l><l n="448">Both parents read them with rejoicing hearts.</l><l n="449">So, many months pass&rsquo;d on: and once again</l><l n="450">The Shepherd went about his daily work</l><l n="451">With confident and cheerful thoughts<del rend="ink" resp="ww">;</del> and now <add place="rmargin" resp="ww">;&sol;</add></l><l n="452">Sometimes when he could find a leisure hour</l><l n="453">He to that valley took his way, and there</l><l n="454">Wrought at the Sheep-fold.  Meantime Luke began</l><l n="455"><add place="lmargin" resp="ww">&sol;;</add> To slacken in his duty<del rend="ink" resp="ww">,</del> and at length</l><l n="456">He in the dissolute city gave himself</l><l n="457">To evil courses: ignominy and shame</l><l n="458">Fell on him, so that he was driven at last</l><l n="459">To seek a hiding-place beyond the seas.</l></lg><pb><milestone n="224" unit="page"><lb><lb><lg n="16" part="I" type="verseparagraph"><l n="460">There is a comfort in the strength of love;</l><l n="461">&rsquo;Twill make a thing endurable, which else</l><l n="462">Would break the heart:&mdash;Old Michael found it so.</l><l n="463">I have convers&rsquo;d with more than one who well</l><l n="464">Remember the Old Man, and what he was</l><l n="465">Years after he had heard this heavy news.</l><l n="466">His bodily frame had been from youth to age</l><l n="467">Of an unusual strength. Among the rocks</l><l n="468">He went, and still look&rsquo;d up upon the sun,</l><l n="469">And listen&rsquo;d to the wind; and as before</l><l n="470">Perform&rsquo;d all kinds of labour for his Sheep,</l><l n="471">And for the land his small inheritance.</l><l n="472">And to that hollow Dell from time to time</l><l n="473">Did he repair, to build the Fold of which</l><l n="474">His flock had need. &rsquo;Tis not forgotten yet</l><l n="475">The pity which was then in every heart</l><l n="476">For the Old Man&mdash;and &rsquo;tis believ&rsquo;d by all</l><l n="477">That many and many a day he thither went,</l><l n="478">And never lifted up a single stone.</l></lg></body></text></group></text></TEI.2>